<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cattle Farmers Buy Cave System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RONCEVERTE, W.Va. (AP) -- Jane Morgan bends at the knees and  
waist, shuffling through a dark passageway about 4 feet high. 
Suddenly, she stands and shines her flashlight into a depression in 
the rock ceiling. 
</P>
<P>
	It's about 15 feet long, humped in the middle, slightly rounded.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is where Thomas Jefferson found the three-toed sloth.  
There's the head and there's the tail,'' she announces, pointing to 
smaller impressions at either end. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1791, she says, Jefferson found the prehistoric skeleton here  
in Organ Cave and had its bones removed to Monticello, his Virginia 
estate. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Morgan then launches into a recitation of all the other  
creatures that have made the southern West Virginia caverns their 
home over the centuries, including two endangered species of bats 
that still dwell within. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so interesting,'' she says. ``Every time I come in here,  
I find something new.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To Mrs. Morgan and her husband, Sam, Organ Cave is a historical  
and geological treasure -- and a fledgling business. To their 
skeptical bankers, it's merely ``a hole in the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Morgans, cattle brokers used to buying and selling on  
impulse, bought the Greenbrier County cave on a whim last fall 
during an auction to settle the estate of the previous owner. They 
knew little of its history then, but enough to feel the cave should 
be locally owned. 
</P>
<P>
	The network of caves, stretching at least 40 miles, is a  
National Natural Landmark that held the encampments of Confederate 
soldiers between 1861 and 1865. The 200- by 96-foot wide ``chapel 
room'' near the main entrance housed religious services for 1,100 
men, many of whom worked mining saltpeter to make gunpowder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought it would be nice if someone in the community bought  
the cave and people got involved and took pride in it,'' Morgan 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	The Morgans went to the auction as observers, but left as new  
owners of the cave with a winning bid of $253,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're in the cattle business for 30 years, you've got to  
gamble,'' Morgan says. ``You buy and sell on impulse. That's what 
we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Morgans had been inside the cave only once before buying it.  
After the auction, they walked the property lines, imagining the 
possibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	As cattle farmers, they saw the perfect above-ground spot for a  
rodeo. Their 29-year-old son, Troy, a bull rider in Gastonia, N.C., 
helped stage the first one last fall. It drew 1,300 people. A dozen 
more were scheduled for the spring and summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Morgans envisioned a log-cabin snack bar and gift shop,  
along with new walkways, guardrails and lights in the cave. They 
would hire guides to lead 90-minute tours for $10 per person and 
four- to six-hour ``wild cave'' adventures for $80 per person. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything just came to us,'' Mrs. Morgan says.  
</P>
<P>
	But there was a problem: Money.  
</P>
<P>
	The couple had borrowed against their business and needed a  
loan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The banks were skeptical, to say the least,'' Mrs. Morgan  
says. ``All manner of people were making fun of us. ... They'd say, 
'Why do you want that hole in the ground?' That's all they thought 
it was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were obstacles to credibility. The former owners kept no  
record of the number of visitors, so the Morgans were hard pressed 
to project a profit margin. They developed a business plan based on 
successful caves in Pennsylvania and Virginia, and sent more than 
20 copies to every branch of state government that might help. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenbrier National Bank provided a small loan after its board  
was assured that other investors would buy the cave if the Morgans 
defaulted. 
</P>
<P>
	``A bank official told us, 'If it works, you'll look like  
geniuses. If it doesn't: I told you so,''' Mrs. Morgan says. 
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia has at least 1,379 caves rivaling those anywhere  
in the world, according to the ``Karst Hydrology Atlas of West 
Virginia.'' Author Bill Jones, a consultant who teaches hydrology 
at American University in Washington, D.C., says at least 26 were 
mined for saltpeter. 
</P>
<P>
	Organ Cave contains 37 saltpeter vats from the Civil War and  
five from the War of 1812, all preserved in a state of suspended 
operation. The saltpeter work stopped abruptly when Union troops 
discovered the cave and captured the rebel soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	The cave itself was formed by the Mississippean Sea about 500  
million years ago. Fossilized sponges and other marine creatures 
dot the limestone ceilings of its passageways. Today, the ocean is 
hundreds of miles east. 
</P>
<P>
	As they sought more money to develop their plan, the Morgans  
invited state and federal lawmakers to visit. Only Delegate Tom 
Campbell, D-Greenbrier, and Rep. Nick Rahall, D-W.Va., took the 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a total lack of support from state government,''  
Mrs. Morgan says. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the Morgans offered part of their farm as collateral  
and got another loan. They now have eight employees and more than 
$600,000 to repay over 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But the business is off the ground: From April 1 through Dec.  
31, there were 7,000 visitors. The Web site, www.organcave.com, has 
drawn hundreds of requests for brochures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our vision is to make it a family-oriented place to come. Kids  
are bored stiff around here,'' Mrs. Morgan says. ``We want local 
people to have so much pride in what we're doing here. We want them 
to say to people who are here visiting, 'You cannot go back until 
you see this.''' 
</P>
<P>
	And Mrs. Morgan has faith in the impulse that made her buy the  
cave. 
</P>
<P>
	``That doesn't mean we don't have a rough road ahead,'' she  
said, '' We do. But I'm at peace.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
