<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belmont Stakes Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The year was 1977, and the owner of Secretariat  
was having a tough time believing the scenario that was unfolding. 
</P>
<P>
	Just four years after Secretariat became the first horse in a  
quarter century to win the Triple Crown, another horse was poised 
to accomplish the same feat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, `Who were they to try and steal our thunder?''  
Penny Chenery said. ``We put a horse in the Belmont just to make 
sure Seattle Slew ran the whole way. We wanted to keep him honest. 
We weren't giving anything away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither was Seattle Slew, who added the Belmont Stakes to his  
Kentucky Derby and Preakness victories and became just the 10th 
Triple Crown champion. Chenery's Spirit Level finished sixth in an 
eight-horse field, and the owner of Meadow Stable even admitted her 
colt didn't belong in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It turned out Seattle Slew was the real thing,'' Chenery said.  
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, an expected crowd of 80,000 will find out whether  
Charismatic is the real thing when the strapping chestnut tries to 
become racing's 12th Triple Crown winner and first since Affirmed 
in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GRANDPA BELMONT:* The Belmont Stakes is the oldest of the  
Triple Crown races, predating the Preakness by six years and the 
Kentucky Derby by eight. 
</P>
<P>
	The first Belmont was run in 1867.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BY A NOSE:* Only three times has the Belmont Stakes been  
decided by a nose -- the slimmest of margins. 
</P>
<P>
	Granville beat Mr. Bones by a nose in 1936; Jaipur beat  
Admiral's Voyage by that margin in 1962; and Victory Gallop spoiled 
Real Quiet's Triple Crown quest in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest margin of victory in the Belmont?  
</P>
<P>
	Secretariat's 31-length win over Twice a Prince in 1973.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WORKOUT CITY:* Patience Game, fifth in the Preakness, had a  
strong workout at Belmont Park on Wednesday, breezing 6 furlongs in 
1:12 1-5 under exercise rider Karl Keegan. The colt worked without 
blinkers for the first time in his last three works, and trainer 
Alex Hassinger Jr., will decide by Wednesday whether it's blinkers 
on or off for the Belmont. ... Lemon Drop Kid, who has one win and 
two seconds over the Belmont track, went 6 furlongs in 1:13 2-5 
with jockey Jose Santos aboard. ``He really likes this track, a 
horse for the course,'' trainer Scotty Schulhofer, who trained 1993 
Belmont winner Colonial Affair, said. ... Adonis and Stephen Got 
Even, trainer Nick Zito's entries for the Belmont, also worked. 
Stephen Got Even, 14th in the Derby and fourth in the Preakness, 
went a half-mile in 47 2-5; Adonis, 17th in the Derby and sixth in 
the Preakness, covered the same distance in 47 3-5. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *IN THE WORKS:* Charismatic and the filly Silverbulletday, are  
scheduled for their final major tuneups on Tuesday at Churchill 
Downs before shipping to New York on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, runner-up to Charismatic in the Derby and Preakness, is  
set for his final workout Tuesday at Belmont Park. Trainer Elliott 
Walden returns to New York to oversee the work. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Charismatic galloped 2 miles for trainer D. Wayne  
Lukas, while Silverbulletday galloped 1 1/2 miles for trainer Bob 
Baffert. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's crunch time, Lukas said. ``I have no peace of mind at  
all. But this is what we strive for.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LARGE FIELDS:* The largest Belmont Stakes field was 15 in 1983,  
when Caveat defeated Slew O' Gold by 3 1/2 lengths. The second largest 
was 14 in 1875 when Calvin beat Aristides; and matched in 1996, 
when Editor's Note was the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	A field of 13 is shaping up for Saturday's Belmont.  
  	   	
</P>
