<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maple Leafs on Brink Against Sabres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Toronto Maple Leafs will find out tonight if  
home ice is an advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Trailing the Buffalo Sabres 3-1 in the Eastern Conference  
finals, the Maple Leafs hope the Air Canada Centre will provide the 
impetus they need to rebound for the third straight series. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're playing good at home,'' Toronto captain Mats Sundin  
said. ``It's going to be a different story. We're going to do 
everything we can. If we win at home, we're back in the series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they don't, they're out. And the way they played on the road  
in Buffalo has left the Maple Leafs with scant room for error. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday night at the Marine Midland Arena, where the Sabres  
have yet to lose in seven playoff games, the Maple Leafs played one 
of their worst games of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Holzinger, Rob Ray, and Geoff Sanderson scored for Buffalo  
less than three minutes apart early in the second period as the 
Toronto defense collapsed in front of goaltender Curtis Joseph. The 
flurry transformed a 1-0 game into a 5-2 rout. 
</P>
<P>
	It was virtually a carbon copy of the previous game, only more  
lopsided. In Game 3 on Thursday night, the Sabres scored three 
goals in less than five minutes -- again in the second period -- and 
won 4-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrages like those are rare in the Stanley Cup playoffs, let  
alone at this juncture. The Sabres even scored a short-handed goal 
in each game. The Maple Leafs, who rallied from 2-1 deficits to win 
their first two playoff series, had not allowed a short-handed goal 
during the regular season and the preceding 14 playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's face it. We didn't respond hardly at all,'' Toronto  
coach Pat Quinn said. ``It did happen very fast. I didn't expect 
we'd come back and win necessarily. But I didn't expect we'd have 
that kind of short response. We kind of disintegrated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Maple Leafs had 59 shots at Buffalo goalie Dominik  
Hasek in the two games, he was rarely tested. The Sabres were 
intent on protecting the Dominator, who missed the first two games 
of the series with a groin injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``They beat us to every loose puck. They initiated every hit,''  
said Sundin, who scored both Toronto goals Saturday night, the 
first on his second penalty shot of the playoffs. ``Every play for 
the first two periods, it looked like our heads were somewhere 
else, like we were too tense to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto can't afford any more of that kind of uninspired play if  
it hopes to advance to the finals for the first time since 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres, though, are intent on finishing the series tonight.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is always the toughest game to win,'' said Buffalo  
defenseman Jason Woolley, who is tied with center Michael Peca for 
the team scoring lead with 12 points. ``They're going to throw 
everything but the kitchen sink at us. We'll have to get the good 
goaltending we've been used to getting. Dominik is getting 
stronger, and that's a good sign for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres checked the Maple Leafs doggedly in both games in  
Buffalo, outshooting the highest scoring team in the NHL during the 
regular season by a combined 20-9 in the first period. That 
strategy, as much to protect Hasek as to thwart the high-powered 
Maple Leafs attack, is not likely to change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to come out and try to take it to them instead of  
weathering the storm as you tend to do as the visiting team,'' 
Woolley said. ``You don't want to give them a sign of life, or you 
don't know what will happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Hasek:  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very nice feeling to be close. We're happy again, but  
not excited. We know it's a very long way to go. We also know the 
Toronto Maple Leafs will come much harder in their own building, 
and we have to be ready.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
