<HEADLINE> Griffey Leads All-Star Balloting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Outfielder Ken Griffey Jr., of the Seattle  
Mariners, leads American League players in early balloting for the 
70th All-Star Game. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, an All-Star starter every year since 1990, has 218,134  
votes in balloting announced Monday. That is almost 66,000 more 
than the second-best total of 152,813 for Texas catcher Ivan 
Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey was the AL's leading vote-getter in 1991 and 1993 and  
led all players in 1994, 1996, 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Other AL leaders Monday were designated hitter Jose Canseco of  
Tampa Bay (105,063); shortstop Derek Jeter of the New York Yankees 
(93,927); third baseman Cal Ripken, Jr. of Baltimore (85,545); and 
four Cleveland teammates -- second baseman Roberto Alomar (145,073), 
first baseman Jim Thome (64,350), and outfielders Manny Ramirez 
(84,925) and Kenny Lofton (77,395). 
</P>
<P>
	Early National League results will be announced Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	The 70th All-Star Game between the American and National Leagues  
will be played Tuesday, July 13 in Boston. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
