<DOCNO> APW19990531.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 23:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Horses Don't Win Triple Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's not always fun to play the spoiler.  
</P>
<P>
	Just ask Chris McCarron.  
</P>
<P>
	``I got hate mail,'' said the Hall of Fame jockey, who in 1997  
rode Touch Gold to a three-quarters-of-a-length victory over Silver 
Charm in the Belmont Stakes and spoiled that horse's chance of 
becoming the first Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't consciously assume the role of trying to be a  
spoiler. My job was to get the best out of my mount. I was painted 
as a spoiler after the fact. I felt like I was just doing my job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five horses have won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness,  
with 11 going on to racing immortality. Fourteen joined the 
bittersweet list of near misses by failing to win the final leg of 
the series, the 1 1/2-mile Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no asterisk next to the winners in the charts of those  
14 Belmonts, noting a Triple Crown bid was foiled in the process. 
And there won't be one Saturday should any one of about a dozen 
challengers upend Charismatic as he tries to become the first 
Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	But should the winner be anyone other than Charismatic, the  
mantle of spoiler will fall across his shoulders as surely as the 
blanket of white carnations. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarron, who nearly guided Alysheba to the Triple Crown in  
1987, but was fourth behind Bet Twice in the Belmont, moved Touch 
Gold ahead of Silver Charm in the final 50 yards for the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	```How dare you? Racing hasn't had a Triple Crown winner in  
20-some years. How could you do this?''' said McCarron, recalling 
some of the mail he received after the '97 Belmont. ``I was a 
little surprised to have received some letters, but I wasn't 
surprised with how impassioned they were.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like McCarron, those who have been involved in the end of a  
Triple Crown run don't think of themselves as spoilers -- they're 
just trying to win one of the most prestigious and richest horse 
races in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years before Secretariat's magical run through the classics  
in 1973, another hugely popular horse, Canonero II, was poised for 
a shot at the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter Blum, now a racing steward in Florida, was aboard 35-1  
shot Pass Catcher when he upended the Triple Crown bid of the pride 
of Venezuela before a record crowd of 82,694 at Belmont Park. Just 
a week earlier, Pass Catcher had run a strong second to Bold 
Reasoning in the Jersey Derby, and Blum knew his horse was ready 
for an upset. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone was looking for a Triple Crown but me,'' Blum said.  
``I think all of Venezuela turned out at Belmont that day, waving 
flags and cheering for Canonero. It was a great scene. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't ever remember being called a spoiler, but if that's  
what they want to call me now, fine. My job was to go out there and 
win the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's 131st running of the Belmont, Charismatic becomes  
the 26th horse with a chance to win the Triple Crown. Since 
Affirmed's '78 Triple Crown, the year after Seattle Slew won it, 
six horses have won the Derby and Preakness, but flopped in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	The past three times, the horse bidding for the Triple Crown  
finished second. In 1989, Sunday Silence was 8 lengths behind rival 
Easy Goer; and the last two Belmonts saw Bob Baffert-trained colts 
fall just short of racing immortality -- Silver Charm's loss to 
Touch Gold and Real Quiet's nose loss to Victory Gallop in '98. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Hall of Fame trainer D. Wayne Lukas saddles  
Charismatic knowing spoilers are lurking everywhere, from the star 
filly Silverbulletday in Baffert's barn, to Derby and Preakness 
runner-up Menifee to the Allen Jerkens-trained Best of Luck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure Wayne does not like the fact that I'm going to run  
her, but if it was me going for the Triple Crown, you'd see five 
Lukas horses in there,'' Baffert said. ``As a trainer last year, I 
was hoping everybody would stay home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert finds himself in a unique situation for this Belmont.  
Bob and Beverly Lewis own Silver Charm and Charismatic, and there 
was talk the trainer might keep Silverbulletday out of the Belmont 
to give the Lewises a better shot at winning the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wouldn't do anything like that. We just want to win the  
Belmont, it's not about spoiling,'' Baffert said, the ``we'' 
including Silverbulletday's owner Mike Pegram. ``I've told Bob 
Lewis we're not trying to spoil your deal. The Triple Crown is made 
so if you are the best you shouldn't worry about anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Bob Lewis welcomes all challengers.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're delighted to see a full field because, if we win, then  
there will be no one on Sunday morning saying we didn't beat much 
of a field,'' said Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Several jockeys have been involved on both sides of the Triple  
Crown chase, notably McCarron and Gary Stevens. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens was aboard Silver Charm for the '97 classics, and he  
came back last year and rode Victory Gallop to the Belmont win over 
Real Quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Day, who will be aboard Menifee in Saturday's Belmont, gets  
his second chance to play spoiler -- he was aboard Easy Goer in the 
'89 Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea of stopping a Triple Crown was not forefront in my  
mind,'' said Day, even though Easy Goer was second to Sunday 
Silence in the Derby and Preakness, just like Menifee has been to 
Charismatic this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wanted to win the race because I contended all along  
that Easy Goer was the better horse. He was sent over in good form, 
and we got the victory very handily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What about Saturday?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure (trainer) Elliott Walden will get Menifee up to the  
race and give him an opportunity,'' Day said, ``and Lord willing, 
we'll upset the apple cart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Day knows a Triple Crown winner would be a gigantic boost to a  
troubled industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're crying out for one,'' he said, ``but given the  
opportunity to run by him, I want to win the Belmont.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Hancock, a co-owner of Menifee, gets his chance to turn  
the Triple Crown tables 10 years after his Sunday Silence lost to 
Easy Goer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to spoil anybody's Triple Crown because I know how low  
it makes you feel, or at least it did me,'' Hancock said. ``But 
I've always thought things kind of go full circle. Pat Day was on 
Easy Goer and beat us. Kind of ironic he's on this horse.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 13:50:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weary Stewart Running on Empty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tony Stewart was sprawled on the couch in  
his trailer, still woozy and lightheaded, every part of his body 
aching. 
</P>
<P>
	Covering nearly 1,100 miles isn't easy any way it's done. Do it  
in about 10 hours, in two different cars, in two different states 
and with a jet ride and a couple of helicopter hops thrown in, and 
it's downright brutal. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's not even mentioning the queasy stomach during his  
hard-driving, high-flying and fast-moving adventure. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eventful. Definitely eventful,'' Stewart said late Sunday  
after becoming the first driver to complete the Indianapolis 500 
and the Coca-Cola 600 in one day. ``I'm ready to lay my head down 
for the night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But after a good night's sleep, he was off again. There was one  
last trip to Indianapolis, this one for the driver awards ceremony 
Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's fine,'' said Judy Dominick, his spokeswoman. ``A little  
worn out, but fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart wrapped up his double quest in spectacular fashion  
Sunday night, charging from last to fourth in the Coca-Cola after 
finishing ninth at Indy. The finish moved him to fifth in the 
Winston Cup point standings. 
</P>
<P>
	But the long day took its toll.  
</P>
<P>
	Aside from two small bagels for breakfast and a couple of Power  
Bars, he didn't eat all day and was sick for the last 100 laps. As 
he climbed out of his Pontiac in front of a crowd of friends and 
media, his legs gave out. He sat next to his car for several 
minutes looking dazed before he was put on a stretcher and taken to 
the track hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	He refused intravenous fluids, so doctors gave him water and  
Gatorade and cooled him down with ice packs. He was released after 
about 15 minutes and went back to his trailer to recuperate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt good when I got out of the car at Indy. Physically, I  
didn't feel real bad,'' he said. ``About lap 80, I was starting to 
feel sick because I was getting hot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His crew packed a few ice packs around him, and Stewart said he  
felt better. But with about 100 laps to go, he was barely hanging 
on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never use the headrest in cars and I used the headrest the  
last 60-70 laps,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two drivers had tried the double before Stewart, who drove  
in the Indy Racing League for three years before switching to 
NASCAR's Winston Cup Circuit this season. Now he knows why. 
</P>
<P>
	After gripping a steering wheel for three hours and trying to  
tame a car with handling problems at Indy, Stewart was whisked away 
on a golf cart to a helicopter waiting in the infield near turn 
three. 
</P>
<P>
	He was flown to the Indianapolis airport where his sponsor, The  
Home Depot, had its private jet waiting for the 65-minute flight to 
North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart changed into his NASCAR driving suit and caught a quick  
nap on the flight, stretching out on the couch in the back of the 
jet after guzzling water and Powerade to rehydrate. Then it was 
into another helicopter for a quick flight to Lowe's Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	All that, and he still had another 600 miles to go.  
</P>
<P>
	``As much fun as I had today, it wasn't fair to (his NASCAR  
team) to give them 90 percent for the last few laps,'' he said. 
``As much as I'd like to go back to Indy, I'm going to stick it out 
with these guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't mean he regrets his quest for the double, however.  
When he heard the strains of ``Taps'' play at Indy, Stewart got 
chills. And when he arrived at the Coca-Cola, some 150,000 fans 
stood and gave a deafening cheer as the helicopter flew low around 
the speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been an experience I'll never forget,'' he said. ``To  
come in here and see the reaction from the crowd and to hear the 
applause at the drivers' introductions at the 500, I wouldn't trade 
it for anything.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
