<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Astronauts in Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) -- Though it was nippy and noisy,  
space shuttle Discovery astronauts were overjoyed when they swung 
open the hatches to the international space station. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuttle commander Kent Rominger likened the visit to checking in  
to a ``fantastic hotel,'' with one major exception: ``Right now 
there's not a space toilet on board, so that makes living here 
permanently kind of tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Astronaut Tamara Jernigan and Russian crewmate Valery Tokarev  
led the way inside the unfinished station Sunday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely delighted to be aboard,'' Jernigan said as  
she and Tokarev floated aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Make yourself at home,'' Mission Control told the seven-member  
crew. 
</P>
<P>
	But their welcome quickly gave way to work early today.  
</P>
<P>
	Inside the Russian-built Zarya control module, Tokarev and  
Canadian astronaut Julie Payette pulled up the floor and began 
swapping out electrical meters on batteries that aren't charging 
properly. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Rick Husband and Daniel Barry replaced two  
electronics boxes for a communication system inside the American 
Unity chamber, where it was a brisk 57 degrees. The system, which 
allows ground controllers to transmit and receive commands from the 
station, had been on the blink since mid-April but fired up quickly 
once the repairs were made. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your hard work has paid off!'' Mission Control radioed up.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well that's super news,'' Husband replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Rominger, Barry and Jernigan took a brief break from their work  
to participate in the first news conference of the mission. 
Rominger, a Navy commander who was deployed to the Persian Gulf 
during Operation Desert Storm, used the opportunity to pass along a 
Memorial Day message. 
</P>
<P>
	``My heartfelt appreciation goes out to all the veterans, and we  
wish them all the best today,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the crew installed insulation around some fans inside  
Zarya to reduce the noise level, which Barry said measured up to 67 
decibels. Station officials hoped the mufflers would reduce the 
noise level to about 60 decibels -- equivalent to an office 
environment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a little bit noisy in there,'' Barry said. ``I think the  
mufflers helped a bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Aeronautics and Space Administration downplayed the  
multitude of problems coming so soon after the space station's 
launch. 
</P>
<P>
	``In high-tech like this, you're going to have that happen,''  
Mission Control's Milt Heflin explained. 
</P>
<P>
	The astronauts also began lugging supplies from the shuttle into  
the station. They have until Thursday to unload 3,600 pounds of 
spare parts, computers, water and clothes for the first permanent 
residents, due to arrive next March. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night, Jernigan and Barry attached another 700 pounds  
of gear to the outside of the station during an eight-hour 
spacewalk. The load included three tool bags and a pair of cranes. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though they spent eight hours outside the seven-story-plus  
complex -- 1 1/2 hours longer than planned -- the excursion ended too 
soon for their taste. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't be telling me we're almost done?'' Barry asked when  
it came time to go back in Sunday morning. His next word summed it 
all up: ``Wow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jernigan said it was an experience she would never forget.  
</P>
<P>
	``Being up high, seeing the space shuttle from a distance and  
the Earth in the background, was just spectacular,'' she said. ``I 
will carry that image with me for the rest of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their spacewalk was just 34 minutes shy of NASA's all-time  
record, an 8 1/2-hour walk back in 1992 in which three astronauts 
grabbed a runaway satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the fourth spacewalk on the space station since the first  
component, Zarya, was launched late last year. Astronauts have 
spent 29 hours working on the station's exterior, mostly back in 
December when the Unity module arrived and spacewalkers wired it to 
Zarya. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA estimates 158 more spacewalks, totaling more than 1,000  
hours, will be needed over the next five years to build and 
maintain the station. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
