<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kosovo Prisoners Tell of Beatings  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Ethnic Albanian men released from two prisons in  
Kosovo are reporting a pattern of savage beatings and abuse behind 
bars, the U.N. refugee agency said today. About 157 men who had 
been held at the Smrekovnica prison, northwest of Kosovo's capital, 
Pristina, arrived in Albania yesterday, following hundreds of 
others over the preceding days, said Kris Janowski, spokesman for 
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. Another 51 men who had 
been held at a jail in Lipljan, 12 miles south of Pristina, arrived 
in Macedonia. Almost all the men released from the prisons have 
been heavily traumatized, with injuries resulting from daily 
beatings. 

</P>
<P>
	More Casualties Reported in NATO Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO pursued its heavy bombing  
campaign today, killing 11 civilians in strikes that hit a 
sanitarium and neighboring retirement home in Surdulica, southeast 
of Belgrade, the state-run Tanjug news agency said. NATO denied the 
report, which could not be independently confirmed. NATO spokesman 
Jamie Shea said allied aircraft had attacked an ammunition depot 
and barracks late yesterday in Surdulica, but he denied the 
alliance had struck the sanitarium or retirement home. The Tanjug 
report today followed reports that 11 other civilians were killed 
yesterday when NATO missiles sent a bridge in central Serbia 
crashing into a river in another town as shoppers were heading for 
market. 

</P>
<P>
	Shuttle Astronauts in Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) -- Space Shuttle Discovery Commander  
Kent Rominger, a Gulf War veteran, delivered a Memorial Day message 
from the new international space station today. Rominger and fellow 
crewmen Daniel Barry and Tamara Jernigan took a brief break from 
their work to participate in the first news conference of the 
mission. 

</P>
<P>
	Remains May Belong to Rock Musician  
</P>
<P>
	MALIBU, Calif. (AP) -- Human remains found inside the wreckage of  
a minivan that plunged down a 200-foot ravine may be those of a 
rock musician missing since 1995, police said. The 1993 Ford 
Aerostar matches the description of a van driven by onetime Iron 
Butterfly bass player Philip ``Taylor'' Kramer. He was believed to 
be driving his van when he disappeared Feb. 12, 1995. The van was 
found by a hiker. The remains were being examined by coroner's 
investigators yesterday, authorities said. No identity has been 
released. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Fills Cabinet Seats  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin and his prime minister  
filled several key seats today in Russia's new Cabinet after days 
of political infighting. Yeltsin named Viktor Khristenko to be 
first deputy prime minister and made Ilya Klebanov a deputy prime 
minister. Khristenko, a former deputy finance minister, is expected 
to have broad economic responsibilities. Klebanov is a relative 
unknown who has served as a regional political leader. Mikhail 
Zadornov, who quit last week as first deputy prime minister after 
only a few days on the job, was named Russia's liaison with the 
International Monetary Fund and other foreign lenders. Yeltsin 
dismissed the previous government earlier this month. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin To Meet Chechnya's Leader  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Despite an increase in tension between Russia and  
Chechnya, President Boris Yeltsin said today that he still plans to 
meet with the leader of the breakaway region. Yeltsin said meeting 
with Aslan Maskhadov would produce ``serious conclusions'' about 
the future relations between the federal government and Chechnya, 
according to Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin, who met with Yeltsin 
today. No date for the meeting with Maskhadov has been announced. 

</P>
<P>
	Swiss Hemp Grower Sent to Jail  
</P>
<P>
	MARTIGNY, Switzerland (AP) -- A Swiss court sentenced a hemp  
grower today to 16 months in prison for producing tons of the dried 
plant and selling it stuffed in cushions. Bernard Rappaz, who was 
found guilty of offenses under federal narcotics law, was also 
ordered to pay about $20,000 in fines and court costs. Hemp and 
marijuana are both derived from the cannabis plant. Rappaz was 
convicted of producing 8.5 tons of dried hemp, and selling some of 
the plants in the form of cushions, which were advertised as having 
therapeutic qualities. 

</P>
<P>
	Kuerten Advances at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Playing better than anyone on clay this season,  
Gustavo Kuerten eased into the French Open quarterfinals with a 
straight-set victory today over Bohdan Ulihrach. Kuerten beat his 
Czech opponent 6-4, 6-4, 6-2 and appears ready to contend for the 
French title he won in 1997. In the quarters, he faces either 
France's Arnaud Di Pasquale or Andrei Medvedev, the much-improved 
Ukrainian player who toppled Pete Sampras in the second round. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  
  	   	
</P>
