<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lake Poisoned After Pike Discovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE DAVIS, Calif. (AP) -- The pike are back, the state officials  
are back and Kelly Griffiths thinks, ``Uh-oh, here we go again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the aggressive northern pike were found in Lake  
Davis, the state Fish and Game Department got rid of the non-native 
predator by poisoning the mountain lake 220 miles northeast of San 
Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The pike, which authorities feared could get into California's  
river system and devastate salmon and trout, died along with almost 
everything else in the lake. 
</P>
<P>
	That October 1997 operation angered the town, inspired scores of  
legal complaints, led to a fruitless local criminal prosecution 
against the state and fed a lingering distrust of state officials. 
Just weeks ago, California agreed to a $10 million settlement to 
end the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	But the discovery last week of two mature pike, both about 3  
years old and 1 1/2-feet long in a shallow, weed-filled cove at the 
northwest edge of the lake, raised fears of a possible new 
infestation. 
</P>
<P>
	The crucial questions: Did they somehow survive the poisoning 19  
months ago or were they placed in the lake later? Have they 
spawned? 
</P>
<P>
	Through the weekend, pike-hunting Fish and Game agents with  
backpacks carrying long electrical probes, walked along the shore 
and zapped the water in the inlets and tributaries that feed the 
seven-mile-long lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to maintain a low profile, the agents intentionally  
stayed away from the main part of the lake, where anglers flocked 
during the Memorial Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, they plan to resume electroshocking from a boat  
drifting along the shallows. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're trying to is to establish whether we have a  
self-sustaining population of pike. If we do, then we're going to 
have to sit down with the community and discuss what to do,'' Fish 
and Game spokesman Patrick Foy said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Griffiths, a Portola resident who said his used furniture  
and home rental businesses depend heavily on tourism, was skeptical 
of the state's efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, he said, the community will suffer another economic  
hit if visitors stay away. His own piece of the state settlement, 
which he said he learned Thursday, was ``four and a half cents on 
the dollar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ridiculous. We've all suffered. My business went down to  
nothing. There have been pike all over the Midwest, all over the 
country, they are good game fish. Why not just go catch 'em?'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
