<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 23:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Less Baggage for Baffert at Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert is going to the  
Belmont Stakes with less baggage than the previous two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to be enjoying this Belmont,'' he said Monday at  
Churchill Downs. ``The last two years I went there under the gun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He went to the Belmont with a pair of Kentucky Derby-Preakness  
winners -- Silver Charm in 1997 and Real Quiet. Both finished second 
and failed to win the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Baffert's enjoyment has to be tempered by the fact that  
he will be trying to foil the Triple Crown bid of Charismatic, 
owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, who have about 20 horses with 
Baffert, including Silver Charm. Baffert will be trying to do stop 
Charismatic with the sensational filly Silverbulletday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only horses I get nervous with when I run them are her and  
Silver Charm because they have so many fans,'' Baffert said. ``They 
are stars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Should Silverbulletday, winner of 11 of 12 starts, win her debut  
against colts and become only the third filly and first since Tanya 
in 1905 to win the Belmont, she would be queen of the Sport of 
Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't heard anybody say I shouldn't run her in the  
Belmont,'' Baffert said, referring to criticism of giving the filly 
a chance to foil the Lewises' chance to own a Triple Crown 
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Lewis has said he welcomes the challenge by Silverbulletday,  
owned by Mike Pegram, owner of Real Quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, could become the 12th  
Triple Crown champion and first since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Both he and Silverbulletday will be flown to New York on  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday also was entered in the Derby and Preakness, but  
she was scratched when 20 horses were entered in the Derby and when 
she drew the outside No. 14 post in the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no change of heart this time, says Baffert.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're taking a shot,'' he said. ``The bottom line is there is  
only one guy I have to worry about and that's Mike Pegram, and he 
wants to run in the Belmont.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Silverbulletday did not run in the Preakness, Baffert  
said, Jerry Bailey told him if she ran in the Belmont he wanted to 
ride her. The filly's regular jockey, Gary Stevens, is now riding 
in England. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy who talked me into it is Jerry Bailey,'' Baffert said.  
``He thinks she has a great chance, that she has the right style 
and you can do anything you want with her. One thing about Bailey 
is if she can't handle it, he won't use her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lot of racing people think Silverbulletday is the best  
3-year-old in training, and she should be one of the three top 
betting choices with Charismatic and Menifee, second in both the 
Derby and Preakness, in what shapes up as a 12-horse field for the 
1 1/2-mile classic. Entries will be taken and post-position drawn on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert and Pegram said they are not worried about the size of  
the field or Silverbulletday's post position because of the 
distance of the race and size of the Belmont Park oval -- 1 1/2 miles 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Belmont is a different race,'' Baffert said. ``You have  
time to get into position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other Belmont probables are Adonis, 17th in the Derby and fifth  
in the Preakness; Stephen Got Even, 14th in the Derby and fourth in 
the Preakness; Lemon Drop Kid, ninth in the Derby; Patience Game, 
fifth in the Preakness; and five horses who will be making their 
debuts in Triple Crown competition -- Best of Luck, winner of the 
Peter Pan; Vision and Verse, Illinois Derby winner; Prime 
Directive, Illinois Derby runnerup; Pineaff, third in the Illinois 
Derby; and Teletable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
