<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coles To Appear Before IOC Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Embattled Australian IOC member  
Phil Coles will appear before a special inquiry panel Thursday to 
provide ``personal explanations'' for conduct that could lead to 
his expulsion. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-member panel advised the IOC executive board Monday  
that it had drafted a list of questions for Coles to answer before 
it makes its final recommendation in mid-June. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have decided what we shall ask Mr. Coles on Thursday  
morning,'' panel member Marc Hodler said. ``We need his personal 
explanations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has already received a severe warning from the IOC for  
accepting lavish travel and other benefits from Salt Lake bidders, 
and is now under investigation for further allegations of abusing 
his Olympic positions. 
</P>
<P>
	His ex-wife has told the IOC that the couple received jewelry  
valued at $6,000 from a businessman associated with the Athens bid 
for the 1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles also has been accused of compiling secret dossiers on IOC  
members for Sydney's successful 2000 bid. Those files were also 
passed on to Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has denied any wrongdoing.  
</P>
<P>
	Hodler said the panel would report its findings to the executive  
board at its next meeting June 16 in Seoul, South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel could recommend that the case be dropped or that Coles  
be expelled. Any expulsion would have to go to the full IOC 
assembly for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to solve this problem as soon as possible, not only  
for us, but also for him and for Australia,'' IOC president Juan 
Antonio Samaranch told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian executive board member Kevan Gosper left the room  
Monday when Coles' case was discussed. 
</P>
<P>
	``My reasons are very simple,'' he said. ``I'm too close to Phil  
Coles as an IOC member in Australia to risk any perceptions of 
conflict of interest,'' he said. ``I have previously said I 
wouldn't participate in any vote on Phil Coles. Now I'm absenting 
myself from all matters.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
