<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 22:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temps May Not Stay Temps for Long </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Temporary workers are increasingly demanding employee benefits  
if they work as long and hard as permanent workers, compelling wary 
businesses to take steps so temps don't become de facto employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Take MindSpring Enterprises, a fast-growing Internet provider  
based in Atlanta that increasingly relies on a temp agency to 
supply a stream of workers for its call-in centers. But the company 
is careful to offer them staff jobs -- or replace them after 90 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	A closely watched court battle between Microsoft Corp. and its  
longtime temps -- dubbed ``permatemps'' -- is the most visible sign 
of this growing workplace issue. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. appeals court panel ruled in mid-May that thousands of  
former temps should have been allowed to join the company's 
lucrative stock-purchase program. Microsoft has asked the full 
appeals court to review the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling was the first to hold that temps can look to both  
their agency and their work-site employer for benefits. It raises 
the specter that employers will be liable for everything from 
temps' benefits to their grievances. 
</P>
<P>
	``(It) is another reminder ... that they just can't change the  
label or badge and turn them into a non-employee,'' said Catherine 
Ruckelshaus, litigation director at the National Employment Law 
Project, an advocacy group for low-wage workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1982, the percentage of temps has quadrupled to 2.2  
percent of all workers, according to forthcoming data from the 
Economic Policy Institute, a Washington, D.C.-based think tank. On 
any given day, about 1.3 million temps are at work, spawning an 
estimated $60 billion industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 90 percent of U.S. companies use temps, often because they  
provide a flexible, quick and cheap source of labor. 
</P>
<P>
	Temps, who are mostly women, are clustered in low-paying work,  
such as secretarial jobs, and most would prefer a permanent job. 
Few get health insurance or other benefits from their agencies, 
according to EPI studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft temps have filed a number of lawsuits against the  
company. Along with the suit seeking stock-purchase rights, the 
temps are suing for health insurance and pension benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft spokesman Dan Leach said temp agency employees should  
look to their agencies for wages and benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear that Microsoft employees work for Microsoft  
and employees of temp agencies work for temp agencies,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But many employers aren't so sure that the lines of  
responsibility are clear anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	Some courts have defined a ``common-law employee'' as a worker  
who's spent more than five months at a company, substantially under 
the employers' control. 
</P>
<P>
	``We get calls regularly on this issue, asking `How do we make  
this determination?''' said Michael Bartlett, manager of labor law 
policy at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``There are serious 
liability concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, companies are tightening contracts to more clearly  
exclude temps from benefit plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Some have established internal ``temp agencies'' that assign  
roving permanent workers to different projects. Others have leased 
some of their operations to outside firms rather than bringing in 
temps. 
</P>
<P>
	MindSpring, the Internet provider, reluctantly began using temps  
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was so antithetical to our philosophy of how a good company  
operates,'' said vice president Carter Calle, explaining that 
MindSpring wants to rely on permanent employees who have a stake in 
the company due to stock options and other benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Now MindSpring uses a staffing agency to recruit, screen and  
hire temps, then -- to prevent ``permatemping'' -- makes sure they're 
either hired or let go after 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Temp agencies, as well, should do more for their workers,  
advocacy groups say. A coalition of such groups, including the 
national working women's group 9 to 5, will unveil a national code 
of conduct for temp agencies in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to raise the bar, and improve practices through  
voluntary action,'' said Ellen Bravo, co-director of 9 to 5. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Jersey, the coalition is helping a community group  
monitor the industry, with plans to publicize model temp agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a strategy applauded by Kamal Larsuel, a 29-year-old  
engineer who's been working as a Microsoft temp for 16 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft needs to put their foot down and say, `If you want  
to be a preferred agency with Microsoft, you need to provide us 
with better benefits,''' she said. ``That would be the smart thing 
to do.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadorean Family Mourned in Conn. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) -- Mourners filed into a Mormon church today  
for the funeral of a woman and her four sons who died in a train 
accident, with the boys remembered for the way they lived, rather 
than their tragic deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never saw them sad or angry,'' said family friend Maria  
Sanchez. ``They always had a smile ... that would enlighten every 
one of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 people turned out at the Church of Jesus Christ of  
Latter-day Saints to say goodbye to Julia Toledo de Urgiles, 47, 
and Carlos, 11, Jose, 10, Angel, 6, and Pedro, 3. 
</P>
<P>
	They were struck from behind by an Amtrak train in Fairfield as  
they walked across a railroad trestle in the middle of the night 
last week. Mrs. Urgiles, Pedro, Angel and Carlos were killed 
instantly. Jose was declared brain-dead two days after the 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years after emigrating from Ecuador, Mrs. Urgiles and her  
boys had been living in a homeless shelter. The night of the 
accident, she had packed up her family and left. It was still 
unclear Monday why she left. 
</P>
<P>
	The coffin bearing Carlos' body, who was due to receive an award  
for a school anti-drug program, had a Drug and Alcohol Resistance 
Education T-shirt draped over it. 
</P>
<P>
	White sashes on three flower arrangements near the front of the  
church had the word ``Classmates'' embossed in gold lettering. A 
young friend's handmade card carried the message, ``Jose We Love 
You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among several messages written on the coffins in Spanish and  
English was this: ``I'm sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Urgiles' estranged husband, Carlos Luis Urgiles, stood  
somberly in the church, accepting condolences from the mourners. 
</P>
<P>
	Urgiles, an Ecuadorean farm laborer, came to the United States  
intending to take the bodies back to their homeland for burial. But 
after a weekend meeting with her family, he decided to bury them in 
Connecticut. He shared a front pew with his wife's family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very bad because I didn't get a chance to speak to them  
before their death,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Urgiles, who is Roman Catholic, left the United States more than  
a year ago after fighting over religious differences with his 
sister-in-law, who is Mormon. His wife, who filed for divorce after 
he left, attended both churches. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 22:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> All-Male Batch of Mice Cloned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Scientists have cloned three identical mice using ordinary cells  
rather than DNA extracted from the female reproductive system -- and 
this time, the cloned rodents were male. 
</P>
<P>
	The clones grew using genetic material extracted from tail cells  
of adult male mice, but only one grew to adulthood, according to a 
study by Hawaiian researchers in the June issue of the journal 
Nature Genetics. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers said the experiment demonstrates that cloning can be  
accomplished with the genetic material contained in the nucleus of 
somatic cells, or ordinary cells found throughout the body. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, most cloning experiments -- from mice to Dolly the  
sheep -- used DNA extracted from female reproductive cells. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the Hawaii team reported cloning more than 50  
carbon-copy female mice extending at least three generations. The 
DNA used in that experiment was derived from cumulus cells, which 
surround developing eggs in the ovaries of female mice. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists said somatic cells are more plentiful and large  
amounts of their genetic material could be frozen and stored for 
later use. 
</P>
<P>
	That would help to make cloning a more efficient procedure in  
agriculture and commercial laboratory operations. It also might 
help conservationists rescue endangered species by enabling them to 
stockpile more of the genes of rare animals for cloning. 
</P>
<P>
	Other scientists said the cloning of male mice from tail cells  
was not a remarkable achievement. For example, bulls have been 
cloned using DNA from ear samples. 
</P>
<P>
	But the problems the Hawaii team encountered with mice  
eventually could improve the cloning of a variety of animals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we've got a beautiful model for looking at these defects  
and how we might solve them,'' said geneticist James Robl of the 
University of Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mice experiment, researchers engineered 274 embryos by  
emptying eggs of their genetic material and adding the cloned DNA 
from the tail cells. 
</P>
<P>
	The embryos were implanted in female mice for development. In  
all but three cases, the resulting fetuses died. Two of the 
surviving mice died within an hour of birth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawaii researchers said the problems were the result of  
incomplete DNA communication between cells in the placenta and the 
fetus following the cloning procedure. Why that happened has not 
been determined. 
</P>
<P>
	Robl said similar problems have complicated calf cloning  
experiments. 
</P>
<P>
	Other researchers said the Hawaii research is promising because  
it suggests that ordinary cells can be used in cloning, and 
identical animals of either sex can be commercially engineered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:38:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
