<HEADLINE> Baffert's Tale of Two Horses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- The colt is called Buddynamedme. The  
filly's name is Silverbulletday. 
</P>
<P>
	They are owned by Mike Pegram and trained by Bob Baffert, and  
they are at opposite ends of racing's pecking order. 
</P>
<P>
	The colt's a ``club fighter.'' The filly's a champion.  
</P>
<P>
	Both horses galloped Monday at Churchill Downs while Pegram and  
Baffert talked about what happened on Feb. 11 at Santa Anita and 
what they hope will happen Saturday at Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	On that February day, Buddynamedme went to the post as the  
favorite in a 6 1/2-furlong race for horses with a $62,500 claiming 
price. The winner on a disqualification was Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	Both colts, neither of them claimed, ended up in Louisville,  
where Buddynamedme won an allowance race during Kentucky Derby week 
and Charismatic won the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the D. Wayne Lukas-trained Charismatic will be  
flown to New York, where he will try to become the first Triple 
Crown champion in 21 years by winning Saturday's Belmont. On the 
plane with him will a would-be spoiler -- Silverbulletday. 
</P>
<P>
	Remaining at Churchill Downs will be Buddynamedme, whose racing  
future lies in allowance and high-priced claiming races. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic and Silverbulleday both were scheduled to have their  
final serious workouts for the Belmont on Tuesday at Churchill 
Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, who has won 11 of 12 starts, all against  
fillies, also was entered in the Derby and Preakness, but was 
scratched when 20 horses were entered in the Derby and when she 
drew the outside No. 14 post in the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no change of heart this time, says Baffert.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're taking a shot,'' he said. ``The bottom line is there is  
only one guy I have to worry about and that's Mike Pegram, and he 
wants to run in the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to win the Belmont,'' added Baffert, who finished  
second with Silver Charm in 1997 and again with Real Quiet last 
year. The defeats cost both colts the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	After Silverbulletday did not run in the Preakness, Baffert  
said, Jerry Bailey told him if she ran in the Belmont he wanted to 
ride her. The filly's regular jockey, Gary Stevens, is now riding 
in England. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy who talked me into it is Jerry Bailey,'' Baffert said.  
``He thinks she has a great chance, that she has the right style 
and you can do anything you want with her. One thing about Bailey 
is if she can't handle it, he won't use her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lot of racing people think Silverbulletday is the best  
3-year-old in training, and she should be one of the three top 
betting choices with Charismatic and Menifee, second in both the 
Derby and Preakness, in what shapes up as a 12-horse field for the 
1 1/2-mile classic. Entries will be taken and post positions drawn on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert and Pegram said they are not worried about the size of  
the field or Silverbulletday's post position because of the 
distance of the race and size of the Belmont Park oval. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Belmont is a different race,'' Baffert said. ``You have  
time to get into position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Should Silverbulletday win, she would be only the third filly  
and the first since Tanya in 1905 to win the Belmont. Charismatic 
would be the 12th Triple Crown champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert was asked what he would have said if he had been told by  
someone after that claiming race Feb. 11 that Charismatic was going 
to win the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have claimed him,'' Baffert replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Other Belmont probables include Adonis, 17th in the Derby and  
fifth in the Preakness; Stephen Got Even, 14th in the Derby and 
fourth in the Preakness; Lemon Drop Kid, ninth in the Derby; and 
Patience Game, fifth in the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Five horses will be making their debuts in Triple Crown  
competition: Best of Luck, winner of the Peter Pan; Vision and 
Verse, the Illinois Derby winner; Prime Directive, the Illinois 
Derby runner-up; Pineaff, third in the Illinois Derby; and 
Teletable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
