<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Albania Border Security Deteriorates  
</P>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- Serb gunners pounded Kosovo guerrillas  
along the Albanian border today and U.S. armor-busting A-10 jets 
countered with strikes against the Serbs. NATO flew its largest 
number of sorties in the border crossing area of Morini, nearly 
hitting the Serb border checkpoint. The jets swooped in to attack 
the Serbs, who shot back with anti-aircraft fire and shoulder-fired 
missiles. With the United States refusing to deploy Apache 
helicopters, the relatively low-flying A-10s are regarded as the 
most effective warplane against tanks and entrenched positions. 
With the guerrillas mounting new operations, security along 
Albania's border with Kosovo has deteriorated sharply in recent 
days, a U.N. spokesman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Six Croats Exonerated of War Crimes  
</P>
<P>
	ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- A local court found insufficient evidence  
today to convict six former Croat soldiers of wartime atrocities 
against rebel Serbs. The trial was the first in which Croats, who 
largely view themselves as victims of Serb aggression during 
Croatia's 1991-92 war, set out to try their own for crimes 
perpetrated against minority Serbs. All six defendants had faced 
charges of extortion, abduction, attempted murder and murder in the 
deaths of at least 14 ethnic Serbs during Croatia's war with rebel 
minority Serbs. 

</P>
<P>
	Union-Car Hauler Nearing Deadline  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Negotiations between the Teamsters and  
new-car haulers today edged toward a midnight strike deadline in 
the first test for union president James P. Hoffa. A strike could 
mean longer waits for hot-selling vehicles and leave manufacturing 
plants without spaces to park vehicles coming off the assembly 
line. Faced with a threatened strike beginning at 12:01 a.m. EDT, 
talks stalled over management proposals that would establish a 
lower pay scale for newly hired drivers and permit hiring of 
part-time workers, spokesmen for both sides said. 

</P>
<P>
	Ecuadorean Family Mourned in Conn.  
</P>
<P>
	TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) -- More than 500 people remembered a woman  
and her four sons who died in a train accident for the way they 
lived, not their tragic deaths. ``I never saw them sad or angry,'' 
said family friend Maria Sanchez. ``They always had a smile ... 
that would enlighten every one of us.'' Julia Toledo de Urgiles, 
47, and Carlos, 11, Jose, 10, Angel, 6, and Pedro, 3, were struck 
by an Amtrak train in Fairfield as they walked across a railroad 
trestle early Tuesday. Jose was declared brain-dead two days later; 
the others died instantly. 

</P>
<P>
	Organ-Rejection Remedy Tested  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A temporary treatment to block organ rejection  
has remained effective for up to a year in monkeys that received 
new kidneys, researchers report. Scientists hope the treatment will 
one day free transplant patients from taking anti-rejection drugs 
for the rest of their lives. The drugs suppress the immune system 
and leave patients vulnerable to infections. The new treatment 
teaches the immune system to accept transplanted tissue rather than 
attack it. Researchers injected the monkeys with a protein to 
prevent certain blood cells from delivering a ``danger'' signal to 
other cells, an initial event in rejection. 

</P>
<P>
	Nevada Bill Would Allow Spanking  
</P>
<P>
	CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) -- The Legislature sent Gov. Kenny Guinn a  
bill that would ensure parents can spank their children and erase 
official records of such incidents if they're not deemed to be 
abuse. The Assembly voted 24-17 yesterday in favor of the bill, 
which was approved by the Senate a day earlier. Parents need to 
know they won't get locked up for disciplining their children, 
supporters of the measure said. But critics argued that a record is 
vital to identifying abusive parents. 

</P>
<P>
	Brewers Stomp Padres 8-2  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Hideo Nomo allowed three hits in 6 1-3 innings  
to lead the Milwaukee Brewers to a 8-2 victory over the San Diego 
Padres today. Nomo (2-1), released by the New York Mets and Chicago 
Cubs earlier this season, has a 2.41 ERA in five starts since being 
signed by the Brewers. After giving up two runs in a 39-pitch first 
inning, Nomo settled down. He allowed a leadoff single to Ruben 
Rivera in the second and then retired the next 15 batters. 

</P>
<P>
	Virginia Wins Lacrosse Title  
</P>
<P>
	COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Virginia won the NCAA Division I  
lacrosse final 12-10 today, surviving a fourth-quarter scoring 
binge by Syracuse that brought back memories of last year's title 
game. In 1998, Syracuse made up a six-goal deficit to beat 
Virginia. This time, the comeback by the Orangemen fell short. 
Conor Gill and Henry Oakey scored in a 21-second span to put 
Virginia up by three with 2:38 remaining, and the Cavaliers won 
their first title since 1972. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
