<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Bank Chief To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The Philippines' respected central  
bank chief, Gabriel Singson, said Monday he will step down as 
scheduled, quashing speculation that he might agree to an extension 
of his six-year term, which ends July 5. 
</P>
<P>
	President Joseph Estrada had earlier said he was willing to  
prolong Singson's term if the central bank governor would agree. 
Singson was one of the few officials appointed by former President 
Fidel Ramos retained by Estrada. 
</P>
<P>
	Singson said he considers his ``most important accomplishments''  
as central bank governor a stable price regime and a stable 
financial system that has weathered the Asian crisis largely 
unscathed. 
</P>
<P>
	His six-year term also saw a stable peso, moderate inflation,  
and the ballooning of the central bank's gross international 
reserves to a record high this month of $13.9 billion, enough to 
cover five months' of imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Singson, who is 70, said he plans to spend more time playing  
golf and with his wife and three children. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
