<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brack Takes $1.4M From Indy Purse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Kenny Brack saw Arie Luyendyk walking toward  
him. He broke into a big smile, shook his head and asked the 
question Luyendyk probably asked himself a hundred times. 
</P>
<P>
	``What the hell were you thinking of? You had that race in your  
pocket. ... I mean, you were fast,'' Brack said, laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, but it was good racing, eh?'' Luyendyk replied as the  
two drivers chatted backstage before the Indianapolis 500 Victory 
Celebration on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Brack, who went on to the checkered flag after Robby Gordon ran  
out of fuel with just over a lap to go, took home $1.47 million 
from a purse of $9.05 million, the biggest prize package in auto 
racing history. Luyendyk, who wound up 22nd, had to settle for 
$382,350, not a bad piece of change under the circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, Luyendyk seemed most likely to get the  
congratulations, not to mention the heaviest paycheck. He started 
from the pole position, led much of the early going and appeared 
almost untouchable on the track. Then, as he admitted later, he 
made a bonehead move, trying a risky pass on the inside of Tyce 
Carlson. 
</P>
<P>
	What he didn't know was Carlson's radio was out, meaning Carlson  
was not in contact with his spotter and wasn't warned of Luyendyk's 
approach. When Carlson lifted off the throttle in the turn, 
Luyendyk had to tap his brakes to avoid a collision, and that was 
enough to send his car into a slide that ended against the wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't have done it with you, I don't think,'' Brack said.  
``That's a bold move. But it was good racing, it really was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It also was the 15th and final Indy 500 for Luyendyk, a two-time  
winner who earlier announced he would retire after this race. And 
as the Flying Dutchman walked toward the stage, where drivers were 
getting ready to be introduced, he turned to the young Swede and 
said, ``I'm happy for you, man. I'm glad you won the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk still holds a lot of Indy records -- including speeds in  
practice, qualifications and the race. He also has won more money 
than any other driver at Indy -- almost $5.6 million -- and two years 
ago set a record with $1,568,150 for his second victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Brack's $1,465,190 is the second-biggest prize in the 83-year  
Indy history. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is absolutely unbelievable,'' said Brack, the 1998 Indy  
Racing League series champion whose previous high was $310,750 for 
sixth place in last year's Indy 500. ``This is the world's biggest 
race, so it should have the world's biggest purse. They're huge 
numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Ward, who finished second to Brack, earned $583,150; Billy  
Boat, Brack's teammate, took home $435,200 for third; Gordon 
received $253,270 for fourth, and Robby McGehee, who was named Indy 
500 rookie of the year, earned $247,750 for fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the best day of my life in the sense of everything I  
ever dreamed about as a child. It means everything,'' McGehee said. 
``I looked at the list earlier today of who else has been rookie of 
the year, and all of them have gone on to fabulous motor sports 
careers. If I can follow in their footsteps, that's all I ever want 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGehee's chief mechanic, Steve Fried, was critically injured in  
a pit accident early in the race. McGehee dedicated his rookie of 
the year trophy to Fried. 
</P>
<P>
	Brack, meanwhile, said his victory still hasn't sunk in.  
</P>
<P>
	``Since yesterday, I've been going flat out doing interviews and  
all kinds of things. It'll probably take a few more weeks until it 
sinks in completely, if it ever will,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brack won three races on the way to his IRL championship last  
year. Still, he remained a virtual unknown to most of this country 
-- until Sunday. And winning at Indy, as his car owner A.J. Foyt has 
always said, can make any driver famous. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can, if you keep winning as many as he did,'' Brack said of  
his boss, the first four-time Indy winner. ``For me, I'm not really 
bothered by that right now. I want to win. That's why I race. I 
want to win every race I take part in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I prepared a long time for Indy,'' he said. ``After  
we won the championship last year, I told A.J., `Next year, I want 
to win the Indy 500 for you, and if you give me the car I can do 
it.' Since then, I have prepared mentally, physically, as hard as I 
could ever prepare for a race. I've done it. It's a great relief to 
come through and make the win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
