<HEADLINE> Four Dead in Chicago Apartment Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Police suspected arson today in an apartment fire  
that killed two children, their mother and their grandmother. Two 
people were critically burned. 
</P>
<P>
	Police spokesman Pat Camden said dogs detected accelerant in the  
rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were identified as Juanita Jones, 5; Jackie Jones,  
6; Gloria Jones, 32; and Juanita Jones, 53. The Rev. Paul Jakes, 
who counseled surviving family members, said Gloria was the mother 
of the two children, and the elder Juanita Jones was her mother. 
</P>
<P>
	An unidentified man and woman were in critical condition with  
burns and smoke inhalation. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruby Ervin, a tenant in the apartment building, said she was  
asleep when she heard an explosion around 3 a.m. and then smoke 
detectors went off. She woke up her grandchildren, but when she 
opened her door there was a wall of smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I put a wet towel over my face and I just followed the sound  
of everybody else'' fleeing, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire Department spokesman Patrick Howe said there were no smoke  
detectors in the apartment where the victims were discovered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
