<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wildfires Burn in Southeast, West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	As federal and state firefighters contained a California  
wildfire that threatened delicate habitat near the Mojave Desert, 
crews in Arizona battled their own lightning-sparked blazes. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, a 40,000-acre fire charred swampland and crossed the  
state line into Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, more than 900 forestry officials and local  
firefighters at Joshua Tree National Park quelled wildfires Sunday 
that had burned more than 13,000 acres of the fragile desert 
habitat. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire began with two lightning strikes, setting off four  
fires. Two burned less than one acre, another burned about 1,900 
acres, and the biggest consumed roughly 11,200 acres. Firefighters 
struggled against high winds, snakes, scorpions and old mineshafts 
as they fought the flames. 
</P>
<P>
	Mop-up work and rehabilitation is expected to take about two  
days, including dousing spot fires and raking out any tire tracks 
left during the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've adapted our firefighting techniques to tread very  
lightly on the terrain,'' said San Bernardino County fire Capt. Jim 
Wilkins. ``We never drove off the road, we kept our aircraft out of 
(river) areas, we did almost everything by hand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In northwestern Arizona, a fire burning oily brush, junipers and  
pinion trees grew to 10,000 acres Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind gusts up to 50 mph helped spread the fire in an area  
between the Arizona-Utah border and Grand Canyon National Park 
known as the Arizona Strip, Interagency Fire Center spokeswoman 
Bette Arial said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranchers rushed their livestock along narrow dirt roads, and  
officials ordered parkgoers to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	A second wildfire about 80 miles west of Phoenix consumed 14,000  
acres by Sunday but was 25 percent contained, said Bureau of Land 
Management spokesman Wendell Peacock. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, a 40,000-acre wildfire burned through portions of  
the Okefenokee swamp and hopped the Florida-Georgia line. The fire 
raged into an area south of the small town of Fargo, Ga., about 
eight miles north of the Florida line, said Gene Madden, spokesman 
for the Florida Division of Forestry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 09:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sterilization Drug, Malaria Fighter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- A drug with a disputed safety record as a  
female sterilization agent has been used by millions of people 
around the world since its introduction in the 1920s. 
</P>
<P>
	Quinacrine hydrochloride, also called Atabrine, was administered  
orally to millions of U.S. troops and sailors in the South Pacific 
during World War II to fight malaria and other parasitic diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	When used to sterilize women, pellets of the drug are inserted  
into the uterus near the fallopian tubes. The chemical dissolves 
and burns the tubes' lining. Blockage from the resulting scar 
tissue prevents pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	The no-anesthesia method can be temporarily painful and, because  
there's no way to check how much of the tubes are blocked, women 
cannot be sure the procedure worked as planned. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug's failure rate has been variously estimated at less  
than one in 10 or one in 20. While not as surefire as surgery, 
quinacrine is effective and so cheap even some of the world's 
poorest women can afford it, supporters say. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is frighteningly good,'' said Dr. Michael Benjamin, a  
Tamarac, Fla., gynecologist eager to use the chemical to sterilize 
women in South Florida. ``There is nothing available today in the 
world of contraception that gives as big a bang for the buck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Family planning researchers also are trying to find ways to  
block the fallopian tubes with clips, gels, plugs and adhesives. 
No-scalpel vasectomies using scar-causing chemicals are also being 
tested. None is as widely used or studied as quinacrine, or as 
readily available. 
</P>
<P>
	Female surgical sterilization is the world's most common method  
of family planning. But in the world's poorest countries, where 
even basic medical care is strained, providing long-term, 
dependable sterilization to women who want it cannot be met with 
surgical methods, family planning experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Health Organization estimates about 585,000 woman die  
in childbirth annually. The WHO also estimates about 78,000 deaths 
a year are due to unsafe abortions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
