<DOCNO> APW19990531.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 03:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle Hotel Implosion Goes Awry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The demolition of a downtown hotel went as  
planned -- almost. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of buckling in as intended Sunday, the fourth-floor  
buckled out when the building imploded, sending debris flying. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured in the explosion-triggered collapse of the  
Waldorf Towers. But a movie theater was damaged, streets were 
blocked by debris, overhead power lines for electric buses were 
knocked down and at least two street lights and a traffic signal 
were wrecked. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials had no immediate estimate of the cost of the damage.  
</P>
<P>
	The Waldorf had been rigged by Engineered Demolition of Hayden,  
Idaho, to collapse within its site -- about one-sixth of a block in 
size -- following detonation of 175 explosives loaded into the 
seven-story structure. 
</P>
<P>
	But something went awry.  
</P>
<P>
	``The fourth floor buckled out,'' said Doug Hazelrigs,  
construction manager for R.C. Hedreen Co. of Seattle which oversaw 
the project. ``The fourth and sixth floors were cabled to buckle 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Engineered Demolition officials were meeting with Cineplex  
representatives Sunday and could not be contacted. No one answered 
the phone at the company's office in Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
	The implosion saved about three weeks in clearing the site for a  
five-star hotel with 550 rooms and a 990-space parking garage to 
accompany an expansion of the Washington State Trade &AMP; Convention 
Center. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wildfires Spreading in Dry Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAYLOR, Fla. (AP) -- Weary firefighters using tanker helicopters  
and planes struggled against a huge fire in the Okefenokee Swamp of 
northern Florida and southern Georgia on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot, dry weather could cause the fire to spread further.  
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like a war zone,'' said Bill Paxton, a spokesman for  
the firefighting operation. ``We've got helicopters and tanker 
planes sweeping in for runs over the fire. We've got dozens of 
bulldozers and fire engines going and coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some real close calls -- fire crews barely making it  
over burning bridges that are the only way in and out of areas. 
Then there's the snakes. Again, some close calls. No one bitten.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fire had burned 53,000 acres by Monday night. It was  
believed to have been started by lightning May 21. The swamp is 
surrounded by fire lines from previous years, and no homes were 
threatened. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, wind gusts up to 50 mph helped spread a fire over  
11,000 acres between the Arizona-Utah line and Grand Canyon 
National Park. Another lightning wildfire 80 miles west of Phoenix 
burned 14,600 acres but was contained by Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters in Nevada called in reinforcements to help battle a  
blaze that had charred 10,000 acres in rugged terrain about 85 
miles northeast of Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	In California's Joshua Tree National Park, a 13,900-acre  
wildfire was contained as crews started work on restoring the 
fragile desert habitat blackened by the blaze, which also was 
started by lightning. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 firefighters were involved in the Florida-Georgia  
fire, and volunteer crews and equipment had come in from 30 states, 
including Alaska. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
