<DOCNO> APW19990531.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 06:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Espionage Could Cost Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson says he will  
fire or demote Energy Department officials whose incompetence led 
to the Chinese obtaining secrets from nuclear weapons laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he said, Congress should concentrate on  
finding solutions rather than laying blame for the security 
breaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said Sunday he will take disciplinary action after  
receiving a report, probably this week, on security problems at the 
Los Alamos, N.M., nuclear weapons lab, a prime target of the 
alleged Chinese grab for American secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were communications breakdowns, there were incompetent  
acts, security was not considered important,'' said Richardson, who 
appeared on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' and ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't a case ``of anything nefarious,'' he added.  
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department has been criticized for being slow in  
removing the security clearance and monitoring the computers of Wen 
Ho Lee, the Los Alamos scientist fired in March under suspicion he 
passed secrets to the Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's counterintelligence chief, Edward Curran, said  
on ABC's ``This Week'' that Congress failed to follow up on FBI 
warnings in 1997 that the labs were in danger of losing secrets to 
the Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the FBI ``made some very, very significant proposals''  
on tightening security at the labs to Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., 
chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee. ``And I never heard 
anything since.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Curren said there were 26 recommendations on improving security,  
as well as a request that Congress provide $12.5 million to begin 
putting the new precautions in place. 
</P>
<P>
	The department later adopted those recommendations, but ``it  
would have been nice to have a head start,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelby, appearing later on the same show, said Curran was ``out  
of bounds in some areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that in 1996, the intelligence committee, then chaired  
by Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., did respond to counterintelligence 
problems at the labs and provided additional money. But he said the 
department ignored the committee's advice. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., another critic of the  
administration's handling of the spy case, said Curran's comments 
were ``entirely inappropriate.'' He said it was improper for an FBI 
official dealing with counterintelligence ``to engage in a game of 
blame between the Congress and the executive branch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said the focus should be on tightening security at  
the labs rather than placing blame for past mistakes. ``Let's stop 
scapegoating, looking for heads to roll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He agreed with Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., chief author of  
the report released last week detailing Chinese efforts to obtain 
U.S. nuclear secrets, that the espionage was serious. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said China stole secrets about the seven major  
warheads in the current U.S. nuclear arsenal as well as the neutron 
bomb, adding that the thefts ``almost certainly continue to the 
present.'' China has denied the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said it was certain the Chinese got information on  
three nuclear warheads, but there is no hard evidence they have 
used that information to modernize or deploy nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox agreed it's not clear what the Chinese are doing with the  
American technology. But, he said, ``diminishing the problem, 
saying it's really not that bad, is actually an obstacle to fixing 
the problem.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 16:21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ocalan Offers Rebel Cease-Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- Begging and bargaining for his  
life, Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan declared at the opening 
of his treason trial Monday that Turkey would have peace if it 
spared him the gallows -- and warned that ``hundreds of thousands 
will die'' if it did not. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking through a microphone in a bulletproof and bombproof  
cage in a converted movie theater, Ocalan directed his fighters to 
give up their armed struggle. He offered to arrange their outright 
surrender if he was allowed to contact them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The armed clashes should immediately cease and arms should  
immediately be laid down,'' Ocalan declared. 
</P>
<P>
	It was his first direct call to abandon the 15-year-old  
guerrilla campaign for Kurdish autonomy in Turkey's southeast. The 
war has claimed 37,000 victims, mostly Kurds. Ocalan called for a 
cease-fire in the struggle in December. 
</P>
<P>
	``For peace and brotherhood I am ready to serve the Turkish  
state, and I believe that for this end I must remain alive,'' 
Ocalan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What will happen if I die?'' the rebel chief asked. ``The  
organization will send out thousands of fighters, and hundreds of 
thousands of people will die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan is widely expected to be convicted and sentenced to hang.  
An overwhelming majority of Turks hold him responsible for all the 
deaths in the conflict, and there is strong support for his 
execution. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday was Ocalan's first public appearance since he was brought  
to Imrali following his February capture by Turkish commandos in 
Kenya. The stocky guerrilla leader seemed thinner, but healthy. He 
appeared calm but spoke hesitantly, gesturing frequently with his 
hands. 
</P>
<P>
	He told the court he had not been tortured or mistreated.  
</P>
<P>
	The guerrilla leader, who tolerated no dissent within his rebel  
organization, appeared conciliatory Monday, asking the families of 
the 5,000 Turkish soldiers slain in the war to forgive him for 
their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``I share the sorrow of the martyrs' relatives deep in my  
heart,'' Ocalan said, facing the families. ``I apologize.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Shameful!'' an angry mother shouted back.  
</P>
<P>
	Many of the families were draped in Turkish flags and carried  
pictures of their slain sons. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear if Ocalan issued his appeal and threat solely  
as a tactic to avoid the death penalty or if it was another step in 
his effort to transform his faltering military struggle and 
international isolation into a political battle within Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey regards any hint of Kurdish nationalism as a threat to  
the state's existence. It has ignored several cease-fires called by 
Ocalan's PKK, or Kurdistan Workers Party, and has brushed aside his 
calls to negotiate a political solution to the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey maintains 250,000 soldiers and police in the largely  
Kurdish southeast, fighting 4,500 rebels. Human rights groups say 
the military has destroyed thousands of Kurdish villages in a 
scorched-earth campaign, pushing the rebels deep into the mountains 
and northern Iraq 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey closely monitors Kurdish political and cultural  
organizations and has closed several due to suspected contacts with 
the PKK. It is illegal to broadcast or teach in Kurdish. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan said he wanted his PKK to ``give up its stance against  
the state and prepare for a legalization process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting has persisted in the southeast. Authorities said Monday  
that a new clash killed 10 rebels and one Turkish security officer. 
They did not say when that occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan is facing trial before a State Security Court.  
International human rights groups have sharply criticized the 
tribunals, saying they are biased because they include a military 
judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has proposed reforming the courts to remove the  
military judge, but the judges on Monday turned down an appeal by 
Ocalan's lawyers to postpone his trial to give the government time 
to pass a court reform bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the lawyers walked out in protest. The military judge  
could still withdraw from the case. The judge's likely replacement, 
a civilian, is already on the prison island. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurds in Europe marked the opening of the trial with demands for  
Ocalan's freedom, demonstrating in Germany, the Netherlands, Russia 
and Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	In Denmark, 2,000 people gathered chanting, ``Long live  
Ocalan!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following Ocalan's capture, Kurds led protests throughout  
Europe, storming embassies and setting themselves on fire. In 
Turkey, PKK rebels attacked repeatedly, killing more than a dozen 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities imposed strict security measures for the trial.  
Warships patrolled the coast near the island and helicopters 
hovered above Mudanya, the nearest port. 
</P>
<P>
	Journalists attending the trial were fingerprinted and had their  
retinas scanned for identification. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkish commandos wearing black ski masks guarded the coast of  
the island, where Ocalan is the only prisoner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 16:21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
