<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 05:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	More Casualties Reported in NATO Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO pursued its heavy bombing  
campaign today while pressing Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic to 
accept a Kosovo peace plan. The NATO strikes reportedly hit a 
sanitarium and a retirement home, killing civilians. The state-run 
Tanjug news agency said at least 11 people died in the hits in 
Surdulica, 155 miles southeast of Belgrade. The report could not be 
independently confirmed. 

</P>
<P>
	Trial Begins for Abdullah Ocalan  
</P>
<P>
	MUDANYA, Turkey (AP) -- Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan  
pleaded for his life and declared himself ready to cooperate with 
the Turkish state for peace and brotherhood today at the opening of 
his trial. For 15 years, Ocalan's guerrillas have battled Turkish 
soldiers in the barren mountains of southeastern Turkey, fighting 
for the Kurdish people and their right to self-determination. But 
the battle now facing the iron-fisted leader of the of the 
Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, is in the courtroom, where he sat 
behind bulletproof and bombproof glass to defend himself against 
treason charges. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Peacekeeper Killed in S. Lebanon  
</P>
<P>
	TYRE, Lebanon (AP) -- A U.N. peacekeeper was killed and another  
wounded today in a battle between Israeli forces and Lebanese 
guerrillas in south Lebanon. The two peacekeepers, both Irish 
soldiers, were hit when two mortar rounds exploded inside their 
position before dawn near Braachit village, six miles north of the 
Israeli border, said Timur Goksel, spokesman for the 4,500-member 
U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon. He said the mortar that hit the 
soldiers had been shot by Israel's proxy militia. 

</P>
<P>
	Stampede in Minsk Leaves 54 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	MINSK, Belarus (AP) -- Pouring rain sent a crowd racing out of a  
rock concert and beer festival, prompting a stampede in an 
underground passage that left 54 dead, mostly young women, 
officials said today. More than 100 people were also injured late 
yesterday and 37 were in ``grave condition,'' Health Minister Igor 
Zelenkevich said today on Belarus Radio. About 2,500 young people 
attended the festival sponsored by a local beer company to mark the 
two-year anniversary of the Mir radio station. 

</P>
<P>
	Suharto's Daughter Questioned  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The state prosecutor questioned the  
eldest daughter of Indonesia's ex-President Suharto today for eight 
hours in connection with allegations that the former first family 
has amassed a fortune abroad. The government has come under heavy 
pressure to prosecute Suharto and his family, and the new 
questioning comes as the ruling party has been slipping in the 
polls less than a week ahead of June 7 elections. Siti Hardiyanti 
Rukmana, social minister in Suharto's final Cabinet and better 
known as Tutut, said after the questioning that most of it involved 
an article on the Suharto family's purported wealth published two 
weeks ago in Time magazine's Asian edition. She said most of the 
article was untrue. 

</P>
<P>
	Shuttle Astronauts in Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) -- The space shuttle Discovery  
astronauts have lost no time getting to work after boarding the 
international space station. Astronaut Tamara Jernigan and Russian 
crewmate Valery Tokarev led the way inside the unfinished station 
Sunday evening. Inside the Russian-built Zarya control module, 
Tokarev and Canadian astronaut Julie Payette pulled up the floor 
and began swapping out electrical meters on batteries that aren't 
charging properly.Astronauts Rick Husband and Daniel Barry replaced 
two electronics boxes for a communication system inside the 
American Unity chamber. The system, which allows ground controllers 
to transmit and receive commands from the station, had been on the 
blink since mid-April but fired up quickly once the repairs were 
made. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Rise  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose today amid lackluster trading  
ahead of holidays in key overseas markets. The Nikkei gained 138.97 
points at 16,111.65. 

