<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former POW Now Ambassador To Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Pete Peterson has plenty of reasons to be  
bitter -- 6 1/2 years as a prisoner of war in Vietnam and the loss of 
his wife and 17-year-old son. 
</P>
<P>
	But the former congressman who became the first U.S. ambassador  
to Vietnam since the end of the war in 1975 likes to look to the 
future, not the past, and to reconciliation, not hatred. 
</P>
<P>
	His long, emotional journey is the subject of an hourlong  
documentary that premiered before a full house in Hanoi today -- 
Memorial Day in the United States. It will air in America on PBS on 
Sept. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson, a former Air Force pilot, was shot down in his F-4  
Phantom on Sept. 10, 1966, while making his 67th bombing run over 
North Vietnam. Of his 6 1/2 years as a POW, three were in the 
notorious ``Hanoi Hilton'' prison where he was tortured and held in 
solitary confinement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pulled out my .38 revolver ... and suggested to myself that  
maybe it would be easier and less painful if I took the revolver 
and ended my life,'' Peterson says in the film, describing the 
moments after he was forced to bail out and got stuck in a tree, 
knowing he would be taken prisoner soon. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. documentary filmmaker Sandy Northrop begins with Peterson's  
May 9, 1997, arrival in Hanoi, where he was greeted by a handful of 
American businessmen, then flashes back to his years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Using Vietnamese archival footage, Northrop graphically  
illustrates the isolation and pain the POWs suffered. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson explains how they used military codes to tap  
Shakespeare and old film plots to each other on the walls between 
their cells. Even when forced to do chores such as sweep the prison 
yard, the men blinked messages in code at each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Without that contact ``life would have been impossible; you  
would have lost faith, you would have given up,'' Peterson says in 
the film. 
</P>
<P>
	Released in March 1973 with other POWs, Peterson returned to his  
family in Florida, including his son Doug, who was born while he 
was in captivity. Peterson went into business. 
</P>
<P>
	But his troubles had only begun.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1985, Doug died in a car accident. The same year, his wife,  
Carlotta, was diagnosed with breast cancer. She died 10 years 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	He won a seat in Congress in 1990, but decided not to seek  
re-election after three terms. He was chosen to return to Hanoi as 
ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	Northrop, who worked on the documentary for almost two years,  
said she was overwhelmed by Peterson's ability to forget the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point you decide, `I will survive or I will die,'''  
Northrop said in an interview at her Hanoi apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you decide that, you've decided the course of your life.  
You just go forward. He hates to look back and wouldn't talk about 
being a POW or the torture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Northrop, whose past film work includes documentaries on animal  
life in Africa for National Geographic, said she wanted to show the 
reality of Vietnam today and explain the suffering that Vietnamese 
endured during the war. Much of the focus has been on the 58,000 
Americans who died, not the 3 million Vietnamese fatalities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to humanize the Vietnamese,'' Northrop said.  
``Americans assume they must hate us. But they don't. Coming here, 
at first you don't believe it, but they don't hate us. We are not 
the bad guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The film includes interviews with Pham Kim Hy, whose son is  
among an estimated 300,000 Vietnamese soldiers still listed as 
missing in action. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the film's most moving moments, Hy describes making  
four trips to the former Demilitarized Zone to search for her son's 
bones before giving up and simply burying earth in his grave 
outside Hanoi, which she visits every week. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the movie is an attempt to bring Vietnam and the United  
States closer together, the Ministry of Culture threatened to ban 
the premiere, backing down Friday afternoon only after Peterson 
intervened. 
</P>
<P>
	They still insisted on some cuts. One scene of a demonstration  
outside the Vietnamese Embassy in Washington was partially blacked 
out to conceal a flag of the former South Vietnam carried by 
protesters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please be aware there will be some places in the film where  
there won't be any sound and there won't be any footage. You can 
all guess why,'' U.S. businessman Peter Ryder told the audience of 
400 before Monday's screening. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the controversy and pain, the film has some happy  
moments. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson fell in love with Saigon-born Vi Le, now trade  
counselor to the Australian Embassy in Hanoi. Hanoi's Roman 
Catholic cathedral was packed when they were married a year ago in 
what was seen locally as a fairy-tale event of reconciliation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 09:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Honeybees As Land Mine Detectors? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- Honeybees equipped with radio tags no  
larger than a grain of rice may one day be used to detect 
antipersonnel land mines on battlefields and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	As farfetched as it might seem, a collaborative project seeks to  
train and track entire colonies of bees that may be conditioned to 
prefer something other than honey, such as TNT, the primary 
component of land mines. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, it may be possible to carry a hive to a site and  
release the bees to search for explosives or other things, such as 
methamphetamine-making ingredients or nuclear waste, said Ron 
Gilbert, who works on electronic systems at the Pacific Northwest 
National Laboratory here. 
</P>
<P>
	``This system is not unique for land mines,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The project, led by University of Montana entomologist Jerry  
Bromenshenk, depends on several factors -- particularly whether bees 
can smell and be taught to find TNT. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing what you can train a bee to do,'' said UM  
postgraduate student Bob Seccomb, who took part in a media 
demonstration with the bees. ``We've got them flying through 
mazes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Cross estimates there are 80 million to 120 million land  
mines in 70 countries around the world and that 60 people a day are 
killed or maimed by buried mines. In some developing countries, 
thousands of acres of productive land are unusable because they are 
death traps. 
</P>
<P>
	If the bees can indeed be trained to seek out explosives, the  
next step is to find a way to keep track of them. 
</P>
<P>
	That's where the radio tags come in. Several years ago, PNNL  
developed a first generation of radio-frequency tags for the 
garment industry to track inventory. The tags are similar to the 
microchips implanted by veterinarians as permanent identification 
for cats and dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers brought some 20,000 bees in two hives to  
Richland for three days of tag testing, which ended May 22. 
</P>
<P>
	UM student Jason Volkman carefully glued the tiny tags to the  
bees. To make them easier to work with, he chills the bees in a 
college dormitory-style refrigerator for four minutes, then 
attaches the tags to the bees' abdomens with tweezers. 
</P>
<P>
	The tags have a 10-character code that identifies each bee  
individually. The tags are read by sensitive instruments attached 
to a portable hive which records when the bees leave to forage, the 
direction they go and when they return. 
</P>
<P>
	A special spectrometer would be installed in the hive to  
``sniff'' the bees for the presence of TNT residue. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromenshenk has characterized the bees as ``flying dust mops,''  
picking up samples everywhere they go. Land mines leak small 
amounts of explosives into nearby soil and water, and the TNT 
residue eventually makes its way into some plants. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tag tests, researchers learned that the bees were not  
dissuaded from returning to the hive by the radio-tag reading 
equipment, Gilbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	They also found that the 27-milligram tags they planned on using  
were a little too heavy for the bees; 25 mg is better. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know how to make them lighter,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Sandia National Laboratories in New Mexico, the Oak Ridge  
National Laboratory in Tennessee and the U.S. Environmental 
Protection Agency also are part of the project, paid for by the 
federal Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 04:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agent: Michael Irvin Wants Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Michael Irvin, the Dallas Cowboys' career  
receiving leader, has requested that the team trade him, his agent 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11-year veteran played a lesser role last season in Dallas'  
offense under first-year coach Chan Gailey. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has not demanded a trade, but he has let the Cowboys know  
if something comes along that benefits the team and himself, he 
would be in favor of it,'' agent Steve Endicott told The Dallas 
Morning News in Monday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Endicott said Irvin had not made an ultimatum, and the wide  
receiver continues to work out regularly at the Cowboys' Irving, 
Texas practice facility, including the twice weekly coaching 
sessions that began in early May. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys have already been shaken in the past month by the  
heroin death of former All Pro tackle Mark Tuinei while he was 
accompanied by current reserve fullback Ricky Sualua, and by the 
injury problems of All-Pro cornerback Deion Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	The Morning News reported that teammates and club officials are  
aware that Irvin is unhappy over his declining role in the team's 
offense, the Cowboys' refusal to extend his contract, and trade 
rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said Irvin was out of town over the weekend and  
unavailable for comment, and club executive vice president Stephen 
Jones declined to speak in detail about Irvin's status. 
</P>
<P>
	``That wouldn't be fair to get in the middle of,'' said Jones,  
the son of team owner Jerry Jones. ``There are things that go on 
all the time that we don't really get into. We would have no 
comment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin made 74 catches for 1,057 yards last season, his lowest of  
the last eight years, with the exception of 1996, when he missed 
the first five games because of an NFL suspension after pleading no 
contest to cocaine possession. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin caught only one touchdown pass, a career low. His team  
record of catching a pass in 117 straight games was snapped by 
Arizona last November. 
</P>
<P>
	Gailey, who became coach before the 1998 season, has emphasized  
passing the ball to many receivers, reducing Irvin's role in the 
offense. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, the team has extended the contracts of  
quarterback Troy Aikman and running back Emmitt Smith, but not 
Irvin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Morning News said personnel directors around the league said  
Irvin's name floated on the trade market in late April. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys have only two other experienced receivers on their  
roster, Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail, recently signed as a free agent, 
and Ernie Mills. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas took two wide receivers in the April draft, in the fourth  
and sixth rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin, 6-foot-2 and 207 pounds, was the 11th player chosen in  
the 1988 draft out of Miami, where he set career records for 
catches, receiving yards and receiving touchdowns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
