<DOCNO> APW19990531.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 16:21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israelis Withdrawing from Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JEZZINE, Lebanon (AP) -- Putting words into action, tanks and  
troops from the Israeli-backed Lebanese militia began withdrawing 
today from a mountain resort in southern Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first sign of troop movement since reports of a planned  
withdrawal were confirmed Thursday, troops headed east with tanks, 
armored personnel carriers, cranes and other equipment. They 
appeared to be dismantling the base, which had served as the SLA 
headquarters for the Jezzine area. 
</P>
<P>
	The militiamen fired machine guns and tracer bullets ahead of  
them, combing the hills above the withdrawal route in standard 
evacuation procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in Marjayoun, the main town in the Israeli-occupied zone  
to the south, SLA commander Antoine Lahd said he was withdrawing 
from Jezzine ``since the situation ... could no longer endure more 
slow deaths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the pullout from Jezzine will be over by mid-June.  
</P>
<P>
	``This stance presents an end to the (SLA's) human presence.  
What remains is the logistical one,'' said Edmond Rizk, a former 
Cabinet member and former member of Parliament in Jezzine, where 
the peacetime population of 25,000 has dwindled to under 5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerrilla attacks led by the Hezbollah group have hurt the SLA  
in Jezzine. A total of 155 militiamen and 65 civilians have died in 
the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the withdrawal had officially begun, about half the  
Israeli-backed militiamen who have held this mountain town since 
1985 abandoned their garrison, dropping their guns and surrendering 
to the Lebanese government. 
</P>
<P>
	The first major retreat in 14 years could serve as a model for  
the troop withdrawals that Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak 
promised during his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Israel's departing Defense Minister Moshe Arens  
stressed Monday that the pullout from Jezzine was not part of a 
larger withdrawal from the Israeli-held zone in southern Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, secretary-general of  
Hezbollah, promised that his Shiite Muslim guerrillas will not 
enter Jezzine when Israeli-allied militiamen withdraw. 
</P>
<P>
	They will, however, continue launching attacks on Israelis and  
the South Lebanon Army militiamen from areas around Jezzine, 
Nasrallah said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.N. peacekeeping force said one of its soldiers  
was killed and another wounded Monday in cross-fire between Israeli 
forces and Muslim guerrillas in South Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	Timur Goksel, spokesman for the 4,500-member United Nations  
Interim Force in Lebanon, said the casualties occurred before dawn 
near the village of Braachit, six miles north of the Israeli 
border. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 227 peacekeepers have been killed since the U.N. force  
was deployed in southern Lebanon in 1978 under a U.N. peacekeeping 
mandate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
