<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Try To Avoid Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Baseball supposedly has the juiced ball. Maybe  
hockey has the juiced puck. 
</P>
<P>
	There has to be some way to explain how the Dallas Stars and  
Colorado Avalanche have turned the Western Conference finals into a 
high-stakes version of the offensive-oriented NHL All-Star Game. 
</P>
<P>
	After combining for 12 goals in Game 5 on Sunday, the teams  
return to the ice Tuesday night with Colorado one victory from 
advancing to its second Stanley Cup finals in four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way this round has gone so far, you can expect anything,''  
Colorado coach Bob Hartley said Monday. ``I didn't look into my 
magic ball today. The person who can predict what type of game it 
will be is a very bright man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To stave off elimination, the Stars need to avoid another  
fast-paced shootout that favored the fleet-skating Avalanche. 
Colorado scored seven goals in the first four games of the series 
before winning 7-5 Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We started playing their game,'' Dallas captain Derian Hatcher  
said. ``We didn't hit people the way we need to. We didn't check 
the way we need to. We played their game. We can't win games like 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado's scoring binge came without rookie forward Milan  
Hejduk (broken collarbone) and all-star right wing Theo Fleury, who 
missed Game 5 because of the flu. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury did not skate Monday but Hartley said he is feeling  
better and hopes to return for Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made sure I was walking on the other side of the street,''  
Colorado goaltender Patrick Roy said of staying away from his 
contagious teammate. ``It was nice to see Theo was much better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Fleury and Hejduk out, the Avalanche figured to be in  
trouble heading into Dallas for Game 5, but Peter Forsberg, Valeri 
Kamensky and rookie Chris Drury made up for their absence. 
</P>
<P>
	Although his only goal went into an empty net Sunday, Forsberg  
was the strongest offensive player on the ice. He set up two goals 
and rarely was knocked off the puck when the Avalanche controlled 
the tempo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The switch in Peter's mind went on and forced him to raise his  
game,'' Hartley said. ``He seems to get better and better with each 
game and he wants to compete. You see sparks in his eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drury has provided another kind of spark, scoring the  
game-winning goal in Game 4 before adding two more Sunday. He is in 
quest of his third team championship; Drury won the Little League 
World Series in 1989 and the NCAA hockey title with Boston 
University in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has great hockey sense,'' Hartley said. ``Once in a while  
it might happen by luck, but by the way he is accumulating 
game-winning goals, you don't just do that by luck. You have to 
have a natural instinct, and Chris Drury has that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Colorado's two-game surge, it's too early to discount  
Dallas. The Stars had the league's top record and did not lose 
three straight all season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's up to us to turn the tables on them and steal one in  
their building,'' forward Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``We had to go to 
Denver anyhow, so we might as well go up there and win it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
