<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women in Developed World, Fewer Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Women in the developed world have fewer children than women in  
the developing world for several reasons, population experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Women in the developed world are more likely to work outside the  
home. Contrary to agricultural societies, where more children mean 
more working hands, modern urban life imposes costs on families to 
feed, house and educate children. Contraception also is more 
available in the world's richer countries. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the average growth rate in the poorest countries is  
eight times higher than in wealthy countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Women in developing countries have an average of 5.5 children.  
Babies in the poorest countries are 11 times more likely to die in 
infancy; their life expectancy is 50 years -- 24 years fewer than in 
the rich countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Health Organization estimates about 585,000 woman die  
in childbirth annually. The WHO also estimates about 78,000 deaths 
a year are due to unsafe abortions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
