<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Little-Remembered Man Donates $377K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHILTON, Wis. (AP) -- An 80-year-old man who died last winter  
bequeathed $377,000 to a church he never joined, fairgrounds he 
rarely visited and a hospital where no one remembered him. 
</P>
<P>
	Randolph Landgraf, a World War II veteran, died in November  
after spending two years in a nursing home. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a very private person and never told us of his plans,''  
said niece Barbara Schmidlkofer of Bonita Springs, Fla., his 
closest surviving relative. ``I guess he wanted to do something for 
the city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calumet Medical Center received $94,000, though there's no  
record Landgraf was ever a patient there, said Lea Whitby, hospital 
chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Martin's Lutheran Church also got $94,000, though he wasn't  
a member. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best we can tell is that he worshipped at our church as a  
young man,'' said the Rev. Wayne Huebner, the pastor. ``Sometimes 
people in small towns do wonderful things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining $189,000 went to the Calumet County Fair Board. No  
one on the board knew the gift was coming, or even knew who 
Landgraf was. 
</P>
<P>
	Acquaintances said Landgraf rarely attended the fair.  
</P>
<P>
	Landgraf's family was once prominent in the town of 4,000, a  
half-hour drive south of Green Bay. His three older brothers died 
before him. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
