<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug's Advocate Fights Regulators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- Flying low over South Korea aboard Army  
medical helicopters, Stephen Mumford saw a flesh-and-blood bar 
graph of the impact rapid population growth can have on a poor 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumford, then administrator at an evacuation hospital, remembers  
skimming the country's roads in the late 1960s. Day after day, he 
saw people below streaming toward the capital city of Seoul. 
Thousands unable to feed themselves by farming migrated to the city 
for factory jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could see this migration below: household belongings in  
oxen carts and old pickup trucks,'' Mumford recalls. ``That's when 
I recognized that overpopulation was truly a serious problem that 
threatened the security of all countries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to the United States and earned a doctorate in  
public health, then began a career promoting contraception and 
population control. For two decades, his fervor has focused on a 
female sterilization method using quinacrine hydrochloride, a 
chemical the Food and Drug Administration and the World Health 
Organization say has not been adequately tested. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been enmeshed in it for 20-odd years. He breathes it.  
He's the only one currently who will not give up on it,'' said Dr. 
Michael Benjamin, a Tamarac, Fla., gynecologist who wants to use 
quinacrine in his practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents caution the drug needs more testing to resolve safety  
concerns. Some say Mumford and his associates have rashly promoted 
a drug used to sterilize more than 100,000 women in developing 
countries when there are questions about whether it causes cancer, 
prompts cells to mutate or affects undetected fetuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not at this point per se opposed to it. I am opposed to  
its use in people at this time based on the complete lack of 
adequate testing,'' said Dr. Amy Pollack, an 
obstetrician-gynecologist and president of AVSC International, 
which promotes family planning and reproductive health in the 
developing world. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA warned Mumford and his colleague, Dr. Elton Kessel, a  
Carlton, Ore., physician that they were violating U.S. law by 
shipping pellets abroad from a storehouse in Mumford's Chapel Hill 
home. They were told to destroy their stockpile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss company that made pellets on contract for Mumford's  
Center for Research on Population and Security has discontinued 
doing so. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumford said he would welcome funds -- it would cost $8 million --  
to could test quinacrine to ensure that it meets FDA guidelines, 
but says quinacrine has been used in humans for six decades. For 
him, the choice is acting to limit populations -- or doom. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's population is expected to reach six billion people  
this year. In 2015, the UN estimates there will be 7.3 billion 
people -- about six billion of them in the developing world. Global 
population is expected to be about 9.4 billion in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Providing sterilization services to everyone in the world  
would be peanuts compared to what the population wars will cost 
us,'' said Mumford, 56, who volunteers that he had a vasectomy in 
his 30s after he and his wife had two children. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumford's latest quest is to convince American doctors and  
researchers the drug is safe. He and Kessel touted quinacrine 
during a recent National Family Planning and Reproductive Health 
Association meeting in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at Family Health International, a Research Triangle  
Park firm founded to find contraception methods for Third World 
cultures, helped develop quinacrine sterilizations in the 1970s and 
1980s. The firm says quinacrine holds great promise but shouldn't 
be used until there's more testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumford and Kessel, both former employees of FHI, joined forces  
when Mumford incorporated his center in 1984. The wood-paneled 
basement of Mumford's home outside this university town for 15 
years has been the place from which quinacrine is distributed 
around the world free to health care workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumford and Kessel have been able to keep going because  
quinacrine is so cheap; each sterilization costs less than a 
dollar. Only about 15 cents of that cost is for the chemical 
itself. 
</P>
<P>
	The worldwide efforts of Mumford's center cost $156,000 in 1997,  
according to the center's annual tax report. Mumford salary was 
$50,000 as the center's president. Kessel was paid nothing as 
secretary-treasurer, but runs his own small research outfit which 
also promotes quinacrine. 
</P>
<P>
	Donors gave Mumford's center $782,000 between 1993 and 1997.  
Nonprofits like the center aren't required to identify donors 
except to the IRS. Mumford refused to share his list of 
contributors with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	News reports in the United States and England have linked donors  
to anti-immigration groups. Opponents have used the reports to 
question the center's motives. 
</P>
<P>
	No anti-immigration group backs his center, Mumford said.  
Neither do groups seeking tighter U.S. immigration limits, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Women's groups in India succeeded in banning quinacrine last  
August after 20 years in use. They were suspicious of the chemical 
being distributed by white men from rich countries. Some women in 
India and Vietnam reported not being told they were undergoing 
sterilization. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mumford says quinacrine sterilizations were developed in  
Chile and researched extensively in Vietnam. Local health care 
workers administered it thousands of times in India, Bangladesh and 
Pakistan, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This method was developed in a Third World country, not in the  
U.S.,'' said Mumford, who has a 3-inch-thick stack of studies on 
the drug dating from the 1940s. ``It's a south-to-south thing. Not 
a First-World-to-Third-World thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FHI has since 1994 been conducting follow-up checks with a  
random sample of 1,800 out of nearly 32,000 Vietnamese women 
sterilized with quinacrine. The results haven't been published, but 
an FHI spokesman says researchers have found no obvious health 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Adrienne Germaine, president of the International Women's Health  
Coalition in New York, said mankind would be better served by a 
successor to the condom -- a barrier to pregnancy and sexually 
transmitted diseases that women can control. 
</P>
<P>
	But Werner Fornos, president of the Washington-based Population  
Institute, compliments Mumford's determination to champion a method 
too cheap and too long off patent protection to make a drug company 
rich. 
</P>
<P>
	``It strikes many of us that there must be cheaper methods of  
contraception to fulfill the desire of more than 200 million women 
in the world who want no more children -- women who can't afford or 
don't have access to contraceptives,'' said Fornos. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
