<HEADLINE> McGehee Wins Indy Rookie Honors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Robby McGehee, whose chief mechanic was  
critically injured in a pit accident during the Indianapolis 500, 
was cited tonight as the race's rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	A trophy, which he dedicated to injured crewman Steve Fried, and  
a check for $25,000 were presented to McGehee at the annual Victory 
Celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	Fried, who suffered head and chest injuries, remained in  
critical but stable condition in the intensive care unit at 
Methodist Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went to see him today, and he wrote a note,'' said McGehee,  
who finished fifth, the highest of four rookies in the race. ``I 
know he's awake. He asked about whether we were rookie of the year. 
I said we were waiting for tonight, but we kind of thought we may 
be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGehee, who started 27th, earned $247,750, plus the $25,000  
rookie prize, for finishing fifth. He completed 199 of the 200 
laps. The other rookies were John Hollansworth Jr., who finished 
13th; Jeret Schroeder, 15th; and Wim Eyckmans, 23rd. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
