<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Down in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar edged higher against the yen early  
Tuesday in thin, range-bound dealings. Tokyo stock prices declined. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.68 yen in early trading, up 0.32 yen from  
late Monday in Tokyo. Currency markets in New York were closed 
Monday for a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 75.25 points,  
or 0.47 percent, to 16,03.40 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On 
Monday, the average closed up 138.97 points, or 0.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar got a small boost after the  
Management and Coordination Agency announced Japan's jobless rate 
stood at a record high 4.8 percent in April, unchanged from March. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the number of jobless people rose to a new record high  
of 3.42 million, the overall unemployment rate was slightly below 
the 4.9 percent which many economists had forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dollar-yen is stuck in a range, and it is hard to imagine it  
breaking out during Asian trading,'' said Hajime Sato, assistant 
general manager of the treasury department at Daiwa International 
Trust Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 126.75 yen, down  
from 128.31 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, profit-taking in reaction to the previous  
day's advance pushed the Nikkei average lower in early trading, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the latest jobless figure may put less pressure on  
the government to do more to stimulate the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The data may tone down calls for additional government  
stimulus measures,'' said Naoki Takahashi, manager at Marusan 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said they expected the Tokyo market to remain in a  
narrow range Tuesday with no other fresh market-moving news 
following the overnight holidays in the United States and Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 2.33 points, or 0.18 percent, to 1,294.86. 
The TOPIX closed down 5.12 points, or 0.39 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.4500 percent from Monday's finish of 1.4750 percent, 
driving its price up to 99.56 yen from 99.34 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
