	He was flown to the Indianapolis airport, where his sponsor,  
Home Depot, had its private jet waiting for the 65-minute flight to 
North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart changed into his NASCAR driving suit and caught a quick  
nap on the flight, stretching out on the couch in the back of the 
jet after guzzling water and Powerade to rehydrate. Then it was 
into another helicopter for a quick flight to Lowe's Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	All that, and he still had another 600 miles to go.  
</P>
<P>
	``This was too hard to do,'' he said. ``That made for a very  
long day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Stewart probably will stick to the Coca-Cola next year and  
leave Indy to the full-time open-wheel drivers. But he's glad he 
did the double at least once. He got chills when he heard the 
strains of ``Taps'' play at Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	And when he arrived at the Coca-Cola, some 150,000 fans stood  
and gave a deafening cheer as the helicopter flew low around the 
speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was definitely worth doing once,'' he said. ``The crowds'  
response at both places was definitely the highlight of the day.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
