<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temps May Not Stay Temps for Long </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MindSpring Enterprises, a fast-growing Internet provider,  
increasingly relies on a temp agency to supply a stream of workers 
for its call-in centers. But the company is careful to offer them 
staff jobs, or replace them after 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Like a growing number of companies, Atlanta-based MindSpring  
uses temporary workers to cut costs and solve labor shortages. 
</P>
<P>
	But temporary workers are increasingly demanding employee  
benefits if they work as long and hard as permanent workers, 
compelling wary businesses like MindSpring to take steps so temps 
don't become de facto employees. 
</P>
<P>
	A closely watched court battle between Microsoft Corp. and its  
longtime temps -- dubbed ``permatemps'' -- is the most visible sign 
of this growing workplace issue. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest twist to the case, a U.S. appeals court panel  
ruled in mid-May that thousands of former temps should have been 
allowed to join the company's lucrative stock-purchase program. 
Last Wednesday, Microsoft asked the full appeals court to review 
the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling was the first to hold that temps can look to both  
their agency and their work-site employer for benefits. It raises 
the specter that employers will be liable for everything from 
temps' benefits to their grievances. 
</P>
<P>
	``(It's) is another reminder ... that they just can't change the  
label or badge and turn them into a non-employee,'' said Catherine 
Ruckelshaus, litigation director at the National Employment Law 
Project, an advocacy group for low-wage workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1982, the percentage of temps has quadrupled to 2.2  
percent of all workers, according to forthcoming data from the 
Economic Policy Institute, a Washington, D.C.-based think tank. On 
any given day, about 1.3 million temps are at work, spawning an 
estimated $60 billion industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 90 percent of U.S. companies use temps, often because they  
provide a flexible, quick and cheaper source of labor. 
</P>
<P>
	Temps, who are mostly women, are clustered in low-paying work,  
such as secretarial jobs and most would prefer a permanent job. Few 
get health insurance or other benefits from their agencies, 
according to Economic Policy Institute studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft temps have filed a number of lawsuits against the  
company. Along with the suit seeking stock-purchase rights, the 
temps are suing for health insurance and pension benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft spokesman Dan Leach responds that temp agency  
employees look to their agencies for wages and benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear that Microsoft employees work for Microsoft  
and employees of temp agencies work for temp agencies,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But many employers aren't so sure that the lines of  
responsibility are clear anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	Some courts have defined a ``common-law employee'' as a worker  
who's spent more than five months at a company, substantially under 
the employers' control. 
</P>
<P>
	``We get calls regularly on this issue, asking `How do we make  
this determination,''' said Michael Bartlett, manager of labor law 
policy at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``There are serious 
liability concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, companies are tightening contracts to more clearly  
exclude temps from benefit plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Some have established internal ``temp agencies'' that assign  
roving permanent workers to different projects. Others have leased 
some of their operations to outside firms rather than bringing in 
temps. 
</P>
<P>
	MindSpring, the Internet provider, reluctantly began using temps  
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was so antithetical to our philosophy of how a good company  
operates,'' said vice president Carter Calle, explaining that 
MindSpring wants to rely on permanent employees who have a stake in 
the company due to stock options and other benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Now MindSpring uses a staffing agency to recruit, screen and  
hire temps, then -- to prevent ``permatemping'' -- makes sure they're 
either hired or let go after 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Temp agencies, as well, should do more for their workers,  
advocacy groups say. A coalition of such groups, including the 
national working women's group 9 to 5, will unveil a national code 
of conduct for temp agencies in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to raise the bar, and improve practices through  
voluntary action,'' said Ellen Bravo, co-director of 9 to 5. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Jersey, the coalition is helping a community group  
monitor the industry, with plans to publicize model temp agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a strategy applauded by Kamal Larsuel, a 29-year-old  
engineer who's been working as a Microsoft temp for 16 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft needs to put their foot down and say, `If you want  
to be a preferred agency with Microsoft, you need to provide us 
with better benefits,'' she suggested. ``That would be the smart 
thing to do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
