<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Joseph Not Great Against Sabres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Goaltender Curtis Joseph, a superhero for the  
Toronto Maple Leafs all season long, came dowm to earth in the 
Eastern Conference final against the Buffalo Sabres. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Cujo was weak or substandard during Toronto's five-game  
loss to the Sabres. He just didn't steal any games like he did 
several times this season and earlier in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maple Leafs played their best game of the series in the 4-2  
loss in Game 5 on Monday night. They dominated at times and 
probably deserved to win, but fortuitous goals by the Sabres ended 
Toronto's season. 
</P>
<P>
	Erik Rasmussen scored the winning goal at 11:35 of the third  
period when he backhanded a Brian Holzinger rebound past Joseph. 
</P>
<P>
	``This game was indicative of the series,'' said Joseph. ``A  
backhander, one-timer, top shelf. You don't see those go in every 
day. It wasn't even close to the middle of the net. Buffalo really 
was a team of destiny all series. They made their shots when they 
had to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Toronto's previous series against the Philadelphia Flyers  
and Pittsburgh Penguins, when Joseph was bordering on the 
spectacular with a .930 save percentage, the Vezina Trophy finalist 
wasn't at his best against Buffalo. His save percentage in the five 
games against the Sabres was just .850. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody was pointing the finger at Cujo in the series. Quite the  
contrary. They defended his play all season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cujo is the reason why this team got this close to the Stanley  
Cup final,'' said forward Kris King. ``He's a fabulous player and 
he's as good a person as he is a player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Cujo was able to win us some games this year when maybe we  
didn't deserve it,'' said center Steve Sullivan. ``He's a much 
better goalie than I expected he would be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maple Leafs coach Pat Quinn called Joseph ``a rock all year.''  
</P>
<P>
	``He was determined all series, but we weren't as good as we  
needed to be.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
