<HEADLINE> Two Killed in Alaskan Raft Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Two Georgia women drowned during a  
weekend river rafting trip just outside Denali National Park and 
Preserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Another rafting accident in Montana left one woman dead and  
another missing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Alaska, Eloise Hubbard, 75 of Doraville, Ga., and Doris  
North, 75, of Decatur, Ga., were on a 13-mile scenic tour Saturday 
of the Nenana River, which forms the eastern border of the park, 
175 miles north of Anchorage. 
</P>
<P>
	When their raft got caught in a whirlpool, the women were thrown  
into the water. 
</P>
<P>
	``They hit a swell in the water and then went into a whirlpool.  
The raft was literally just sucked down,'' said Alaska State 
Trooper Bill Tyler. 
</P>
<P>
	The other passengers who shared the raft with the women managed  
to remain inside. Nine people were treated for mild hypothermia and 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	``She had planned this trip for a year,'' Mrs. Hubbard's  
18-year-old grandson, Chris Ryan, told The Atlanta 
Journal-Constitution. ``She always took care of me and my mother. 
She never had a bad word to say about anyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tour company, Alaska Raft Adventure, suspended its rafting  
operations indefinitely and was investigating the circumstances 
that led to the accident, said Bob Seney, a manager with the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Near Divide, in southwestern Montana, four people were on a raft  
that capsized Sunday afternoon in the cold, swift-running Big Hole 
River. One died and another was missing and presumed dead. The 
search for her was called off for the night at 10 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, she's been in there five hours, and we've gone from  
a rescue mode to a recovery (of a body),'' Butte-Silver Bow County 
Sheriff John McPherson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The four, two men and two women, were unable to guide the raft  
to the river bank in the strong current as it approached the Divide 
Pumphouse Dam, officials said. The raft capsized as it went over 
the dam. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men got out of the water but the river carried the women  
ahead of them. Names of the rafters were not released Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	McPherson said the river is far too swift for rafters at this  
point. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a good idea to be rafting on that river tonight,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
