<HEADLINE> Cathay Cancels Flights in Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways canceled 31 flights  
Sunday, a quarter of its total daily flight schedule, after pilots 
called in sick amid a dispute over pay cuts and layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots have been staying home since Friday when the Hong  
Kong-based airline halted nine weeks of negotiations. Cathay has 
given the pilots until June 11 to choose whether to take a pay cut, 
retire early or be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the carrier asked its senior pilots to take an 8  
percent pay cut in exchange for stock options after it took its 
first losses in 35 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials denied they had organized for the pilots to call  
in sick in an effort to force Cathay to reopen negotiations, but 
said they would not rule out future strike actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay officials refused to disclose how many pilots had called  
in sick. Some pilots have taken sick days saying they are too 
stressed by the layoff threats. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest flight cancelations announced by the airline came  
after it canceled 30 flights Saturday, affecting 5,000 passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline has stopped taking bookings since late Friday for  
flights flying in the next two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay lost $69 million last year and has been trying to cut  
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots' pay dispute follows Cathay's recent battle with its  
flight attendants, who eventually conceded to management demands 
that they work more hours in exchange for a pay increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
