<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bombs Kill 16 Yugoslav Civilians  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO missiles killed at least 16  
people when they smashed into a hospital and a retirement home 
today in Yugoslavia, said Serb officials, amid growing concern 
about civilian casualties from the alliance's bombing campaign. The 
alliance acknowledged striking a military barracks and an 
ammunition storage area in the area around Surdulica, 220 miles 
southeast of Belgrade, but would not confirm hitting the civilian 
sites and the reports of casualties. Condemning the ``murdering of 
civilians'' in Serbia, President Slobodan Milosevic said the latest 
attacks endangered fragile peace efforts. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombia Won't Talk to Rebels  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- The government today rejected further  
peace contacts with rebels until 85 hostages seized from a plane 
and a church are released. In the latest abduction, about 30 
members of the National Liberation Army, or ELN, barged into the La 
Maria church yesterday and tricked the worshippers into their 
trucks by claiming a bomb was in the building. The rebels abandoned 
84 of the worshippers to pursuing troops and fled into the 
mountains, an army chief said. Last month, the ELN hijacked an 
Avianca Airlines flight and it is holding 25 people captive from 
that incident. 

</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Fix Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Working fast, astronauts fixed a  
broken radio, replaced flawed battery packs and installed foam 
mufflers over noisy fans today aboard the new international space 
station. They launched into the repairs within minutes of entering 
the 77-foot orbiting complex late yesterday. Several hours later, 
much of the work was done. The astronauts have until Thursday to 
finish the repairs and unload 1 1/2 tons of tools, spare parts, 
computers, water and clothes into the station's two compartments. 
The hatches will be sealed Thursday, and Discovery will pull away 
Thursday night. 

</P>
<P>
	Rwanda, Rebels Down Congo Jets  
</P>
<P>
	KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Congolese rebels and Rwandan forces shot  
down two MiG fighters today after they attacked positions in 
southern Congo, a Rwandan leader said. The violence came despite a 
unilateral cease-fire called by Rwanda. Vice President Paul Kagame 
also urged Congo to start talking directly to the Congolese rebels, 
who are backed by Rwanda and Uganda, and declare a cease-fire. The 
Zimbabwean MiG fighters, flying in support of the Congolese 
government, were shot down during two separate attacks, Kagame 
said. The pilots were killed when their planes crashed in Manono 
and Eshimba in southern Congo, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	EU Lifts Sanctions on Nigeria  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- The European Union today announced it was  
lifting economic sanctions against Nigeria following the 
inauguration of a civilian government. The EU imposed sanctions on 
Nigeria in 1995 during the rule of Gen. Sani Abacha, whose regime 
became a pariah as a result of state-sponsored human rights abuses. 
Abacha's death a year ago paved the way for the democratic 
transition, which culminated in Saturday's inauguration of Olusegun 
Obasanjo, the winner of elections in February. 

</P>
<P>
	Britain Revives Cheeserolling Race  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Runners tore down a 300-yard course in pursuit of  
an 8-pound double Gloucester cheese wheel today at a revival of the 
custom of cheeserolling. The person who crosses the finish line 
right behind the fast-rolling wheel gets to keep it. Stephen Brain, 
30, of Gloucester, won all three men's races at Cooper's Hill near 
Gloucester, 115 miles west of London. According to ``The Customs 
and Ceremonies of Britain,'' cheeserolling was once an event at 
spring celebrations. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs Take 2-0 Lead  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Sean Elliott made six of seven 3-pointers,  
including the game-winner with nine seconds left, as San Antonio 
came from 18 points down in the third quarter to beat the stunned 
Portland Trail Blazers 86-85 today. The Spurs' eighth consecutive 
playoff victory gives them a 2-0 lead in the Western Conference 
finals. 

</P>
<P>
	Cardinals 5, Marlins 2  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Edgar Renteria, Kent Bottenfield and a TV replay  
helped the St. Louis Cardinals beat the Florida Marlins 5-2 today. 
Former Marlins World Series hero Renteria hit a pair of solo homers 
against his ex-teammates, while Bottenfield pitched five innings 
and improved to 8-2, tying him for the NL lead in victories. 
Television also had a rare role: The Marlins played the game under 
protest after the umpiring crew consulted a TV replay before 
changing a call, costing Florida a run. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
