<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Creatine May Not Be Good As Thought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The supplement creatine is not the muscle  
builder and performance booster that many athletes believe it is, 
the chairman of a panel of experts has concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	``The expectations for creatine far outweigh the returns,'' said  
Ron Terjung, a professor of physiology at the University of 
Missouri, Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Terjung chaired a roundtable on creatine supplementation at the  
American College of Sports Medicine in Indianapolis. The 
roundtable's opinions will be shared at the sports medicine 
organization's annual meeting June 5 in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one critic, a supporter of creatine, plans to be on  
hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers have found performance improvements in laboratory  
tests involving sudden bursts of very strenuous activity, Terjung 
said. But the improvements are under specific conditions, and they 
don't match up with what most athletes do, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, in the third through sixth repetition of a brief  
but very intense workout on a stationary bike, performance might 
improve 2 percent or 3 percent, Terjung said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Others would say that's the distinction between a gold medal  
or not, but the circumstances don't match the sport task,'' he 
said. What's more, so many other things can affect sports 
performance that it would be hard to weed out the effects of the 
creatine on competition, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Creatine-using athletes don't seem to realize this, Terjung  
said. There are many reports of athletes who believe creatine makes 
them stronger or faster, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Creatine supplements work by helping the body replenish  
adenosine triphosphate, known as ATP, which is a key source of 
energy for muscle. The body makes creatine, but creatine also can 
be found in protein-rich foods as well as in over-the-counter 
preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	When the body reaches a maximum and muscles are saturated with  
creatine, the balance is excreted in the urine. As a result, more 
is not necessarily better, and users who try to supersaturate with 
massive doses will fail, Terjung said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the muscles have what they can handle, only about 3 more  
grams a day are needed to maintain this level, he said. ``The 
modest few grams will certainly suffice,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury is still out on creatine's value as a training aid,  
Terjung said. The supplement clearly makes athletes bigger, but 
this seems largely to be because creatine makes them retain water, 
he said. It's not certain if creatine builds lasting strength or 
endurance improvements, or whether the performance changes that 
result from creatine linger after creatine use ends, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, some training rooms are becoming more cautious  
about supplying the supplement, although others still provide it 
freely to athletes, said Dr. Mark S. Juhn of the University of 
Washington. Schools that are cutting back may also be concerned 
about possible side effects and the resulting potential for legal 
action, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletes who have taken creatine have reported such problems as  
cramping and diarrhea, although the problems end after creatine use 
is stopped. On the other hand, any severe long-term effects that 
creatine could have on the body aren't known yet, said Juhn, who 
wrote a review article in a medical journal, The Physician and 
Sportsmedicine. Juhn noted two case reports of kidney problems, 
including one March 19 in the New England Journal of Medicine. The 
cases responded to treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Juhn overstates the risk, countered researcher Richard B.  
Kreider of the University of Memphis. He and Steven S. Plisk of 
Yale wrote a largely supportive review in the Strength and 
Conditioning Journal of the National Strength and Conditioning 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our view is that creatine appears to be safe and effective,''  
he said. The reports of cramping are not out of the ordinary, 
considering that athletes normally have some cramping as they 
train, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two clinical reports don't make a case for risk because they  
can't rule out some other cause for the condition, he said, adding 
that several studies have found no kidney risk. 
</P>
<P>
	And creatine clearly works, said Juhn, who plans to attend the  
ACSM's Seattle seminar. Creatine helps athletes gain muscle, and 
the gains are too big to be explained simply by water retention, 
Juhn's article said. What's more, creatine's gains come without 
adding body fat, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Creatine's critics also understate the supplement's benefits,  
Juhn said. If it improves performance in a lab test, then creatine 
should help performance on the field, he said. Lab tests are done 
because it's scientifically too difficult to test the supplement 
under game conditions, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Juhn and Plisk caution athletes who take creatine to be  
sure they are getting the real stuff. ``The market is being flooded 
with low-quality product of overseas origin and possibly with 
domestic product that is being cut by unscrupulous distributors 
(often accompanied by a bogus/photocopied certificate of analysis 
or none at all),'' their article said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buyers should make sure their dealer and the manufacturer have  
solid reputations, it said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
