<HEADLINE> Higher Interest Rates May Be on Way / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At their present pace of spending and borrowing,  
Americans will surely get a dose of what they don't want, which is 
higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	That isn't to say they will maintain the present pace, but if  
they do the excess of demand over supply eventually will show up in 
prices, setting off a clanging alarm in Federal Reserve offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Providing a clear indication of what could occur, Fed  
policy-makers recently indicated that they were leaning toward a 
move to raise rates if supply didn't more evenly match demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other effects, higher short-term rates would mean added  
costs to corporations, which have been able to hold the price line 
by raising productivity and cutting prices. 
</P>
<P>
	With their money costs raised, and unable to cut costs in other  
areas, companies would be inclined to raise prices. That is, unless 
consumer demand lessened, and consumers lowered their level of 
borrowing, reduced their debts and began saving. 
</P>
<P>
	Borrowing and spending as a percentage of income have been near  
record highs over the past year, and the savings rate has fallen to 
its lowest since records were begun. It has been less than zero for 
five of the past six months, a feat made possible by easy credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Housing markets and prices too have been near all-time highs,  
month after month surprising analysts who say a downturn is likely. 
And automobile sales too. And recreation and travel as well. 
</P>
<P>
	It isn't likely to continue, unless as they say in the stock  
market, we've entered a new era, this one being an era of unlimited 
funds for unlimited demands for limitless material desires. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the economy needs a rest, and if consumers won't  
provide it then higher interest rates will. Higher rates inevitably 
work their way through the economy, raising costs and slow 
activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Housing's fate, usually a precursor of things to come, provides  
an excellent example since it leads to so many other purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Home Builders estimates that  
construction of 1,000 single-family homes generates 2,448 jobs, 
$79.4 million in wages and $42.5 million in tax revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	This spending helps finance thousands of companies in hundreds  
of industries: lumber, paints, masonry, glass, steel, copper, 
aluminum, asphalt, slate, drywall, tile, mortar, plastics, etc. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending doesn't stop there. The NAHB study indicates that a  
new homebuyer in the first year after purchase spends $2,475 on 
property alterations, $2,177 on furnishings and $529 on appliances. 
</P>
<P>
	Raise mortgage rates just slightly and otherwise make borrowing  
a bit tougher and you'll have thrown a pebble into the local 
economic pond. Multiply by a thousand and the ripples cross oceans. 
</P>
<P>
	For a forecast of things to come, therefore, it would be  
instructive to look at housing's statistics. If the pace slows, 
maybe there won't be higher rates. If not, then watch the Fed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
