<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally mixed  
Monday, with prices rising in Tokyo and Hong Kong but slumping in 
Taipei and New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained  
138.97 points, or 0.87 percent, to close at 16,111.65. On Friday, 
the average shed 204.51 points, or 1.26 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Market sentiment in Tokyo was boosted by a rise in U.S. shares  
on Friday and the dollar's climb against the yen in Asian trading 
on Monday. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 92.81 
points to close Friday at 10,559.74. 
</P>
<P>
	However, trading was light as many investors abstained from  
taking positions due to market holidays Monday in the United States 
and Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Many market players also held back as they mulled over whether  
Japan is likely to draw up a new budget to pay for additional 
economic stimulus measures, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the dollar was quoted at 121.36 yen in late afternoon  
trading, up 0.84 yen from late Friday in Tokyo but below its late 
New York level of 121.43 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange closed higher after two  
straight sessions of sharp declines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 87.87 points, or 0.7 percent, closing at 
12,147.12. On Friday, the index had slumped 249.28 points, or 2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices were pushed up by a bout of  
bargain-hunting late in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	But shares of Cathay Pacific Airways slumped because of a pay  
dispute between the airline and its pilots that caused many flights 
to be canceled. Cathay's shares fell 1.15 Hong Kong dollars (U.S. 
14 cents) to 10.65 Hong Kong dollars (U.S. $1.30). 
</P>
<P>
	In Taiwan, share prices closed sharply lower in the absence of  
market-boosting news. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's main Weighted Stock Price Index fell 103.13  
points, or 1.38 percent, to 7,316.57. 
</P>
<P>
	New Zealand share prices also closed sharply lower, with brokers  
attributing the slide to a bout of heavy overseas selling in local 
blue-chip stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The main NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 52.81 points, or 2.5  
percent, to 2,061.40. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was closed in Thailand for a public holiday.  
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: The Philippine stock index closed higher, boosted by the  
favorable first quarter economic data released Friday and a 
recovery on Wall Street. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange 
Index (PSE Index) rose 27.55 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,419.83. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher, with a sharp rise  
in banking stocks countering a fall in the resources sector to see 
the broader market push up into positive territory. The All 
Ordinaries Index rose 11.6 points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,900.2. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed mixed. The Korea Composite Stock  
Price Index rose 3.78 points, or 0.5 percent, to 736.02. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed little changed. The Straits Times  
Index edged up 0.18 point to 1,903.86. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower on  
profit-taking despite the release of favorable trade data for 
April. The benchmark Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip 
stocks, fell 5.99 points, or 0.7 percent, to 743.04. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed mixed, but continued buying in  
selected blue chips pushed the broader index into positive 
territory. The Composite Index rose up 0.3 percent, or 1.593 
points, to 585.242. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
