<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Casting Stones on China Spy Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To make a political issue of Chinese nuclear  
spying, Republicans have to pleaded ignorance, because GOP 
administrations were in charge for 12 of the 20 years when weapons 
secrets are said to have been leaking. 
</P>
<P>
	That's producing an odd debate.  
</P>
<P>
	Presidents are supposed to supervise national security and  
intelligence gathering, so in contending that the current 
administration is culpable but theirs weren't, Republicans are 
admitting that their people didn't do the job right either. 
</P>
<P>
	There is ample evidence of blundering by this White House. It's  
worse because of blurred White House accounts of who knew what 
when, of what President Clinton was told, at what time, and why 
there wasn't instant action. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's instinct for the evasive answer is part of his problem  
now. He said 2 1/2 months ago that he was not aware of any espionage 
by China against U.S. nuclear weapons laboratories ``during my 
presidency.'' In defense of that statement, Clinton allies now say 
that nobody has been convicted of spying. 
</P>
<P>
	But the administration had reports of alleged espionage as early  
as 1995, and Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, has 
said he briefed the president on the problem in July 1997; he'd 
earlier said it wasn't until 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton issued a directive for stronger security and  
counterintelligence measures at the nuclear weapons labs in 
February 1998. And whatever the timing of Clinton briefings, the 
House report that China has been stealing nuclear secrets was 
delivered to the administration on Jan. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	All of that invites suspicions and Republican accusations of lax  
security or worse, suggesting, without really saying, that the mess 
may have something to do with illegal Chinese contributions to the 
Democrats for the 1996 Clinton re-election campaign. The House 
report said Chinese agents ``may have used these contributions to 
gain access to U.S. military and commercial technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., chairman of the select committee  
that investigated Chinese spying, said it has worsened on Clinton's 
watch. ``If you take a look at the quality and quantity of thefts 
that have occurred of late, this is an espionage effort that has 
accelerated over the last several years,'' he said in a TV 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The report from Cox's committee was unanimous and bipartisan,  
but the mood didn't last. While both Democrats and Republicans are 
saying that the task now is to fix what's wrong and protect what 
secrets haven't been lost, the blame argument comes first. Sen. 
Trent Lott, the Senate Republican leader, said there should be no 
rush to judgment -- and that heads should roll. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighty House Republicans joined by one maverick Democrat have  
sent Clinton a letter calling for the resignation of Berger on 
grounds he misled Congress and the nation as to when he was told of 
Chinese espionage and when he told the president. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, Sen. Richard  
Shelby, R-Ala., wants Attorney General Janet Reno to resign for 
mishandling the legal side of the spy case. She said she won't, but 
acknowledged delays in the case, and said she was not informed of a 
dispute that prevented FBI wiretapping of an alleged spy two years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican candidates for president in 2000 quickly seized on  
the spy issue, Texas Gov. George W. Bush breaking his relative 
silence to say that he'd have acted immediately as president. He 
said Clinton didn't, and then tried to minimize the seriousness of 
the breach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that China has been stealing secrets during  
Carter, Reagan, Bush and Clinton,'' he said. ``But there is only 
one administration that has been given the news.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This administration knew more and still chose not to take  
action,'' said Elizabeth Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle, vice president in the administration of Bush's  
father, said they would have dealt with the spying had they known. 
``The real political scandal is the fact that there was evidence of 
this and the first response of the administration was simply to 
ignore it, to cover it up,'' Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	He sidestepped the question of whether the Bush administration  
should have known. ``The fact is we didn't, and I can't go back 
eight, or seven years as to why we didn't, but we didn't,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were warning signals in those Republican years. A  
Defense Intelligence Agency report in 1984 reported Chinese nuclear 
spying even then. It was released last week by the private National 
Security Archive. During the Bush administration, the General 
Accounting Office reported that ineffective security made the 
weapons labs vulnerable to espionage. An Energy Department official 
says he tried to alert the Senate Intelligence Committee to alleged 
spying in 1994 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The House report suggests that the problem may have started as a  
Cold War leftover, because U.S. intelligence was so focused on the 
old Soviet Union that China wasn't a priority. That has changed in 
the past few years, the committee report said, but U.S. authorities 
still lack the resources or the linguists needed for the task. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
