<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Tries To Disprove Charges  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's government took reporters on a tour of  
the Internet today to show that data about America's nuclear 
arsenal is freely available. Zhao Qizheng, the government's top 
spokesman, said the power, weight, dimensions and other details of 
the seven types of U.S. nuclear weapons China was alleged to have 
stolen were openly published in the United States. More data, 
including information on the most sophisticated U.S. warhead, the 
W-88, ``can easily be found on the Internet,'' Zhao said. ``They 
are no longer secrets, so there is nothing to steal.'' A U.S. 
congressional committee on Chinese espionage concluded that China 
stole secrets about the major warheads in the U.S. nuclear arsenal 
over 20 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Bombs Kill 16 Yugoslav Civilians  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO missiles reportedly smashed  
into a hospital and a retirement home today, crushing part of a 
building and killing at least 16 people. NATO has not accepted 
responsibility for the attack. President Slobodan Milosevic said 
the latest attacks endangered peace efforts, which continue this 
week with talks with the Finnish president. The Yugoslav government 
reiterated that it accepts principles set forth by the Group of 
Eight for ending the Kosovo conflict. But Milosevic's latest 
statement still fell short of Western demands for the makeup of a 
peacekeeping force in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Fans, Wrestlers Attend Hart Funeral  
</P>
<P>
	CALGARY, Alberta (AP) -- Politicians and singers joined  
professional wrestlers and fans at a funeral today for wrestler 
Owen Hart. Hart, 34, known as the Blue Blazer, plunged 70 feet to 
his death last Sunday during a dramatic entrance for a match in 
Kansas City, Mo. Some 1,300 mourners packed the private service 
today. About 1,000 fans stood outside listening to the service over 
loudspeakers. 

</P>
<P>
	All-Male Batch of Mice Cloned  
</P>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Scientists in Hawaii have cloned a trio of  
identical mice using ordinary cells rather than DNA extracted from 
the female reproductive system. This time, the cloned critters were 
male. The clones grew using genetic material extracted from tail 
cells of adult male mice, but only one grew to adulthood, according 
to a study in the June issue of the journal Nature Genetics. 
Researchers said their experiment demonstrates that cloning can be 
accomplished with the genetic material contained in the nucleus of 
somatic cells, or ordinary cells found throughout the body. 

</P>
<P>
	Hackers Hit More Federal Computers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hackers vandalized two more government sites  
on the Internet today and left a taunting note promising to attack 
more federal computers because of a related FBI investigation. 
Hackers from different organizations defaced a Web page within the 
Interior Department and a site run by a federal supercomputer 
laboratory in Idaho Falls, Idaho, claiming ``it's our turn to hit 
them where it hurts.'' Last week, hackers claiming to be from 
another group defaced the Web site for the U.S. Senate, causing it 
to be taken offline until the weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Trial Resumes Tuesday  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Microsoft's trial resumes for the final  
phase, the government will urge the judge to focus on the software 
company's aggressive behavior toward competitors earlier this 
decade and on its dominance today. Microsoft, though, wants U.S. 
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to look to the future, when 
Microsoft believes its Windows software will face unprecedented 
competition from fledgling technologies. The antitrust trial was 
scheduled to resume tomorrow after a 13-week recess and despite 
secret efforts to settle the case. 

</P>
<P>
	Pirates Beat Dodgers 5-4  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Warren Morris blooped a tiebreaking single to  
center as the Pittsburgh Pirates, helped twice by some 
lackadaisical Los Angeles outfield defense, scored twice with two 
outs in the eighth inning to beat the Dodgers 5-4 today. The 
Pirates won their season high-tying fourth in a row and seventh in 
nine games. The Dodgers, who squandered leads of 3-0 and 4-3, 
hadn't played in Pittsburgh on Memorial Day since 1990, when the 
Pirates rallied with five runs in the ninth to win 6-5. 

</P>
<P>
	Mechanic Survives Indy Pit Accident  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Crewmates of a mechanic who was critically  
injured when he was run over on pit row during the Indy 500 said 
today they are staying optimistic he will be OK. Meanwhile, 
management of the Energizer Motorsports team will have their crews 
donning helmets at the next Indy Racing League event June 12 at 
Texas Motor Speedway. Chief mechanic Steve Fried remained in 
critical but stable condition in the intensive care unit at 
Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis. He is awake and responding to 
those around him, doctors said. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
