<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Rescuers on Monday pulled out 17 cave  
enthusiasts who were trapped overnight in a Puerto Rican cavern 
when an underground river sealed off their exit and swept away one 
of their guides. 
</P>
<P>
	The group was touring a cave in western Lares, about 50 miles  
west of San Juan, when heavy rains began at about 3 p.m., swelling 
a subterranean river. 
</P>
<P>
	One of their guides, Francis Reyes, tried to cross the river  
with a member of the group, but was dragged deeper into the cave by 
the current, police said. His body was found Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The caver he had tried to help, Elba Vazquez Gonzalez, was  
thrown against rocks and suffered a head injury. She was in stable 
condition Monday at a hospital in nearby Arecibo. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other women made it across unhurt and walked to nearby homes  
for help. 
</P>
<P>
	A Civil Defense team rappelled into the cave using  
mountaineering equipment and located the group early Monday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori said Monday that  
Peru had relaunched the sale of its vast Camisea natural gas fields 
in the Amazon jungle, 10 months after oil giants Shell had Mobil 
pulled out of the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Fujimori has called the $2.4 billion Camisea development the  
``project of the century'' for Peru that would power this poor 
South American nation's economic growth into the 21st century. 
Camisea is the largest natural gas field in the Americas. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal Dutch/Shell and Mobil Corp. pulled out of the project due  
to differences with the government over the sale and marketing of 
the gas. Industry analysts said that rising projected costs and a 
lack of secure markets for the gas had also taken some of the 
luster off the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Camisea is located 310 miles southeast of Lima amid some of the  
world's most biodiverse jungle and primitive Indian tribes. It has 
proven reserves of 13 trillion cubic feet of natural gas. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Hundreds of people in central Mexico  
developed food poisoning after eating contaminated cakes last 
weekend, Mexican news media reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government Notimex news agency reported about 200 people  
became sick Sunday in the community of Tlalpujahua in the state of 
Michoacan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Televisa news agency said 600 people had become ill in 15  
communities in Michoacan and neighboring Mexico state with 
vomiting, diarrhea and fever. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaime Lopez Rivera, the Tlalpujahua health director, said  
victims had attended various functions Sunday in which they ate 
cakes from several stores in the community of El Oro in the state 
of Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	He said tests are being conducted to determine what caused the  
illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Pledging an end to political  
infighting, San Juan Mayor Sila Calderon become president of her 
Popular Democratic Party Monday, the first step in her campaign for 
Puerto Rican governor. 
</P>
<P>
	As party supporters cheered and waved the party's red-and-white  
flag, Calderon took her oath of office from outgoing president 
Anibal Acevedo Vila during a ceremony at the party's headquarters 
near San Juan's colonial district. 
</P>
<P>
	The act was a signal that the popular mayor is the party's only  
candidate to run against Gov. Pedro Rossello, who is expected to 
seek a third term in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In her acceptance speech, the 56-year-old mayor said the party  
must quickly heal differences between politicians vying for 
resident commissioner, Puerto Rico's non-voting delegate in the 
U.S. Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Puerto Ricans want to see us united,'' Calderon said. ``It is  
imperative that we leave behind the confrontations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A mob beat and burned to death two men  
they accused of thievery in a village in northern Guatemala Monday, 
bringing the number of lynching victims nationwide to 19 so far in 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,000 residents of the village of Setul, 60 miles north of  
Guatemala City, captured the two men, aged 21 and 27, and beat them 
severely before burning them alive, said Angel Conte, director of 
the National Civil Police. 
</P>
<P>
	Another group of villagers blocked police and human rights  
officials from entering the village while the lynching took place, 
Conte said. By the time officials made it into Setul, the charred 
bodies had been buried. 
</P>
<P>
	Another four men, who villagers claimed belonged to the same  
criminal gang, escaped. Residents are reportedly searching for 
those men in surrounding villages. 
</P>
<P>
	A 30-year-old man was lynched in the same area last week.  
</P>
<P>
	About 50 people were lynched in Guatemala in 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	In a January report, the U.N. Verification Mission in Guatemala  
said mob justice threatens the rule of law, sometimes targets 
people known to be innocent and is often tolerated by local 
officials. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
