<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds Mourn Ecuadorean Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) -- Using black and red felt-tip markers,  
friends of the four boys struck and killed by an Amtrak train wrote 
goodbyes on their light-colored caskets. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 700 mourners crowded the Church of Jesus Christ of  
Latter-day Saints on Sunday at a wake for the boys and their 
mother, Julia Toledo de Urgiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services were scheduled today at the same Trumbull  
church. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were beautiful children, well-behaved,'' said Terry  
Asija, a native of Ecuador. She knew the Toledo family, who 
emigrated to Bridgeport from Ecuador 18 months ago, through the 
church. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Urgiles ``loved her children. They were very well cared  
for,'' said Asija. ``In one tragic moment, they're all gone. What 
more can I say?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Urgiles, 47, will be buried in the same casket with her  
3-year-old son, Pedro. Jose, 10, and Angel, 6, also will share a 
casket. The oldest boy, Carlos, 11, will lie in his own casket. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was struck from behind Tuesday by an Amtrak train in  
Fairfield as they walked across a railroad trestle in the middle of 
the night. Mrs. Urgiles, Pedro, Angel and Carlos were killed 
instantly. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose was declared brain-dead at Bridgeport Hospital two days  
after the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, children left messages in both English and Spanish  
for the boys, saying ``I love you,'' or ``Te amo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Marquez, 9, a friend of Jose Toledo, wrote ``I will miss  
you a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A large arrangement of flowers with a white ribbon sash read  
``classmates'' in gold lettering. 
</P>
<P>
	A Drug and Alcohol Resistance Education, or DARE, T-shirt was  
signed by classmates and placed behind Carlos' casket. He was to 
receive a bronze DARE medallion this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral Director Edgar Rodriguez, of Funeraria Luz de Paz in  
Bridgeport, said arranging the funeral for a mother and her four 
young children has been an emotional task. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult, but I have to really put my feelings aside,''  
he said. ``My goal is to protect this family and help them grieve 
and help them heal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The boys' father, Carlos Luis Urgiles, who arrived from Ecuador  
on Friday, did not attend the wake. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
