<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose today amid lackluster trading  
ahead of holidays in key overseas markets. The dollar climbed 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 138.97  
points, or 0.87 percent, to close at 16,111.65. On Friday, the 
average shed 204.51 points, or 1.26 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.36 yen in late afternoon trading, up 0.84  
yen from late Friday in Tokyo but below its late New York level of 
121.43 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, trading was light as many investors  
abstained from taking positions due to market holidays today in the 
United States and Britain, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many market players also held back as they mulled over whether  
Japan is likely to draw up a new budget to pay for additional 
economic stimulus measures, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outlook for the New York market, as well as events in  
Japan, such as the possible compilation of a supplementary budget, 
remains uncertain,'' said Masatoshi Sato, manager of investment 
information at Kankaku Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 375.53 million shares changed hands on the First  
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 416.77 million 
issues on Friday and the lowest level since Feb. 18. Advancers 
exceeded declining stocks 615 to 532, with 144 issues closing 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on  
the first section picked up 5.12 points, or 0.39 percent, to 
1,297.19. The TOPIX closed down 10.10 points, or 0.78 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of telecommunications giant Nippon Telegraph and  
Telephone Corp. and its mobile unit, NTT Mobile Communications 
Network, were among the biggest gainers. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall market sentiment received a boost from a rise in U.S.  
shares on Friday and the dollar's climb against the yen in Asian 
trading today. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 92.81 points  
to close Friday at 10,559.74. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar moved slightly higher on  
short-covering as strength in the euro against the yen indirectly 
helped support the greenback in relation to the Japanese currency, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's strength was based on speculation the European  
Central bank may finally move to prop up the euro by intervening in 
foreign exchange markets to buy it. 
</P>
<P>
	But so far the bank has taken no such action to try to stem the  
euro's steady decline since its January launch. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.4800 percent from Friday's finish of 1.4900 percent, 
driving its price up to 99.38 yen from 99.21 yen. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
