<DOCNO> APW19990531.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 06:51:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Luyendyk Crashes in Final Indy 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Arie Luyendyk tapped the brakes and spun out  
of control. Amid the smoke from burning rubber, he slammed backward 
into the third-turn wall. 
</P>
<P>
	Not exactly the way the Flying Dutchman wanted to end his  
career. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 15th and final appearance in the Indianapolis 500,  
Luyendyk seemed to have everything going his way. He started from 
the pole, leading 63 laps, ready to enjoy his retirement as a 
three-time winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he got careless. Maybe a little greedy.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have to say to myself, `Why did I make a move like that?'''  
he asked. ``I really feel stupid right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk, in the lead after 117 of the 200 laps, made a move to  
the inside to pass Tyce Carlson. When Carlson eased off the 
throttle, Luyendyk had no room and as his right front wheel drew 
even with Carlson's left rear tire, the Dutchman's G Force Aurora 
began to wobble and shake. 
</P>
<P>
	In a matter of seconds, it was over. Luyendyk touched the  
brakes, spun around backward and hit the wall. He wound up 22nd, 
his worst finish at Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	So much for going out like John Elway or Michael Jordan in this  
year of the retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a trip to Victory Lane for a swig of milk, Luyendyk  
took a humbling golf cart ride back to the garage to mull his fate. 
A huge ovation from the crowd seemed to ease his anguish. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I got out of the car, the crowd was going nuts,'' he  
said. ``I was trying to take it all in. It's been great throughout 
the years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 45-year-old driver, who first won in 1990 and added a second  
Indy victory in 1997, announced before the Indy Racing League 
season that this would be his final ride. 
</P>
<P>
	The 500, where he holds almost every speed record and has won  
more money than any other driver, was his only race this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had the best car here today that I've ever had,'' he said.  
``The car gave me so much confidence. It was too good to be true, 
and this was probably part of my demise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the crash, Luyendyk climbed from the battered car and  
peered down as if he couldn't comprehend what had happened. As he 
walked toward the infield grass, he slapped his right glove on the 
hood of the red safety truck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I should have known better than to be racing the traffic that  
hard,'' he said. ``I probably just got too relaxed out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk felt he was crowded a bit in the turn by Carlson,  
forcing him to tap the brakes and send his car skidding into the 
wall. Television replays seemed to show the blame clearly belonged 
to the more experienced driver. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was my fault,'' Luyendyk conceded. ``I was the guy making  
the pass. There's no excuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carlson's radio went out during the race, which meant he  
couldn't communicate with his trackside spotters as Luyendyk 
approached. But the 28-year-old driver saw the approaching car in 
his mirror and tried to make room. 
</P>
<P>
	``I even went off the throttle,'' Carlson said. ``Arie's a great  
guy, and I never would have gotten in his way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk wavered a bit when asked if he might change his mind  
about retiring, but that was merely the competitor in the man 
showing through. He's looking forward to spending time with his 
family, in addition to working as a television analyst on IRL 
events and assisting the Treadway Racing team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to stick with my plan,'' he said. ``I'll be back  
here next year in another capacity and enjoy the race. ... But I 
know when I come back next year, I'll start kicking myself again 
for what happened here today.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
