<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> '99 Peach Crop Expected To Be Good / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT VALLEY, Ga. (AP) -- Thousands of plump peaches are  
pirouetting down conveyor belts and into crates at farms around 
central Georgia this month as workers prepare to ship what experts 
predict may be the best crop in five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The noise of workers and machinery processing the fruit is music  
to the ears of growers, who have been clobbered by extreme weather 
in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers are delighted with the early quality of the 1999  
harvest, which began two weeks ago. Spring weather was peachy for 
peaches -- warm and dry with abundant sunshine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have good quality and good color,'' said Bill McGehee, a  
partner at the Big Six Farm near Fort Valley. ``Peaches are like 
humans. They need sunshine. Sun is what colors the fruit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After cleaning, grading, sorting and packaging, workers load the  
peaches into refrigerated trailers for their trip to market. On a 
recent day, Big Six was preparing shipments for Puerto Rico, 
Canada, New Jersey and South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Fort Valley is located in the heart of the Georgia's peach  
growing area, and signs of the importance of the $50 million crop 
are everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Peaches are emblazoned on everything, from the water tower that  
looms over town to the sign in front of the Peach Industrial Park. 
</P>
<P>
	When it's a bad year for peaches, everyone in the area feels it  
economically. In 1996, growers lost 92 percent of the crop to a 
series of late spring freezes. 
</P>
<P>
	Cold weather isn't a problem this year, but some growers say the  
rest of the harvest -- which stretches from mid-May to mid-August -- 
won't turn out well unless the state gets some much needed rain. 
Central Georgia is five to six inches short of rain this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Kathy Taylor, a peach specialist with the University of  
Georgia Extension Service, is optimistic about the crop. She 
predicts this year will be the best since 1994, despite a shortage 
of chill hours during the warm winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Trees need temperatures below 45 degrees for several hundred  
hours during the winter to produce a crop in the spring. Growers 
helped offset the lack of chill hours with a chemical substitute. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Agricultural Statistics Service rates the crop as 35  
percent excellent, 28 percent good, 17 percent fair, 11 percent 
poor and 9 percent very poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a better-than-average crop,'' said grower Chop Evans  
of Evans Farm, a major producer. ``The quality is good to 
excellent. The dry weather has certainly hurt us a little in size, 
but what you lose in size you gain in taste.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They taste great,'' added Betty Hotchkiss, spokeswoman for  
Lane Packing Co., another major producer. ``The sunshine we're 
having gives them a great flavor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGehee said he is optimistic about the future of Georgia  
peaches. His farm grows 30 to 40 varieties. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're seeing a real appreciation for the taste of Eastern  
peaches,'' he said. ``We feel we've had taste all along, but 
because of varying weather patterns, they didn't always look good. 
Now we feel we have the taste and the good appearance.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:39:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Trial Resumes on Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Microsoft Corp.'s trial resumes for the  
final phase of testimony, the government will urge the judge to 
focus on the software company's aggressive behavior toward 
competitors earlier this decade and on its dominance today. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, though, wants U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield  
Jackson to look to the future, when Microsoft believes its Windows 
software will face unprecedented competition from fledgling 
technologies 
</P>
<P>
	The antitrust trial was scheduled to resume Tuesday after a  
13-week recess and despite secret efforts to settle the case. Key 
differences remain, such as how Microsoft can continue adding new 
technology to its the Windows operating system without undercutting 
rivals offering similar software products. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft must convince Jackson that federal intervention is  
unnecessary to maintain the robust high-tech industry robust. The 
company also must minimize the ill effects of its past actions on 
some of its competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	The government and Microsoft each have identified three  
witnesses who will testify during this phase of the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin Fisher, an economist who testified previously for the  
government, was to take the stand again Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's most important witness will be Garry Norris, an  
IBM Corp. manager who will describe pressure Microsoft allegedly 
exerted on IBM to sacrifice its rival OS/2 operating-system 
software during the early 1990s. That software competed directly 
with Windows until its popularity waned in late 1994 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the last courtroom testimony, America Online Inc.  
finalized its $10 billion purchase of Netscape Communications 
Corp., the Internet pioneer whose Web browser software competes 
with Microsoft's own Internet Explorer. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice lawyer David Boies has said Microsoft's emphasis on the  
merger was a sideshow, but the judge remarked previously that the 
deal ``might be a very significant change in the playing field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that AOL, as the world's largest Internet  
provider, could help revive Netscape's popularity as a browser, and 
that other alliances would encourage development of handheld, 
wireless devices that do not use Windows and could displace 
Microsoft's importance. 
</P>
<P>
	In a deposition last month with AOL Chairman Steve Case,  
Microsoft also suggested that future high-speed Internet 
connections for consumers threaten to reduce the industry's 
reliance on Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Case has taken an unusually high-profile role in recent weeks  
lobbying Congress and federal regulators to force cable companies 
to allow their subscribers to use his AOL software with those 
companies' ultra-fast data pipelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Software used across such high-speed networks typically can go  
with whatever operating system a consumer has on his computer. 
Microsoft argues that, in effect, the Internet itself becomes a 
competing software platform, threatening to make Windows less 
important. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also contends that fast Internet connections allow  
consumers to more easily retrieve even large software programs, 
which could contradict government charges that Netscape was 
prevented from being able to adequately distribute its rival 
browser software. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 08:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> All Nippon Airlines Unveils Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's All Nippon Airways Co. will cut 10 percent  
of its staff and establish a new discount airline as part of a 
broad reform strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's second largest airline said it would cut its  
28,000-person global work force by 10 percent by March 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the cuts will be made at the ANA parent company, where  
1,700 jobs will be trimmed through early retirement and by limiting 
new hiring. The other cuts will be made at subsidiaries and 
affiliates, though the company did not say where. 
</P>
<P>
	A nearly two-year-long economic crisis has curbed demand for  
plane tickets in Asia, and a stubborn recession has dampened travel 
demand at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the establishment of new discount airlines such as  
Skymark Airlines Co. has put pressure on big flyers to cut fares. 
</P>
<P>
	``The business environment in Japan is extremely difficult right  
now,'' ANA President and CEO Kichisaburo Nomura said in the 
statement. ``Many of the reforms we will undertake are going to be 
challenging, even painful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's salary will be cut by 25 percent, the company  
announced, though it didn't say how much he would make. 
</P>
<P>
	ANA will set up its own low-cost airline this year that will  
focus on routes out of the western Japan city of Osaka, the company 
said without providing details. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement follows a dismal earnings report from ANA last  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	ANA suffered a net loss of $54.46 million, deeper than its  
year-earlier loss of $22.15 million. The loss stemmed from higher 
operating costs and a one-time charge to pay workers who retired 
early under an existing plan to cut jobs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
