<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lyme, Conn., Skeptical of Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LYME, Conn. (AP) -- In the wooded enclave that gave Lyme disease  
its name, people are greeting a new vaccine with a dose of New 
England skepticism. 
</P>
<P>
	If the new LYMErix vaccine is going to be successful anywhere,  
Connecticut ought to be the place, since it has the nation's 
highest rate of the disease -- 105 cases per 100,000 people last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	But five months after the vaccine came on the market, doctors  
said people aren't exactly lining up in Lyme disease country as 
summer approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've lived here for years and years, and I think you'll find  
that most people who've lived here for years aren't that excited 
about it,'' said First Selectman Ralph F. Eno Jr., the top elected 
official in this town of 2,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Resident Polly Murray, who wrote ``The Widening Circle'' about  
her family's battle with the disease, said she fears the vaccine 
might aggravate her arthritis, a lingering effect of the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are a little bit cautious,'' she said. ``It is a first  
vaccine. They haven't tested it for children and the elderly, and I 
think everybody has to decide for themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the reluctance may be the fact that the vaccine is  
administered in three doses over a year and offers no guarantee 
against being infected. 
</P>
<P>
	If caught early, Lyme disease, spread by a tiny bug called a  
deer tick, can be cured with antibiotics. But if it goes 
undiagnosed, as is often the case, it can cause arthritis, heart 
irregularities, facial paralysis and other disabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The vaccine provides 50 percent protection after the first two  
doses and 78 percent protection after all three doses. Since it 
isn't known how long protection lasts, booster shots may be 
necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the cost. LYMErix, marketed by SmithKline Beecham,  
costs about $150 for the course of injections. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Dr. Allen C. Steere, who first identified the disease in  
the 1970s and was the primary investigator on LYMErix, said he can 
understand why people might be hesitant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, an area like Lyme, Connecticut, is an area where  
you would consider vaccination,'' said Steere, chief of 
rheumatology and immunology at the Tufts School of Medicine in 
Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it really becomes a personal decision as to whether a  
person wants to take a preventative approach, or is thinking, `I've 
lived here 20 years and I've lived with this risk before,''' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steere has not been vaccinated himself, saying he is a city  
dweller who spends much of his time in a laboratory. But he 
recommends it for patients in high-risk areas who are often 
outdoors. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Vijay Sikand, a leading Lyme disease specialist from East  
Lyme who tested the vaccine, said part of the problem may lie with 
doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``As with anything that's new, patients and physicians need to  
be familiar with it before they reach a comfort level,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most states have registered cases of the disease, but it is most  
prevalent in the Northeast, upper Midwest and Pacific coastal 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	The disease came to Steere's attention in 1975 when mothers in  
Lyme, notably Murray, insisted there was an outbreak of arthritis 
in their children. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyme disease comes from bacteria carried by the deer tick. The  
ticks transmit the infection from animals like deer and mice to 
humans. Early symptoms include a rash, headache, fever, fatigue, 
joint and muscle aches and a stiff neck. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 128,000 cases have been reported in the United States  
since 1982. But with the range of symptoms so wide, it is often 
misdiagnosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration approved LYMErix for people  
ages 15 to 70. SmithKline Beecham spokesman Richard Koenig said 
demand for the vaccine -- about 200,000 units around the country -- 
has not been disappointing. The company has registered $18 million 
in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on target with our expectations to date,'' Koenig said.  
</P>
<P>
	But analyst Michael Krensavage of Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co.  
says the revenues so far may result from an initial buildup of 
inventory, rather than a true gauge of sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody on Wall Street is expecting it to power SmithKline's  
earnings. It will be a small niche product,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Terrence W. Norchi, a specialist in internal medicine and an  
analyst with the Wall Street firm Sanford C. Bernstein, said there 
are still too many unknowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Four or five years from now, if we see a decrease in the  
incidence of Lyme, then people may start lining up for it,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, residents of Lyme are in no hurry, said Eno.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real small town,'' he said. ``People make up their own  
minds.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 04:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
