<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	While the South sizzles and the Northeast bakes today,  
thunderstorms threatened the central Plains and Gulf Coast, where 
hail and isolated tornadoes also were possible. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure was continuing its grip over the East, bringing  
fair to partly cloudy skies and very warm temperatures from New 
England southward into the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mississippi, Tennessee and Ohio Valleys were expected to  
have scattered afternoon thundershowers, prompted by afternoon haze 
and very moist air over the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Florida also was predicted to be stormy.  
</P>
<P>
	A cold front pushing through the northern Plains was forecast to  
scatter showers and thunderstorms from the western Great Lakes, 
southwestward to the central Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms in Nebraska, Kansas, Missouri and Oklahoma were expected  
to have the potential to become severe, with damaging winds, large 
hail and isolated tornadoes possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Further West, a cold front hanging over the central Rockies also  
may bring showers and thundershowers when the front collides with 
warmer air from the South. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, a tornado touched down a few miles from the  
governor's mansion in Cheyenne, Wyo., damaged a home and uprooted 
trees but caused no injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Pacific Northwest today, a cold front approaching from  
the northwest was forecast to bring showers to Washington, Idaho 
and western Montana. The Southwest should remain mostly fair and 
dry. 
</P>
<P>
	The high on Sunday in the U.S. mainland was 99 degrees in Del  
Rio, Texas. The low was 23 degrees in Codey, Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's forecast highs ranged from the 50s and 60s in the  
northern Plains and northern Rockies, to the 90s and 100s in the 
desert Southwest and southern Plains; and in the 70s and 80s in the 
central Plains, southern Rockies, California, central Plains and in 
the East, from Pennsylvania and New Jersey, southward to North 
Carolina. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
