<DOCNO> APW19990531.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 03:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Wins Sprint Double Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Maurice Greene has a cozy relationship going  
with the track at Hayward Field. He'll have a rival for its 
affections next month in Michael Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene won the 100 and 200 at the Prefontaine Classic on Sunday,  
sweeping the marquee sprint events for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this track loves me, and I love this track. I love  
this city,'' Greene said after his magnificent double thrilled the 
crowd of 12,247. ``We're going to have a lot of good times here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The good times roll next month, when Greene and Johnson are  
expected to compete in a 200 showdown at the USA Championships, the 
qualifying meet for the World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	As world champion in the 100, Greene does not have to qualify in  
that event. Neither does Johnson in the 400, since he also is the 
world champion. Thus, both will concentrate on the 200 for the 
national championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson easily won the 400 Sunday, and Marion Jones was dominant  
in the women's sprints. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pre also produced another outstanding mile, with 10 runners  
breaking the four-minute barrier, led by Kenya's Noah Ngeny. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, ranked No. 1 in the world in the 100 meters and the 1997  
world champion, won the 100 in 9.84 seconds, a time that equaled 
Canadian Donovan Bailey's world record but was negated by a wind of 
7.83 mph, well over the allowable of 4.473 for record purposes. The 
clocking has been bettered only six other times. ``Easy,'' was all 
he said when asked to describe the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty minutes later, Greene won the 200 in 20.06, a time that  
would have broken the meet record of 20.15 by Johnson in 1995, if 
not for the wind. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, with slightly less wind, Greene ran even faster,  
winning the 100 in 9.79 and the 200 in 19.88. Still, the wind was 
over the limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 200 was a little challenging, because I was winded after  
the 100,'' Greene said. ``But I'm in good enough shape where I can 
go back-to-back like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, ranked No. 1 in the world in the 400 eight times, beat  
world No. 2 Mark Richardson of Britain by nearly 10 meters at 
44.51, matching his best time of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wind was blowing hard down the backstretch, so running a  
good time today was pretty much impossible,'' said Johnson, who 
said he thought he was in shape to break 44 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, track and field's woman athlete of the year the past two  
years, was competing for the first time in more than a month. But 
she won the 200 by about nine meters in 21.81, the fastest time in 
the world this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to go through the season undefeated because I've yet to  
do that,'' said Jones, who lost only once last year, in her final 
competition of the season, in the long jump. 
</P>
<P>
	While the near-capacity crowd roared its approval for the  
sprinters, it saved its loudest cheers for the men's milers. 
</P>
<P>
	The milers went through a quarter-mile in 56:00, then the  
20-year-old Ngeny took the field through a 1:56.02 half-mile and 
was timed at 2:54.9 for three-quarters, before pulling away down 
the final straightway and winning at 3:52.09, the fastest mile in 
the world this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Kevin Sullivan, the former Michigan star, finished  
second at 3:53.70, and Adam Goucher, the 1999 national indoor 3,000 
champion and 1998 NCAA 5,000 winner for Colorado, was third at 
3:54.17. It was his career best and the best by an American this 
year. Americans Karl Paranya, fifth at 3:54.83, and Steve Holman, 
eighth at 3:55.13, also cracked the four-minute barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Wade, who came into the meet as the world leader in the  
110 hurdles, lowered his best time to 13.12. Reggie Torian, the 
runner-up at 13.17, also went under Wade's previous leading time of 
13.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade said he held back a little off the blocks because of two  
false starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It kind of threw me off a little bit, but after the third  
hurdle I got into the race and I started running,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-event program produced three other 1999 American leaders.  
</P>
<P>
	Regina Jacobs, a seven-time national champion, won the women's  
1,500 meters at 4:07.90. Lance Deal, the American record-holder in 
the hammer throw, won at 261 feet, 2 inches, and Bob Kennedy, the 
American record-holder at 5,000 meters, finished third at 13:18.83, 
behind Kenya's Luke Kipkosgei (13:17.15) and Mexico's Pablo Olmedo 
(13:18.21). 
</P>
<P>
	Deal, coming back from surgery last summer on his broken right  
foot, had the handle of his hammer break during his second throw. 
It cut his right index finger, but he was otherwise uninjured, and 
went on to overtake Kevin McMahon, who finished second with a 
personal-best 260 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nationals is going to be a dogfight,'' Deal said. ``It'll be  
fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were two other surprises. Lawrence Johnson, the former  
American record-holder in the pole vault, beat current 
record-holder Jeff Hartwig, 18-8 1/4 to 18-4 1/2, and Andy Bloom, the 
former NCAA shot put and discus champion from Wake Forest, beat 
1999 world leader John Godina, 220-0 to 217-8. 
</P>
<P>
	w  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
