<HEADLINE> Examples of Special-Interest Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Examples of members of Congress who accepted recent free trips  
paid by special interests. 
</P>
<P>
	The list includes the congressman's name, the cost of the trip,  
the location, the sponsor, the amount of contributions from the 
sponsor's political action committee to the congressman in 1997-98, 
the amount the sponsor spent on lobbying in 1998 and the 
legislation the sponsor is interested in. 

</P>
<P>
	Rep. Martin Olav Sabo, D-Minn.: trip cost $1830; Kona, Hawaii;  
American Association of Airport Executives; sponsor PAC 
contributions to Sabo, $2,000; association lobbying expenditure 
$175,296; issues, airport construction money and increased user 
fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich.: trip cost $3,113; Palm Springs,  
Calif.; United States Telephone Association; sponsor PAC 
contributions to Bonior $2,000; association lobbying expenditure 
$1.3 million; issues, telecommunications law revision and reform of 
the Federal Communications Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Mac Collins, R-Ga.: trip cost $322; Las Vegas, Nev.,  
Consumer Electonics Manufacturers Association; sponsor PAC 
contributions to Collins $0; lobbying expenditure $560,000; issues, 
export-trade and Y2K computer problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Kay Granger, R-Texas; trip cost $8,366; Greece;  
Lockheed-Martin; sponsor PAC contributions to Granger, $10,000; 
lobbying expenditure $5.9 million; issues, defense appropriations, 
product sales, general defense issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash.; cost of trip, $7,387; India;  
Confederation of Indian Industry; contributions $0; lobbying $0; 
issues: international trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ron Packard, R-Calif.; cost of trip, $8,366; Kona, Hawaii;  
American Association of Airport Executives; sponsor PAC 
contributions to Packard, $4500; lobbying expenditure $175,296; 
airport construction money and user fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Harold Rogers, R-Ky., cost of trip $2,481; Palm Springs,  
Calif.; United States Telephone Association; sponsor PAC 
contributions to Rogers, $2000; lobbying expenditure, $1.3 million; 
issues, telecommunication law revision and reform of the Federal 
Communications Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb.; cost of trip $4,807; Orlando, Fla.;  
American Bankers Association; sponsor PAC contributions to Hagel, 
$0; lobbying expenditures $4.6 million; issues, banking overhaul 
and bankruptcy. 

  	   	
