<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Horses Don't Win Triple Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The difference has been as short as a nose or as  
long as 15 lengths, but the result was the same -- a Triple Crown 
bid spoiled. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five horses have won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness,  
with 11 going on to racing immortality. Fourteen joined the 
bittersweet list of near misses by failing to win the final leg of 
the series, the 1 1/2-mile Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no asterisk next to the winners in the charts of those  
14 Belmonts, noting a Triple Crown bid was foiled in the process. 
And there won't be one Saturday should any one of about a dozen 
challengers upend Charismatic as he tries to become the first 
Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	But should the winner be anyone other than Charismatic, the  
mantle of spoiler will fall across his shoulders as surely as the 
blanket of white carnations. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Chris McCarron played the part of spoiler when he  
guided Touch Gold past Silver Charm in the final 50 yards to win 
the Belmont by three-quarters of a length. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't consciously assume the role of trying to be a  
spoiler. My job was to get the best out of my mount. I was painted 
as a spoiler after the fact,'' McCarron said. ``I felt like I was 
just doing my job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I received hate mail. `How dare you? Racing hasn't had a  
Triple Crown winner in 20-some years. How could you do this?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Like McCarron, those who have been involved in the end of a  
Triple Crown run don't look at it that way -- they were just trying 
to win one of the most prestigious and richest horse races in the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years before Secretariat's magical run through the classics  
in 1973, another hugely popular horse, Canonero II, was poised for 
a shot at the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter Blum, now a racing steward in Florida, was aboard 35-1  
shot Pass Catcher when he upended the Triple Crown bid of the pride 
of Venezuela before a record crowd of 82,694 at Belmont Park. Just 
a week earlier, Pass Catcher had run a strong second to Bold 
Reasoning in the Jersey Derby, and Blum knew his horse was ready 
for an upset. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone was looking for a Triple Crown but me,'' Blum  
recalled. ``I think all of Venezuela turned out at Belmont that 
day, waving flags and cheering for Canonero. It was a great scene. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't ever remember being called a spoiler, but if that's  
what they want to call me now, fine. My job was to go out there and 
win the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's 131st running of the Belmont, Charismatic becomes  
the 26th horse with a chance to win the Triple Crown. Since 
Affirmed's '78 Triple Crown, the year after Seattle Slew won it, 
six horses have won the Derby and Preakness, but flopped in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	The past three times, the horse bidding for the Triple Crown  
finished second. In 1989, Sunday Silence was 8 lengths behind rival 
Easy Goer; and the last two Belmonts saw Bob Baffert-trained colts 
fall just short of racing immortality -- Silver Charm was edged by 
Touch Gold and Real Quiet was nosed out by Victory Gallop in '98. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1961, Carry Back finished seventh in his Triple Crown bid, 15  
lengths behind the winner, Sherluck. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Hall of Fame trainer D. Wayne Lukas saddles  
Charismatic knowing spoilers are lurking everywhere, from the star 
filly Silverbulletday in Baffert's barn, to Derby and Preakness 
runner-up Menifee to the Allen Jerkens-trained Best of Luck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure Wayne does not like the fact that I'm going to run  
her, but if it was me going for the Triple Crown, you'd see five 
Lukas horses in there,'' Baffert said. ``As a trainer last year, I 
was hoping everybody would stay home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert finds himself in a unique situation for this Belmont.  
Bob and Beverly Lewis own Silver Charm and Charismatic, and there 
was talk the trainer might keep Silverbulletday out of the Belmont 
to give the Lewises a better shot at winning the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wouldn't do anything like that. We just want to win the  
Belmont, it's not about spoiling,'' Baffert said, the ``we'' 
including Silverbulletday's owner Mike Pegram. ``I've told Bob 
Lewis we're not trying to spoil your deal. The Triple Crown is made 
so if you are the best you shouldn't worry about anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Bob Lewis welcomes all challengers.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're delighted to see a full field because, if we win, then  
there will be no one on Sunday morning saying we didn't beat much 
of a field,'' Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several jockeys have been involved on both sides of the Triple  
Crown chase, notably McCarron and Gary Stevens. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarron's Triple Crown dreams aboard Alysheba in 1987 were  
foiled by Bet Twice, ridden by Craig Perret. Ten years later, 
McCarron played spoiler aboard Touch Gold, beating out Stevens, who 
was on Silver Charm. Last year, Stevens spoiled Real Quiet's Triple 
Crown bid with his win aboard Victory Gallop. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a great responsibility to my betting public, the  
owners I'm riding for and the trainer,'' McCarron said. ``I 
wouldn't be doing my job if I did anything less than try to win 100 
percent of the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Day, who will be aboard Menifee in Saturday's Belmont, gets  
his second chance to play spoiler -- he was aboard Easy Goer in the 
'89 Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea of stopping a Triple Crown was not forefront in my  
mind,'' said Day, even though Easy Goer was second to Sunday 
Silence in the Derby and Preakness, just like Menifee has been to 
Charismatic this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wanted to win the race because I contended all along  
that Easy Goer was the better horse. He was sent over in good form, 
and we got the victory very handily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What about Saturday?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure (trainer) Elliott Walden will get Menifee up to the  
race and give him an opportunity,'' Day said, ``and Lord willing, 
we'll upset the apple cart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Day knows a Triple Crown winner would be a gigantic boost to a  
troubled industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're crying out for one,'' he said, ``but given the  
opportunity to run by him, I want to win the Belmont.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Hancock, a co-owner of Menifee, gets his chance to turn  
the Triple Crown tables 10 years after his Sunday Silence lost to 
Easy Goer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to spoil anybody's Triple Crown because I know how low  
it makes you feel, or at least it did me,'' Hancock said. ``But 
I've always thought things kind of go full circle. Pat Day was on 
Easy Goer and beat us. Kind of ironic he's on this horse.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 11:00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Takes Steps on Path to Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Six months after the Olympic  
corruption scandal broke, the IOC sets out this week on a path of 
reform that could reshape the 105-year-old organization. 
</P>
<P>
	A special task force, whose members include Henry Kissinger and  
Peter Ueberroth, meets for the first time Tuesday to begin 
rebuilding the International Olympic Committee after its worst 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Convinced the Salt Lake City bribery scandal and its aftershocks  
are finally behind them, IOC leaders are now taking the first 
concrete steps toward the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``This meeting is only the beginning,'' IOC president Juan  
Antonio Samaranch said in an interview Monday. ``We cannot expect 
any kind of resolution this week. Our aim is to have final 
decisions by the end of the year. If that's not possible, then by 
the spring of next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the reforms would not be dictated by pressure  
from Arizona Sen. John McCain and other congressional critics who 
have threatened to enact legislation that would punish the IOC 
financially. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can do what they desire,'' Samaranch said. ``But I  
repeat: The IOC is run by the IOC members. ... We highly respect 
the Senate of the United States, but I am sure they also will 
respect the IOC.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six IOC members were expelled in March and four resigned after  
being accused of receiving cash or other improper inducements 
during Salt Lake's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC ethics commission, formed after the Salt Lake scandal,  
met last week and drafted a conduct code for IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the reform commission -- called IOC 2000 -- will begin  
examining ways of overhauling the IOC's structure and the way host 
cities are chosen, including a radical suggestion to abolish the 
bidding process. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally planned as a group of 20-24 people, the commission  
has expanded to 80 members -- 44 from the IOC and 36 from outside. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC leaders have rejected critics' complaints that the body,  
chaired by Samaranch, is too large to work effectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more people participating in the decision process, the  
more likely the reforms will pass in the general assembly,'' IOC 
board member Jacques Rogge said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is divided into three groups: the composition and  
structure of the IOC, the role of the IOC, and the selection of 
host cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel examining the IOC structure, viewed as the most  
significant group, is chaired by Italian IOC member and former Rome 
Mayor Franco Carraro. 
</P>
<P>
	German executive board member Thomas Bach leads the group  
dealing with the IOC's role, while American IOC vice president 
Anita DeFrantz runs the panel on site selection. 
</P>
<P>
	A 26-member executive committee, divided equally among IOC and  
non-IOC members, will be appointed Tuesday to oversee the reform 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the most prominent names of non-IOC members on the  
commission are Kissinger, the former U.S. Secretary of State; 
Ueberroth, chief organizer of the 1984 Los Angeles Games; Italian 
industrialist Giovanni Agnelli; former U.N. Secretary General 
Boutros Boutros-Ghali of Egypt; NBC Sports chief Dick Ebersol; and 
Nobel Peace Price winner and former Costa Rica president Oscar 
Arias Sanchez. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is to submit a preliminary report June 20 at the  
next IOC general assembly in Seoul, South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Final recommendations are to be prepared by the end of October,  
submitted to all IOC members for review in November and adopted at 
a general assembly in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the reforms expected to be considered are changes in the  
way the IOC chooses its members, including new age limits and 
possible term limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC's traditional system of membership for almost life terms  
is expected to be abolished. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the IOC raised its age limit from 75 to 80 to allow  
Samaranch to gain another term as president. Now, the IOC is 
expected to consider reducing the limit to as low as 70. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the scandal, the IOC has imposed restrictions on  
the bidding and selection process for the 2006 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC members are banned from inspecting the candidate cities and  
bid officials are forbidden from visiting IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	A panel will reduce the field of six European cities to two  
finalists in Seoul on June 19. On the same day, the full assembly 
will choose the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz said the IOC commission should consider scrapping the  
bid process and let the IOC decide where it wants to stage the 
games and negotiate directly with that city. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could say, `We really want the games in city X,' and see  
what would they need, what it would cost,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
