<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schilling Is Complete Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- In the era of long balls and sore arms, Curt  
Schilling is making a case for baseball to evolve. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe those in charge of the game should call an emergency  
meeting to fix a glaring oversight in the way stats are kept. The 
first order of business: Finding a new name for the complete game. 
</P>
<P>
	How about a ``Schilling?''  
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Phillies' ace is unique in this era of  
five-inning starters and career-ending arm injuries. The sheer 
amazement inspired by his five consecutive complete games says a 
lot about how much baseball has changed. 
</P>
<P>
	It also speaks volumes about Schilling's quest to return the  
game to its simple, utterly pure roots. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do know that I run into a lot more guys that have a smile on  
their face when get pulled after six innings winning 4-1 than guys 
that are angry,'' Schilling said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once again, Schilling lived up to his menacing aura with a  
four-hit shutout for his fifth consecutive complete game Friday 
night. He has six complete games this season, not only leading the 
majors individually but surpassing every other team in both 
leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why we have no intention of ever letting him go,'' said  
Phillies manager Terry Francona. ``That's why teams are clamoring 
for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling (8-2) did more than pitch his first shutout of the  
season and 13th of his career in the Phillies' 2-0 victory over 
Colorado. He did so by blowing away Larry Walker, Dante Bichette 
and Vinny Castilla in the ninth inning with pitches approaching 100 
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	After striking out Walker with a 96-mph fastball and winning a  
13-pitch battle with Bichette with a 98-mph heater, Schilling 
struck out Castilla on three pitches. The last one was a merciless 
93-mph splitter, his 135th of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	So much for pitch counts.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had a ton left,'' Schilling said. ``I try to reach back in  
the ninth inning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling's remarkable adrenaline rush came less than a week  
after the worst ninth-inning collapse of his career. Last Sunday, 
in New York, Schilling inexplicably squandered a 4-0 lead in a 5-4 
loss to the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, it motivated me,'' said Schilling, who struck out nine  
and walked one. ``How could it not? To lose a game like that all by 
yourself is tough. It was a tough five days for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Francona took some heat for leaving Schilling on the mound in  
the ninth against the Mets. John Olerud completed New York's 
comeback with a game-winning single on Schilling's 138th pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pitch counts, for the most part, are incredibly overrated,''  
Schilling said. ``I've thrown 100 pitches and felt like it was 150 
because I made the 10 toughest pitches at the end. You have to fail 
to figure out how to do it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling made those comments nearly two weeks ago in a national  
conference call which he also used as a forum to blast Phillies 
ownership for its thriftiness. Not everything about him is old 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies, 24-24 after losing to the Rockies on Sunday,  
entered the season with a $30.36 million payroll that was the 
fourth-lowest in the National League. Schilling urged the team to 
spend more money or take their pick between trading him and selling 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Goaded to expound after his latest masterpiece, Schilling  
refused. All he would say was, ``This is a great baseball town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling's frequent squabbles with management don't interfere  
with the throwback persona he's crafted on the mound. Few 
contemporaries share his zeal for completing games. 
</P>
<P>
	In the days of knickers and mitten-like gloves, complete games  
were the rule. ``Old Hoss'' Radbourn completed all 73 of his starts 
in 1884, going 60-12 with a 1.38 ERA at a time when home runs were 
almost as unheard of as helmet cams. 
</P>
<P>
	In the modern era, the Phillies' Robin Roberts pitched 28  
straight complete games in 1953 and finished the season with 33. 
Steve Carlton's career-high was 30 in 1972, that awesome season in 
which he had 27 of the Phillies' 59 victories. 
</P>
<P>
	How times have changed. Schilling led the NL with 15 complete  
games last season, and Baltimore's Scott Erickson led the AL with 
11. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not something you teach,'' Schilling said. ```It's  
something you're raised with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only two other pitchers this decade have had five consecutive  
complete games -- Pat Hentgen for Toronto in 1996 and Philadelphia's 
Tommy Greene in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling goes for his sixth straight complete game on Thursday  
afternoon against the Giants, something no one else has done this 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll expect nothing less.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
