<DOCNO> APW19990531.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 00:30:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Police Shoot Homeless Woman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Every day Margaret Mitchell pushed her  
grocery cart up trendy La Brea Avenue, passing expensive antique 
shops and en-vogue restaurants, looking for all the world like she 
was going somewhere important. 
</P>
<P>
	The 54-year-old mentally ill woman didn't really have any  
appointments. She didn't even have a home. But she was a fixture on 
this thoroughfare where a cup of coffee costs $3.50 and doorknobs 
sell for $50. 
</P>
<P>
	She was well-groomed, didn't panhandle and rarely spoke, say  
those who knew her. When merchants tried to give her food, she 
refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Mitchell no longer strolls along La Brea. On May 21, after  
living on this street for more than a year, she was shot to death 
by a bicycle policeman new to the beat. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Larrigan, 27, and his partner, Kathy Clark, 29, had asked  
if Mrs. Mitchell's cart was stolen. Larrigan, with five years' 
experience under his gun belt, said he felt his life was threatened 
when the 5-foot-1 woman thrust a screwdriver at him. 
</P>
<P>
	He jumped to avoid her, fell to one knee and fired one shot into  
her chest, police said. She died at a nearby hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI, the Police Commission and the LAPD are separately  
investigating an incident that has taken on racial overtones. Mrs. 
Mitchell was black; Larrigan is Hispanic. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Police Chief Bernard Parks said the officers  
appeared to have done nothing wrong, and he blasted accusations of 
bigotry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to carry the burden of racism in the country  
of the United States for the last 200 years and place it on those 
officers' shoulders,'' said Parks, who is black. 
</P>
<P>
	Advocates for the homeless and the mentally ill also are using  
Mrs. Mitchell's death as an emblem for their causes. And on La 
Brea, white and black merchants who knew Mrs. Mitchell are 
incensed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were all horrified. It's just so stupid,'' said Avril  
Clinch, as she wept inside her employer's antique shop. ``That 
woman never did any harm to anyone. And she gets shot to death over 
a shopping cart?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philippe Tie, her colleague at Chateau de la Companie, said he  
saw the woman every morning. ``At first, I didn't even know she was 
homeless,'' he said. ``She was clean. She wore a different outfit 
every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watching her stride down the street, head bent, ``she looked  
like she always had a purpose,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Next door, at the popular La Brea Bakery, manager Lora Davis saw  
Mrs. Mitchell the morning she died. Usually, the woman slept on the 
sidewalk or the bus bench fronting a nearby phone company office. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was talking to herself,'' Davis said. ``That was the first  
time I'd ever heard her speak.'' At closing time, Davis and her 
employees often stand at the back door and give away leftover 
bread. Mrs. Mitchell never came. 
</P>
<P>
	``She never asked for anything,'' Davis said. ``It's just so  
frightening to think that anyone would get shot over waving a 
screwdriver. None of it makes sense to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Parks said witnesses substantiate Larrigan's assertion  
that Mrs. Mitchell lunged at him. Attorney Leo Terrell, who 
represents son Richard Mitchell, said there are several witnesses 
who say the woman posed no threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Mitchell has said that his mother was a college-educated  
former bank employee whose mental health began deteriorating over 
the past few years. She heard voices, her son said, but refused 
help. 
</P>
<P>
	She lived off-and-on with him and his wife until about a year  
ago, he said. Under state law, a person cannot be unwillingly 
institutionalized unless they pose a threat to themselves or 
others. His mother was not violent, Mitchell said. But he was 
frustrated at not being able to force her into treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Increasingly paranoid, she preferred the street.  
</P>
<P>
	Shaun Pepper inhabits the same stretch of La Brea that Mrs.  
Mitchell did. He usually saw her twice a day, he said, but it took 
months to get the subdued woman to smile at him. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was a refined lady. She never bothered no one,'' said  
Pepper, sitting on the corner of Fourth Street, where a shrine of 
flowers, candles and a shopping cart mark the intersection where 
she died on a Friday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	If Pepper didn't see Mrs. Mitchell on any given day, he went out  
looking. 
</P>
<P>
	``Females are not the weaker sex,'' he said. ``But they really  
are preyed on out here on the streets. We watch out for each 
other.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
