<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	New Offer in Union-Car Hauler Talks  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Less than an hour before a strike  
deadline, company negotiators submitted a new economic offer late 
Monday to try to head off a strike by Teamsters against companies 
that haul new cars from factories to showrooms. Teamster Chip Ross 
said the union was reviewing the offer, but gave no further 
details. A union source described the new offers as 
``comprehensive'' and that it likely would take time beyond the 
12:02 a.m. EDT Tuesday strike deadline to fully evaluate it. No 
details of the offer were provided. 

</P>
<P>
	More Kosovo Talks Planned  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Russia's Balkans envoy Viktor  
Chernomyrdin announced plans to travel to Germany tomorrow for more 
talks on the crisis in Kosovo. He was to meet in Bonn with U.S. 
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Finnish President 
Martti Ahtisaari, a spokesman said. On Wednesday they are expected 
to fly to Belgrade for more talks with Milosevic, according to 
Chernomyrdin and German officials. The Yugoslav government 
reiterated Monday that it accepts principles set forth by the Group 
of Eight major powers for ending the Kosovo conflict. But 
Milosevic's latest statement still fell short of Western demands 
for the makeup of a peacekeeping force in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Israeli: U.S. Meddled in Election  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A senior adviser to outgoing Prime Minister  
Benjamin Netanyahu accused the Clinton administration Monday of 
aiding Netanyahu's downfall. David Bar-Illan said the State 
Department ran its own campaign of disinformation against the 
premier while the White House encouraged financial contributions to 
Netanyahu's main opponent -- and eventual successor -- Ehud Barak. A 
spokesman for Clinton's National Security Council said Monday that 
``the Clinton administration in no way became involved in the 
internal politics of the Israeli election.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Astronauts Fix Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Astronauts fixed a broken radio,  
replaced flawed battery packs and installed foam mufflers over 
noisy fans Monday aboard the new international space station. They 
launched into the repairs within minutes of entering the complex 
late Sunday. The astronauts have until Thursday to finish the 
repairs and unload 1 1/2 tons of tools, spare parts, computers, water 
and clothes into the station's two compartments. Discovery will 
pull away Thursday night and return to Earth on Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	Students To Return to Columbine  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Columbine students were to return to the  
school Tuesday for the first time since the shootings to retrieve 
purses, glasses, credit cards, keys and other belongings left 
behind during the attack. Students will be escorted in groups of 
15. Some areas remain off-limits because of the ongoing 
investigation. The return is expected to be emotional so counselors 
will be available, and parents have been invited. Students Eric 
Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 12 classmates and a teacher in a 
shooting spree on April 20. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Preparing for Y2K  
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Airlines said Monday they're  
stepping up efforts to ensure that planes from poor countries 
aren't grounded by the so-called Y2K bug. The International Air 
Transport Association, an airline industry group voted to commit 
$8.5 million to helping airlines in poor countries prepare. The 
concern is over how airlines and airports will react on Jan. 1, 
2000, when computers that were programmed to recognize years by 
their last two digits could think it's 1900 and get confused. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Down in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices declined Tuesday due to  
profit-taking in reaction to Monday's advance. The Nikkei Stock 
Average fell 75.25 points to 16,03.40 in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. U.S. markets were closed Monday for Memorial Day. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres Win Eastern Conference Title  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Erik Rasmussen scored midway through the third  
period Monday night to snap a tie as the Buffalo Sabres rallied to 
beat Toronto 4-2 and capture the Eastern Conference final in five 
games. The goal came just over two minutes after the Sabres had a 
goal by Vaclav Varada disallowed and sent Buffalo to the Stanley 
Cup finals for only the second time since the team joined the NHL 
in 1970. The Sabres and their famed ``French Connection'' line of 
Gilbert Perreault, Rick Martin and Rene Robert were beaten 4-2 in 
the 1975 finals by the Philadelphia Flyers. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs Take 2-0 Lead  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Sean Elliott made six of seven 3-pointers,  
including the game-winner with nine seconds to play, as San Antonio 
came from 18 points down in the third quarter to beat the stunned 
Portland Trail Blazers 86-85 Monday. The Spurs' eighth consecutive 
playoff victory gives them a 2-0 lead in the Western Conference 
finals. The best-of-7 series resumes Friday at Portland's Rose 
Garden. Tim Duncan had 23 points, 10 rebounds and five blocked 
shots for the Spurs. Arvydas Sabonis led the Blazers with 17. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
