<DOCNO> APW19990531.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 06:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Vacation Spending Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Coleman Hart wanted to reward his wife for  
finishing school, so he planned a winter cruise in the Caribbean 
and expects to spend more on their vacation than usual. But he only 
plans to spend a week away from work. 
</P>
<P>
	Short vacations are the style for almost two-thirds of Americans  
these days, even though most people expect to spend as much or more 
money on vacations than they spent last year, an Associated Press 
poll found. 
</P>
<P>
	``I manage an office and it is difficult to take more than one  
week at a time,'' said Hart, a 51-year-old insurance adjuster from 
Cape Coral, Fla. ``I steal a day and make a long weekend to travel 
or get out on holiday weekends like Memorial Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart is not alone in preferring shorter vacations and in  
expecting to spend more money, said the poll, conducted for the AP 
by ICR of Media, Pa. The survey, taken May 21-25 among 1,008 
adults, carried a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	About six out of 10 interviewed said they expect to spend as  
much on getaways as they spent a year ago. And nearly one-fourth 
said they expect to spend more. 
</P>
<P>
	``We bought a house a couple of years ago,'' said Chris Hughes,  
a Bristol, Tenn., mother of four with another child on the way. 
``It seems like the finances are better for a trip this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She and her family plan a 10-day trip to Gatlinburg, a Smoky  
Mountain resort on the eastern tip of Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We like traveling by car,'' Ms. Hughes said. ``We have a van  
and it's comfortable for everybody. We like to see the 
countryside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strong economy was a big factor for Darroll Dawkins, a  
20-year-old college student from New York City, who plans to fly to 
Jamaica in late summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money isn't that much of a problem; it's been a good year with  
the economy,'' he said. ``Being able to save money made a lot of 
difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The typical American likes to go on vacation in the summer,  
travel by car and spend a week or less on their trip, according to 
the poll. Nearly two-thirds of participants said they expect their 
longest vacation this year to last a week or less. 
</P>
<P>
	About one-quarter said they would spend less than $500 on  
vacation and four out of 10 said they would spend between $500 and 
$1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Summer travelers will spend an average of $213 a day for a  
family of four, according to estimates from the AAA travel service, 
up $3 a day from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the poll:  
</P>
<P>
	--About half of those questioned said they prefer to travel in  
the summer, while almost one-fourth said fall and one out of six 
said spring. Winter was the choice of 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--A majority of adults between ages 18 and 55 prefer summer  
trips. For those from 55 to 64, fall was almost as popular as 
summer. For those 65 and older, spring and fall were more popular 
for vacations than summer. 
</P>
<P>
	--The percentage of people taking three-week vacations increases  
steadily as they get older. 
</P>
<P>
	--Driving, 55 percent, was the most popular mode of vacation  
travel, followed by flying at 30 percent, bus travel at 3 percent, 
cruises at 3 percent and train travel at 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Only those who made $50,000 or more preferred to fly as much as  
drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline prices have increased in recent months, but travel  
industry officials say they don't expect that to have an impact on 
the vacation season. 
</P>
<P>
	And they expect a very busy summer vacation season, because of  
the strong economy, low unemployment and consumer confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be a big year,'' said Jack Mannix, managing  
director of travel-related services for AAA. ``There's almost a 
sense of entitlement about vacations. They feel like it's a 
learning experience, time to be with family, time to rest and 
recharge batteries.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:37:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ballpark Dining Goes Upscale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Hot dogs and popcorn just won't cut the mustard  
anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	With baseball salaries soaring and teams looking to pack  
skyboxes with upscale fans, the ballpark menu is getting a new 
look. 
</P>
<P>
	Enter Larry Levy, a Chicago entrepreneur. Instead of ``Buy me  
some peanuts and Cracker Jack,'' he has fans humming a different 
tune. More like, ``Serve me some sushi and Chardonnay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Levy's company, Levy Restaurants Sports &AMP; Entertainment Group,  
provides food service to skyboxes and clubs for 26 major pro teams. 
And fans are eating it up -- generating revenues of $200 million for 
the company in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got into this because I love baseball,'' Levy said while  
overseeing his enterprise at Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago 
Cubs. ``But I'm so busy at the ballpark that I have no time to 
watch the game and have to wait until I get home and find out the 
score on ESPN.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Wrigley skyboxes, Levy provides ballpark staples such as  
wieners, but also such culinary treats as smokehouse barbecue pork. 
The Stadium Club provides more gourmet cuisine, like salmon 
souffle. 
</P>
<P>
	Levy also plays on regional favorites, offering sushi in  
California stadiums and Southern cooking at Nashville Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Even restaurant critics are starting to take notice of Levy's  
company, which got its start 20 years ago with a deli. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very good for what it is -- ballpark food. People don't  
expect gourmet food there,'' says Don Rose, a Chicago restaurant 
critic who has tasted Levy's skybox cuisine. ``The Levys have been 
able to take their know-how in the restaurant business and applied 
that at the ballpark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brothers Larry and Mark Levy -- who now own 21 restaurants  
nationwide -- started out with a delicatessen in 1978. They didn't 
do well at first and their mother, Eadie, had to rescue them with 
recipes from her kitchen. 
</P>
<P>
	Her reward? Her own place. She still greets customers at Mrs.  
Levy's Delicatessen in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Levys got into the stadium food business when Chicago White  
Sox owner Jerry Reinsdorf needed someone to cater his new skyboxes 
at Comiskey Park in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	``He promised us some playoff tickets if we did him the favor,''  
Larry Levy remembers. 
</P>
<P>
	Levy expanded to crosstown Wrigley Field, then to Cleveland's  
Jacobs Field. Now, Levy-fed stadiums are spread from the MCI Center 
outside Washington and Pro Player Stadium in Miami to Portland's 
Rose Garden and the Oakland Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Levy has about one-fourth of the major pro sports market.  
He also caters rock concerts and even provided food for Pope John 
Paul II's visit to St. Louis in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've learned from our experience in the restaurant business,  
you never say 'no' to a customer,'' Levy says. ``We try to fill all 
kinds of special diet requests -- vegetarian, skinless chicken -- you 
name it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gene Guidici, a 36-year-old trader at the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, says the clients he brings to his skybox at Wrigley are 
thrilled with the food. 
</P>
<P>
	``The food always gets compliments; there's never any  
complaints,'' Guidici says. ``They go out of their way to make sure 
everything is perfect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even after a Cubs game was called off one recent rainy  
afternoon, some skybox fans stayed to party for about an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a complete wipeout for us. We made some money on  
early food sales,'' said Brett Bils, Levy's manager at Wrigley. 
``The leftover food goes to a shelter for battered women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just then, the dessert cart rolls by.  
</P>
<P>
	``Snickers pie, cheesecakes, giant taffy apples, gourmet ice  
cream bars, white chocolate pecan turtles, All-American apple pie. 
I promise, everything is fat-free,'' says Toni Parker, operator of 
the Levy dessert wagon, aptly decorated with replicas of Wrigley's 
signature ivy and brick. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the desserts are what they remember when they leave  
the ballpark,'' Bils says. ``We hope they remember the good food 
and good time they had here and want to come back for more someday 
soon.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
