<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Completes Indy, Coca-Cola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- As Tony Stewart flew over the speedway, one  
race down, the second just about to start, he looked down at the 
crowd that was cheering and waving at him, and shook his head. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is awesome,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Yes, his double-duty day was quite a trip.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart became the first driver to complete both the  
Indianapolis 500 and the Coca-Cola 600 in the same day Sunday, 
racing 1,090 miles in about 10 hours. He went from last to fourth 
with a hard-charging drive in the Coca-Cola after finishing ninth 
at Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	And when the day was finally done, he collapsed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Eventful. Definitely eventful,'' a weary-looking Stewart said  
after the race. ``I'm ready for a nap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or hibernation, perhaps. Stewart, who ate barely anything all  
day Sunday, was sick for the last hour of the Coca-Cola. When he 
climbed out of his car, his legs gave out and he sank to the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
	He sat next to his car for several minutes with a wet towel  
wrapped around his head, occasionally drinking fluids. He got 
oxygen, and then was put on a stretcher and taken to the track 
hospital where he was given fluids and released. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never use the head rest in cars and I used the head rest the  
last 60-70 laps,'' he said. ``I felt like I was about 90 percent 
and leaving 10 percent on the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not good enough for NASCAR's hottest rookie, who said he  
doubts he'll try the double again next year. Stewart, who switched 
to NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit after three years in the Indy 
Racing League, had said all along the Coca-Cola was his priority. 
But Indy is still special to Stewart, who grew up 45 miles away in 
Columbus, Ind., and he wanted a chance to win it. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if it meant running his body into the ground for a day.  
</P>
<P>
	John Andretti is the only other driver to race in Indy and the  
Coca-Cola on the same day, but he crashed in 1994 and didn't finish 
the 600. Robby Gordon's bid to do the double in 1997 was rained out 
in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been experience I'll never forget. ... I wouldn't  
trade it for anything,'' Stewart said. ``As much fun as I had 
today, it wasn't fair to these guys to give them 90 percent for the 
last few laps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was fun while it lasted, though. When he got out of his car  
at Indy, four laps behind winner Kenny Brack, raising his index 
finger to tell fans, ``One more.'' He hurried to his trailer, 
changed into jeans and a red T-shirt and made a brief stop at his 
garage to thank his crew and say goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart was running strong early, but his car developed handling  
problems and a mistake in the pits didn't help. While working on 
the Dallara Oldsmobile Aurora, the crew released the jack too soon 
and slightly damaged the car. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it was off to a helicopter waiting in the infield near the  
third turn. He flew to the Indianapolis airport, where The Home 
Depot, his sponsor, had its private jet waiting for the 65-minute 
flight to North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``In all honesty, I'm not as disappointed as I thought I'd be,''  
Stewart said on the flight to North Carolina. ``Obviously, I wanted 
to win the race and anything short is a disappointment. But we did 
everything we could. We fought hard all day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once he was on the plane, Stewart changed into his NASCAR racing  
suit, ate a Power Bar and guzzled some Powerade and water. Though 
he'd only had a couple of mini-bagels before Indy, he wasn't hungry 
and didn't eat anything else -- a move that might have cost him 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	``I should have planned that better,'' he said at the end of the  
night. ``We were so concerned about keeping fluids in me we didn't 
think about getting food in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did get in a nap, though, stretching out on the couch in the  
back of the plane for most of the flight. By the time the jet 
landed, Stewart was awake and ready to go again. After another 
helicopter ride -- this time on fellow NASCAR driver Rusty Wallace's 
helicopter -- he arrived at Lowe's Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd let out a huge roar when the helicopter landed about a  
half-hour before the race began, and he got into a white Camaro and 
was driven around the track for driver introductions. 
</P>
<P>
	He was supposed to start 27th, but he was banished to the last  
and 43rd spot because he missed the drivers' meeting. He worked his 
way up quickly, weaving through the field until he took the lead on 
lap 268. For the rest of the race, he battled Jeff Burton and 
teammate Bobby Labonte for the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's someone we're going to have to deal with next week and  
next year and well into the future,'' Burton said. ``It wouldn't 
surprise me if he won some races this year -- not just a race, but 
some races.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 23:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capel, Miller Developing Rivalry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Sprinters John Capel of Florida and Coby  
Miller of Auburn have stirred up a rivalry that will reach its peak 
in the NCAA Championships beginning Wednesday at Boise State. 
</P>
<P>
	Capel is fanning the flames of the confrontation, Miller is  
downplaying it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question is who's going to win this time and who's going  
to lose?'' Capel said. ``And who's going to get raked over in the 
newspapers? 
</P>
<P>
	``Coby said he had no competition because he was dominating the  
sprints. I don't see that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In truth, Miller was dominating the collegiate sprints until  
Capel beat him in the 200 meters at the Southeastern Conference 
Championships in 19.99 seconds. That was the first sub-20 second 
clocking by a collegian in 11 years, only the fourth ever, the 
first by a freshman, and made Capel the fastest American in the 200 
this year. Not even Michael Johnson, the world record-holder, nor 
Maurice Greene, ranked No. 3 in the world, ran faster in college. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, only Frank Fredericks of Namibia, ranked No. 2 in the  
world, has run faster than Capel in 1999, with times of 19.87 and 
19.92. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Miller won't concede anything to Capel.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great competitor,'' the Tigers' junior said. ``I never  
underestimate anyone. He had a little more left at the end than I 
did. He beat me over the last 10 meters. He got me on form. I got 
out of my form. This time, I'm going to be ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're friends. We talk. We congratulate each other. There's no  
sense holding grudges against each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see a rivalry. It depends on whose on top of his game  
that day. If you're on top of your game, you should be successful. 
Most look at me as the favorite. It's a great honor to have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Capel ran his sizzling 19.99, Miller was runner-up at  
20.09, his career best. 
</P>
<P>
	While Capel got his victory over Miller in the 200, his first  
during the outdoor season, Miller beat Capel in the 100 -- 10.10 to 
10.12. 
</P>
<P>
	In that instance, Capel felt he should have won.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had the race won,'' he said, ``but I leaned at the wrong  
line. The lines were messed up, so I leaned too soon. Coby kept 
running. I was leading with about 5 to 8 meters left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the fierceness of their competition, the two have mutual  
respect. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I line up against him, I race my hardest because the  
first person that gets lazy is going to lose, or whoever makes the 
first mistake is going to lose,'' Capel said. ``I hate losing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Losing makes me train harder. I'm training harder than ever.  
It's paying off, but coach (sprint coach Mike Holloway) says I can 
improve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller also has trained hard this season, losing about 10 pounds  
to his present weight of 188. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a perfect weight,'' he said. ``I run with a lot of  
power. I carry weight well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The weight loss, plus the tutoring and counseling of Auburn  
coach Ralph Spry, a former world-class long jumper, helped Miller 
win the NCAA indoor title at 200 meters and set school records 
outdoors in the 100 and 200. His best outdoor time is 10.03, 
third-fastest in the world, and better than 1976 Olympian Harvey 
Glance's 22-year-old Auburn record of 10.04, and he has twice 
broken Daron Council's 1985 school record 200-meter time of 20.29. 
</P>
<P>
	A change in attitude also has been beneficial to Miller, who is  
in his first season at Auburn after spending one year at East 
Central Community College in Decatur, Miss., and one year at 
Meridian (Miss.) Community College, where he won the National 
Junior College indoor 55-meter championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``This season I have changed from a negative attitude to a  
positive attitude,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also has given up football in which he was a high school star  
in Louisville, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Capel also was an outstanding scholastic football player in  
Brooksville, Fla., and still is playing. He was a return specialist 
for the Gators last season, averaging 30 yards per return. 
</P>
<P>
	In the NCAA championships, the two sprinters will meet in the  
100 and 200, while Capel will run on Florida's 400-meter relay 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Capel will have help from teammate Bobby Williams, who also is  
in the 100 and 200. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll try to gang up on Coby,'' Capel said. ``We're all going  
after Coby.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990531.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 06:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man-Made Lakes Eyed for Recreation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's 1,782 man-made federal lakes,  
created to boost power, grow crops and control floods, have great 
untapped potential for fishing, boating and other recreation, a 
presidential commission has concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress and federal agencies, however, pay little attention to  
recreation and provide insufficient funds to maintain facilities 
now deteriorating, the National Recreation Lakes Study Commission 
said in a study coming out Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lake managers often make recreation their lowest priority  
because of laws, agency policies and a ``corporate culture'' that 
values traditional uses of reservoirs such as navigation and 
irrigation, commission members said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a lot of cases, it appears (recreation) is being ignored,''  
said Richard Davies, commission vice chairman and director of the 
Arkansas Department of Parks &AMP; Tourism. 
</P>
<P>
	But as the population rises and outdoor amusement becomes more  
popular, the lakes' potential for holiday recreational activities 
has become as important as the traditional uses, the commission 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're great national treasures,'' said Tom Strickland, U.S.  
attorney for Colorado and a commission member. ``They generate 
enormous social benefits in terms of recreation and just play 
opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lakes, found in 47 states, resulted from massive public  
works projects primarily from the 1950s through the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Many were built with adjacent campgrounds and beaches, but the  
commission found that restrooms, boat docks and roads are falling 
apart, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many lakes are polluted, and sport fishing suffers because fish  
are dying. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal recreation funding for lakes has been shrinking, from  
$889 million in 1994 to $839 million in 1998 for the seven largest 
agencies that manage them. 
</P>
<P>
	In turn, dwindling funds have contributed to a maintenance  
backlog of more than $800 million at the lakes, the report found. 
</P>
<P>
	Even where lakes have active tourism, managers face difficult  
tasks in balancing recreation and other lake uses. 
</P>
<P>
	At Lake Mead near Las Vegas, the largest reservoir in North  
America at 180,000 acres, water levels can fluctuate by as much as 
50 feet depending on water demand, snow levels and diversions for 
flood-control storage. 
</P>
<P>
	That means boat docks have to be moved in and out and rest rooms  
can wind up under water. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a balancing act,'' said Kent Turner, chief of resources  
for the National Park Service there. ``There's a lot of planning 
that has to revolve around the water level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are so few boat launches at Lake Mead and other lakes that  
many visitors must show up early and wait in long lines if they 
hope to get their boats in the water, said Ryck Lydecker of the 
Boat Owners Association of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not the way to run a lake,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The commission, authorized by Congress in 1996 to assess lake  
recreation and look for ways to improve it, made 16 recommendations 
to address the problems, including: 
</P>
<P>
	--Federal agencies should make recreation a higher priority, with  
appropriate funding and attention. 
</P>
<P>
	--Congress should authorize a permanent fee structure at the  
lakes and allow more agencies to collect fees. 
</P>
<P>
	--Federal agencies get more flexibility to address recreational  
needs. For instance, the Bureau of Reclamation and the Army Corps 
of Engineers should be able to build recreational facilities 
without finding a state or local partner, as current law requires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
