<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Prep Star Could Be Top Baseball Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Josh Hamilton may have an easier time  
playing professional baseball than finding cleats to fit his 
18 1/2-inch feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton's huge feet haven't slowed his progress toward the top  
of the major league baseball draft list. The Raleigh Athens Drive 
prep star may be the No. 1 overall pick by the Tampa Bay Devil Rays 
on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a problem. I guess I've grown up with them,''  
Hamilton said of his rather large feet. ``My shoe size stayed the 
same as my age up until I was 14, and then it took off. When I as 
14 I was wearing a size 16.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4, 200-pound outfielder-pitcher has a good chance to  
be the first high school player chosen No. 1 in the draft since 
Seattle selected a prep shortstop by the name of Alex Rodriguez in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Jennings, director of scouting for Tampa Bay, spent hours in  
meetings over the weekend with scouts who have watched Hamilton's 
every move for the past six months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen him pitch up to 96 mph, I've seen him hit homers and  
I've seen him hit an inside-the-park homer,'' Jennings said. ``He 
shows you what you want to see in a major league prospect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-year-old left-hander hit .514 with 13 home runs in high  
school this past season, when teams chose to pitch to him instead 
of around him. Last week in an American Legion game, Hamilton was 
intentionally walked three times. When he finally got a chance to 
hit, be hit a homer. Then, after the game, he signed balls for 
players on the other team. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton shrugs off all the attention he has received, calling  
it fun but hectic. 
</P>
<P>
	During one high school game for Athens, 55 scouts attended to  
watch him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Josh has been under such a microscope,'' said his father, Tony  
Hamilton. ``Tampa had people at 20 of the 25 games he played. And 
not just one, but two, three and four people. Everything he does, 
how he walks, talks, acts, they are taking notes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's how teams act when they're preparing to make a $3 million  
or $4 million investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton's life has been consumed by baseball since he was 7,  
when he moved up to Little League two years ahead of his schedule 
and was coached by his father. 
</P>
<P>
	``He threw the ball and hit the ball too hard for the kids his  
age,'' Tony Hamilton said. ``He played center field in Little 
League and he always stayed mad because he batted ninth. He said, 
`Why am I batting ninth? I can hit.' I told him he was the youngest 
and the smallest so he was going to hit ninth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton is no longer the smallest, but some say simply the best  
prep prospect to come along in quite awhile. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would never put a `can't miss' label on any player, there  
are risk factors,'' Jennings said. ``It is unfair to the player, 
but he has tremendous God-given ability. The thing I like most 
about him is Josh Hamilton likes to play the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton is already preparing for his foray on pro ball by  
taking half his batting practice with a wooden bat. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got pop. Wood or aluminum -- he could hit with a telephone  
pole,'' said Royals scout Paul Faulk. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton's character also impresses scouts, who call him a  
`throw-back' type of athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew he was going to be something special because of the way  
he goes about his game. He's serious business,'' Faulk said. ``He 
goes about the game the way you should -- 100 percent. If you talk 
to the kid for five minutes, you know he's a good kid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How good? Hamilton had several invites to attend his recent high  
school prom, but turned them down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided it was best I didn't go,'' he said. ``I am trying to  
stay away from crowds and different groups. If something bad 
happened at the wrong time, I didn't want to be in that 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton is quite aware of his future, and where he would like  
to end up -- in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not really nervous about the draft, but (I'm) anxious to  
see what is going to happen, who I am going to go with,'' he said. 
``I guess I am ready to get started. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was in first grade, we had to write a story about what  
you wanted to be when you grew up and I wrote that I want to be a 
professional baseball player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton begins living his dream Wednesday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
