<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Recession Widens Japan Social Gaps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese have long taken pride in their success at  
building a modern economy free of the gaps between rich and poor 
that plague other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	But while many here still see their country as one big, happy  
middle-class family, a few are raising cries of alarm that Japan's 
vaunted social equality may be disappearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The evidence is in figures showing that a long recession and  
efforts to open the economy to competition are broadening the gap 
between haves and have-nots at an alarming pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``Very few countries have seen inequality rise so sharply in  
such a short period,'' said Toshiaki Tachibanaki, an economist at 
Kyoto University, one of the most prestigious in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, Japan still receives praise for its ability  
to spread the fruits of affluence throughout its population. Social 
equality is widely seen behind Japan's enviably low rates of crime 
and school drop outs. 
</P>
<P>
	It has also played an important role in Japan's social contract.  
Consumers have put up with high prices and inefficiency in exchange 
for the peace of mind of knowing they would have no problem keeping 
up with the average income. 
</P>
<P>
	But economic statistics are starting to show a troubling trend.  
</P>
<P>
	The most common way to measure how evenly a country's incomes  
are distributed is a mathematical tool called the gini coefficient, 
which rates a country on a scale of 0 to 1. The closer to 1, the 
less equal. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, Japan's gini coefficient had been stuck at a very low  
level: about 0.3 as measured by the Health and Welfare Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	But since the 1980s, the figure has soared. In 1993, the most  
recent year for which figures are available, the coefficient stood 
at 0.44, almost exactly the same as the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers like Tachibanaki, who has waged a long, often lonely  
campaign to draw attention to the trend, say the number has 
probably risen even further in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, by most standards Japan remains more equitable by a  
long shot than the United States. Poverty levels in Japan are less 
than half the U.S. figure of 16 percent, and corporate executives 
make only a few times more than their average employee, compared 
with 10s or 100s more in American companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the recent gini coefficients do place Japan among the less  
equitable countries in Europe, like England, and far behind 
countries with strong welfare systems such as Sweden and Denmark. 
</P>
<P>
	``The myth that we were different has been shattered,'' lamented  
an article on the trend in the influential Asahi newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the factors contributing to the growing gap has been a  
government campaign to end Japan's nine-year economic slump by 
lifting restrictions on competition. 
</P>
<P>
	That has forced companies to scrap the old egalitarian lifetime  
employment system, with its age-based wage scales, in favor of 
rewarding productive workers with higher salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The ranks of those earning little or no income have also swelled  
as the economy's slide into recession has increased bankruptcies 
and corporate job-cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	Other factors are less obvious.  
</P>
<P>
	One is the growing number of women in the work force, as social  
mores relax and families seek second incomes. They show up in 
government statistics as a surge in low-income workers because they 
get paid so much less than Japanese men -- about half, according to 
recent studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there were the soaring land prices in the 1980s, which  
still help split the country into haves and have-nots. 
</P>
<P>
	When prices took off, those lucky enough to own land, usually  
through inheritance, had the chance to become instant millionaires. 
The rest have seen the dream of home ownership slip beyond their 
reach -- and bigger chunks of their salary into their landlord's 
pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	A return to equality seems highly unlikely. Tokyo appears  
committed to free-market reforms. In fact, wage gaps could widen 
further as the government trims the top income tax rates in a 
Reaganomics-inspired effort to boost investment and consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	But then again, inequality may be Japan's normal state, said  
Tachibanaki. The country saw large gaps between rich and poor for 
most of its history. Equality of incomes was only achieved in the 
years after World War II, after Japan's defeat leveled social 
differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at the last century, the relative equality of  
1950s and 1960s appears as an anomaly,'' Tachibanaki said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
