<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Open Treats Older Women Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- While a new generation of women dominate the  
headlines, look who's winning at the French Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindsay Davenport, Steffi Graf, Conchita Martinez, Arantxa  
Sanchez-Vicario and Monica Seles all have made their way to the 
quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, much of the heralded new generation -- the Williams  
sisters, Anna Kournikova and Amelie Mauresmo -- are out after a 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Seles, who made her Roland Garros debut in 1989, plays Spain's  
Martinez, making her 12th appearance in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf, in the final eight for the 13th consecutive year, plays  
Davenport, in the French Open for the seventh time. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez-Vicario, the defending champion, is making her 13th  
appearance at Roland Garros. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf, who'll be 30 in June, is the elder stateswoman of the  
women's tour. 
</P>
<P>
	She's a fan of the younger generation but showed that she isn't  
ready to step aside on Sunday by beating 17-year-old Kournikova 
6-3, 7-6 (7-4) on center court. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's game, Graf says, can only benefit from the publicity  
attracted by the new generation of players. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sport is gaining public attention, and the way players  
present themselves is more outspoken with a lot more confidence,'' 
she says. ``That is very positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Graf doesn't believe experienced players are any worse off  
as a result. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that we have been written off,'' Graf said. ``We  
have been around so long that I guess the stories about us get a 
little boring at some point. It is more fun if you hear something 
about the younger players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And she said competing against younger players doesn't present  
any new challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel I need to prove anything to anybody. I go out to  
play tennis against somebody whether they are older or younger. It 
doesn't matter,'' Graf said. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf said the level of competition is much higher than when she  
ruled the women's game by winning 21 Grand Slam titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's much tougher on the tour earlier on in tournaments these  
days. The field has gotten much closer,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Graf worries there might be an overemphasis among younger  
players on powerful physiques. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is surprising to me is that girls of 12 or 14 years old  
already have bodies that don't look that age. They already have 
well-developed muscles,'' she said. ``They seem very strong, very 
early on. 
</P>
<P>
	``Players used to be a lot skinner, tinier,'' she added. ``If  
you see some of the juniors now, the way they are built, it is 
clear that they are playing hours and hours a day. Their bodies 
might not last as long as they used to.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
